<FIRST>r a AM-TimesSued     01-13 0265</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Times Sued,0271</SECOND>
<HEAD>NAACP Drops Out of NY Times Suit</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The NAACP said Friday it had pulled out of a suit
against The New York Times that charged the newspaper's real estate
advertisements promote racial discrimination by featuring white
models.
   Director Dr. Benjamin Hooks said the NAACP ``suspended its
participation'' because the organization had not held direct
negotiations with the Times prior to filing the suit, contrary to
longstanding policy.
   The suit was filed Thursday in U.S. Disrict Court by the New York
Open Housing Center and four individuals, along with the National
Association for the Advancement of Colored People.
   ``While other members of the coalition met with representatives
of the Times, the NAACP was not represented and hence the Times'
publisher, Arthur Ochs Sulzberger, was correct when he complained
that the lawsuit was filed without any discussion with the NAACP,''
Hooks said in a news release.
   Hooks said the failure to hold direct talks occurred ``through an
adminstrative oversight.'' Hooks said the suit had not been dropped
and a meeting with Times officials would be sought.
   ``We regret any confusion that might have arisen over this matter
and have taken steps internally to see that such an oversight does
not occur again,'' Hooks said.
   On Thursday, the Times issued a statement maintaining that its
advertising conforms with anti-discrimination laws and saying the
complaint appeared at first reading to be ``without merit.''
   The plaintiffs said photos and drawings that accompany real
estate ads in the Times ``depict whites almost exclusively as
potential residents, thus indicating a preference based on race.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
