<FIRST>r a PM-Goetz-Chronology     01-13 0369</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Goetz-Chronology,0390</SECOND>
<HEAD>A Chronology Of The Goetz Case</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Also in the Saturday AMs report.</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Goetz Sentencing, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Here is a chronology of events in the Bernhard
Goetz case:
</TEXT>
<NOTE>1984</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   DEC. 22 _ Gunman shoots four young black men on subway train and
escapes.
   DEC. 31 _ Bernhard Hugo Goetz, 37, of Manhattan, surrenders to
state police in Concord, N.H.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>1985</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   JAN. 3 _ Goetz returns to New York and is arraigned on charges of
attempted murder and illegal weapons possession.
   JAN. 25 _ Grand jury indicts Goetz for illegal weapons
possession, rejecting charges of attempted murder.
   MARCH 27 _ Second grand jury hears new witnesses, including two
of those wounded who had refused to testify to previous grand jury
without grants of immunity. Goetz indicted on four counts of
attempted murder, one count of reckless endangerment, four counts of
assault and illegal weapons charges.
   JAN. 16 _ Acting state Supreme Court Justice Stephen Crane drops
attempted murder charges because he says grand jury was not properly
instructed on laws of justification.
   JULY 8 _ The state's highest court, the Court of Appeals,
reinstates attempted murder charges.
   DEC. 12 _ Jury selection begins.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>1987</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   APRIL 7 _ Jury selection completed, with half of those seated
crime victims.
   APRIL 27 _ Trial opens with prosecutor calling Goetz ``vicious,
even sadistic'' in shooting the young men, while defense claims
Goetz ``gave the victims _ thugs _ what the law allows.''
   JUNE 16 _ Jury acquits Goetz of attempted murder but convicts him
on one count of illegal gun possession.
   OCT. 19 _ Goetz sentenced to six months in prison and five years'
probation.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>1988</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   JUNE 29 _ Appellate Division rules that six-month sentence for
weapon possession is illegal because law mandates either one-year
term or indeterminate sentence. Because of legal peculiarity, Goetz
would be eligible for release after serving two months of one-year
term, but must complete four months of six-month term.
   NOV. 22 _ State Court of Appeals upholds Goetz's conviction for
gun possession and agrees that six-month sentence was wrong.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>1989</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   JAN. 13 _ Goetz resentenced to one year in jail and fined $5,000.
He will be eligible for parole in 51 days.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
