<FILEID>AP-NR-01-13-89 0059EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-ScienceFront     01-13 0699</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Science Front,0722</SECOND>
<HEAD>On the Science Front</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Similar version in Friday AMs report.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Among developments on the science front:
</TEXT>
<NOTE>MEDICINE-BLACKS</NOTE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   New research indicates blacks have less access to
medical care than whites.
   According to a 1986 nationwide telephone survey, one in 11 blacks
reported not seeing a doctor for economic reasons, compared with one
in 20 whites. And blacks who did go to a doctor may not have been
treated as well as whites, the study said.
   The report, which appears in today's Journal of the American
Medical Association, also said blacks were less likely to have
health insurance.
   Another study in the Journal reviewed 50 medical studies of
trials of new drugs published from 1984-1986 and found that blacks
were included in less than two-thirds of them.
   A third study looked at racial inequities in use of medical
procedures for heart-disease patients in Massachusetts, and found
that whites were 1.38 times more likely to undergo angiography, a
technique for taking X-rays of the heart, and 2.26 times more likely
to undergo bypass operations.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>OSTEOPOROSIS</NOTE>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Scientists say a new treatment for osteoporosis has
proved successful in reversing the bone loss that afflicts an
estimated 5 million Americans.
   A five-year clinical test reveals that use of a new slow-release
form of sodium fluoride _ long used by dentists to strengthen teeth
_ when given with calcium citrate can reverse the effects of
osteoporosis by increasing bone mass, researchers at the University
of Texas Southwestern Medical Center reported Thursday.
   Spinal osteoporosis, a gradual loss of a kind of bone found
primarily in the spine, commonly affects elderly, postmenopausal
women and results in shortened stature, curvature of the back and a
protruding abdomen that can cause back pain and discomfort in the
digestive system.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>ULCERS</NOTE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A new ulcer drug that is still being tested is
superior to one of the mainstays of ulcer treatment because it
promotes healing and relieves symptoms more quickly, according to a
new study.
   The study found the new drug, known as omeprazole, worked better
in patients with stomach ulcers than Zantac, one of two widely used
treatments for ulcers. Both work by blocking the body's secretion of
hydrochloric acid.
   After one month of treatment, ulcers had healed in 80 percent of
those getting omeprazole and 59 percent receiving Zantac. After two
months, 96 percent of the omeprazole patients and 85 percent of the
Zantac patients had healed.
   The results were published in Thursday's issue of the New England
Journal of Medicine.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>MEASLES</NOTE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. Centers for Disease Control recommends
two significant changes in the routine for measles vaccinations.
   _ Infants under 15 months old, in areas where recurrent measles
is a problem, should get two measles shots instead of one _ a shot
of measles vaccine alone at 9 months, and a second dose at 15 months
of the commonly used measless-mumps-rubella vaccine.
   _ In schools with measles outbreaks _ and in nearby schools where
the disease might spread _ all students whose measles shots came
before 1980 should be re-vaccinated, along with their siblings.
   Measles specialists have discovered two major outbreak patterns
in recent years: outbreaks among infants under the 15-month
vaccination age and outbreaks among school-age children who have
been vaccinated but still got measles anyway. As much as 10 percent
of all vaccinations don't provide the intended protection.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>HERPES</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Studies show that acyclovir, an antiviral drug,
can reduce or eliminate recurrent outbreaks of genital herpes even
when taken for more than a year, a researcher reported.
   Dr. David Baker, a specialist in obstetrics and gynecology, said
Thursday that a study involving 261 patients with active herpes
infections showed that outbreaks of the disease were virtually
eliminated for about half of those taking acyclovir twice daily. The
others who took the drug experienced milder, shorter outbreaks.
   Although earlier studies showed that acyclovir was effective
temporarily against herpes, Baker said the trial was the first to
demonstrate that the antiviral drug is effective over many months.
   A report on the study was published this month in the journal
Obstetrics and Gynecology.
</TEXT>
