<FIRST>r a AM-BelgianSoldier     01-13 0284</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Belgian Soldier,0291</SECOND>
<HEAD>Belgian Soldier Tells Police Killings Were Acts Of Revenge</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FORT LAUDERDALE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Belgian soldier assigned to his
country's Washington embassy surrendered to police Thursday, saying
he had killed two people here as revenge after breaking up with his
male lover, authorities said.
   Rudy Van Den Borre, 25, surrendered after making several calls to
police, challenging them to ``come and find me.'' He was booked into
Broward County Jail without bond on two counts of first-degree
murder.
   He told the officer who arrested him early Thursday that he'd
killed two people and was planning another murder as revenge against
the lover he'd just broken up with, the Broward County Sheriff's
office said in a statement.
   ``He had a lover's quarrel with his boyfriend up (in) the
Washington area,'' sheriff's Sgt. Tom Carney told reporters. ``He
came down here, he was emotionally upset about that.''
   Police statements said Van Den Borre arrived in south Florida
Jan. 4 and wandered around the Fort Lauderdale beach area visiting
gay hangouts.
   ``And he meets these people at local clubs, goes down on the
beach with them and at some point decides that he's going to shoot
and kill them,'' Carney said.
   Michael Egan, a 36-year-old airline reservation clerk from Fort
Lauderdale, was found shot in the head Jan. 8. Less than 24 hours
later, the body of Hollywood cab driver Gerald Simons, 52, was
found, similarly killed.
   Fort Lauderdale police said both victims were homosexuals.
   Because Van Den Borre is a diplomatic employee, there is some
question about his status before the law. Officials said the Belgian
Embassy had been told of the charges against him and was cooperating
in the investigation.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
