<FIRST>r a PM-Grammy-Chapman     01-13 0589</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Grammy-Chapman,0614</SECOND>
<HEAD>Recording Industry's Newest Star Revives Singer-Songwriter Tradition</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Also in Friday AMs report.</HEAD>
<HEAD>^With PM-Grammys, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DOLORES BARCLAY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Arts Editor</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Tracy Chapman seems of another time, a time when
Dylan, Odetta, Seeger and Guthrie celebrated freedom and the spirit
of man, and defied brutality and repression with their songs and
anthems.
   Chapman, whose self-titled debut album has been nominated for six
Grammys, is of this age and her songs take a hard, cold look at
poverty, racism, inequality and human relations. She is
uncompromising, tough and compassionate.
   ``I think people look at the world in many different ways and
choose to see what they like,'' she said in an interview last year
with The Washington Post. ``I think lots of people ignore some of
the harder issues, the more unpleasant things. I don't think I harp
on them.''
   Her LP opens with ``Talkin' Bout a Revolution,'' a song that
tells of ``standing in the welfare lines
   Crying at the doorsteps of those armies of salvation
   Wasting time in the unemployment lines
   Sitting around waiting for a promotion
   Poor people gonna rise up
   And get their share
   Poor people gonna rise up
   And take what's theirs.''
   Until ``Tracy Chapman'' hit record stores last April, the
24-year-old poet-singer-songwriter-folksinger was one of the Boston
area's best kept secrets. As an anthrolopolgy major at Tufts
University in Medford, Mass., she performed in coffee houses and
clubs, and was a local hit.
   The LP, with its range from folk to pop ballad to reggae,
enchanted millions more. It has sold over 4 million copies and has
been nominated for album of the year and best contemporary folk
recording. The single, ``Fast Car,'' has been nominated for best
song and record of the year, and Chapman herself is up for best new
artist and best female pop vocalist.
   ``Fast Car'' was a No. 1 hit and tells of a high school dropout
who works to supports her alcoholic father and who wants to escape
it all with her unemployed boyfriend:
   ``You got a fast car
   And I got a plan to get us out of here
   I been working at the convenience store
   Managed to save just a little bit of money
   We won't have to drive too far
   Just 'cross the border and into the city
   You and I can both get jobs
   And finally see what it means to be living.''
   Chapman's rich contralto with its melancholic underpinnings is an
instrument by itself and highly effective on ``Behind the Wall,'' a
song about a battered woman. She sings a capella of the harsh
realties of the domestic fight: ``Last night I heard the screaming -
Then a silence that chilled my soul'' _ and slams the police for
doing nothing.
   She grew up in Cleveland and has been singing since she was a
child. She was in a Connecticut boarding school when
singer-songwriters had been put out to pasture by synthesizer
philistines. Chapman didn't turn on her radio, but many of her
classmates listened to folk music and played guitar.
   In college, one of her classmates was Brian Koppelman, whose
father, Charles, is a leader in the music publishing business. This
gave her the wedge she needed to gain entry to the recording world.
   Chapman, whose musical roots can be traced to Joan Armatrading,
Carol King and Joni Mitchell, was part of a new wave of
singer-songwriters in the late 1980s, especially women such as Toni
Childs, Marti Jones, Melissa Etheridge and Michelle Shocked.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
