<FIRST>r w PM-FinalPush     01-13 0622</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Final Push,620</SECOND>
<HEAD>WASHINGTON TODAY: US Scores Last-Minute Successes</HEAD>
<BYLINE>An AP News Analysis</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>By BARRY SCHWEID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Diplomatic Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   With only a week to go, the Reagan
administration is managing to eke out a few foreign policy successes
before turning leadership in world affairs over to President-elect
Bush and his deputies.
   The withdrawal of 450 Cuban soldiers from Angola this week marks
the beginning of the end of a 14-year presence in the Southwest
Africa country. The pullout is part of a deal arranged by the United
States that will bring independence to Namibia, now under South
African control.
   Chester A. Crocker, the assistant secretary of state for African
affairs, worked eight difficult years for a settlement, continuing
efforts that began early in the Carter administration.
   The Cuban exodus does not end the war in Angola. The Marxist
government, armed by the Soviet Union, is still fighting the rebel
Union for the Total Independence of Angola, or UNITA, which has been
supported by South Africa and the United States.
   But the war is likely to be less intense, and Namibia will get
the independence South Africa was unwilling to grant despite
worldwide condemnation.
   In Afghanistan, the Soviets have again started to withdraw their
troops despite threats to stall until a political settlement is
worked out with U.S.-armed rebels.
   Transports carried some units out by air this week, while others
streamed northward from the Soviet garrison in the capital city of
Kabul. By Feb. 15, the last of the 50,000 Soviet troops are supposed
to be gone.
   Here, too, the departure of a foreign army does not mean peace is
settling in. But the fighting may slacken.
   Rebels armed by the United States and Pakistan have government
forces on the run. Without Soviet backing, however, President
Najibullah and his army could collapse without much of a struggle.
   Soviet troops have been in the country since December 1979. Their
ouster was a main foreign policy goal of the Carter and then the
Reagan administration.
   Success came partly as a result of massive Soviet losses and the
kind of anguish at home that Americans suffered during the Vietnam
war. But the advent of Mikhail S. Gorbachev in April 1985 and the
smoother relationship he worked out with President Reagan had a lot
to do with it.
   Superpower cooperation also helped bring about the African
settlement and the ongoing Vietnamese troop withdrawal from
Cambodia, although it did not crack the Arab-Israeli conflict or
have an impact on the wars in Nicaragua and El Salvador.
   In the meantime, the outgoing administration is defying tradition
by not just fading away.
   Secretary of State George Shultz has purchased his tickets for
flying home to California right after the inaugural next Friday. But
a U.S. Air Force jet is waiting for him to board at Andrews Air
Force Base this weekend.
   The idea is to fly to Vienna and celebrate the end of a 27-month
human rights conference, hold a 32nd and final meeting with Soviet
Foreign Minister Eduard A. Shevardnadze and make preparations for
East-West arms control talks.
   Those negotiations will seek the reduction of troops all across
the European landscape. The idea is to ease tensions between the
North Atlantic Treaty Organization and the Warsaw Pact.
   To get those talks going, the Soviets met U.S. demands for the
release of more than 600 political prisoners, the reunification of
more than 100 families and stepped-up emigration of Jews, ethnic
Germans and Armenians.
   The Shultz trip is on hold, though, pending resolution of a
dispute between Greece and Turkey over how much Turkish territory
across from Cyprus will be included in the reduction talks.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Barry Schweid heads the AP's State Department
staff.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
