<FIRST>r w PM-FarmScene     01-13 0710</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Farm Scene,710</SECOND>
<HEAD>Hawaii Convention For Troubled System Stirs Protests</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DON KENDALL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Farm Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A spokesman for the Farm Credit Council, an arm
of the financially beleaguered Farm Credit System, says it makes
sense to send nearly 200 of its representatives to Hawaii later this
month for a midwinter convention.
   Protests have been raised by a grassroots unit in North Dakota,
the Fargo Farm Credit Services, which tried unsuccessfully to get
the council's St. Paul, Minn., district to reduce its number of
delegates to the meeting.
   The Fargo board objected to sending a 14-member district
delegation, plus some staff people, to the Jan. 24 meeting scheduled
at the Sheraton-Waikiki Hotel. After the one-day council meeting,
most of the delegates will attend the annual convention of the
National Council of Farmer Cooperatives on Jan. 25-26.
   Joe Terrell of the Farm Credit Council's national office in
Washington said the council is an affiliate of the NCFC, which will
send about 800 delegates to Honolulu, compared with the council's
175.
   The council handles lobbying activities for the cooperative Farm
Credit System, which includes nationwide networks of federal land
banks, production credit associations, bank for cooperatives and the
federal intermediate credit bank.
   Overall, the system has a loan portfolio of more than $50
billion. As a result of a continuing financial crisis and huge
losses, Congress late in 1987 drew up a bailout plan that could pour
as much as $4 billion into the ailing system.
   Terrell said Thursday in a telephone interview that the Honolulu
convention site was selected in 1983 by the NCFC and that the
council had studied the situation for almost a year before deciding
to go to Honolulu or hold its own annual meeting somewhere else and
apart from the NCFC.
   Although there was some agonizing over the potential public
relations harm of going to Hawaii, Terrell said that a cost analysis
showed it was good business to join NCFC in Honolulu.
   Terrell said other sites were studied, including Washington,
D.C., and cities in the Midwest and on the West Coast.
   Air travel to Honolulu will be ``a little bit higher for a larger
number of people'' than to mainland cities, he said. But those
additional costs will be offset by other things, such as holding a
joint reception and sharing other functions with the NCFC.
   ``So we decided to do it, knowing that there could be some
criticism about it,'' Terrell said.
   Rep. Byron L. Dorgan, D-N.D., called the decision to send Farm
Credit System officials to Hawaii ``a foolish mistake'' in the wake
of the $4 billion bailout passed by Congress.
   ``We didn't bail them out to send them to Hawaii,'' Dorgan said.
``We bailed them out to help family farmers.''
   Dorgan, in response to an Associated Press query, said the Farm
Credit System has ``done a pretty good job under some rough
circumstances, but this is the kind of foolishness that shows a lack
of sensitivity to how things look to the folks out there in the
country who are paying bills.''
   He added: ``There are plenty of empty hotels in the farm belt
that would love to host a meeting of the Farm Credit folks. There
might be less sun, and also less heat for the Farm Credit Council.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Flue-cured tobacco farmers and buyers each will
be assessed 1.12 cents per pound for the 1989 crop, the Agriculture
Department said.
   The total of 2.24 cents covers a no-net cost assessment of 2
cents per pound and 0.24 cents to help cover the federal budget
deficit. The 1989 total assessment will be down slightly from last
year's total of 2.26 cents per pound.
   Department officials said Thursday they consulted with the
Flue-cured Tobacco Cooperative Stabilization Corp., the
producer-owned association that handles the support program, before
determining the 1989 assessment.
   The budget deficit assessment will be imposed according to the
Omnibus Budget Reconciliation Act of 1987, which calls for a
reduction in the level of price support by 1.4 percent or,
alternatively, an assessment on producers to achieve and equal
reduction in spending.
   Officials said the 1989 price support for flue-cured tobacco will
remain at $1.468 per pound as announced on Dec. 15 for this year's
crop.
</TEXT>
