<FIRST>r i PM-Britain-Ballet     01-13 0181</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Britain-Ballet,0186</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ballet Company Leaving London For Birmingham</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sadler's Wells Royal Ballet is leaving London for
the industrial city of Birmingham, lured away by $10.6 million in
extra funding.
   ``The facilities to be built in Birmingham and the new money to
be made available add up to an offer we cannot refuse,'' Jeremy
Isaacs, director of the Royal Opera House, told a news conference
Thursday.
   Sadler's Wells Royal Ballet is the touring section of the Royal
Ballet and performs at Sadler's Wells Theater, while the Royal
Ballet appears at the opera house. Both companies will continue to
be managed by the opera house, Isaacs said.
   He said the ballet company's future artistic development will
``best be secured'' by basing it in Birmingham, Britain's second
largest city with a population of more than 1 million and 110 miles
northwest of London.
   Birmingham authorities will spend $7.1 million extending the
Hippodrome Theater to provide rehearsal and other facilities for the
ballet company and will join the state-funded Arts Council to give
it an additional $3.5 million over two years.
</TEXT>
