<FIRST>u a AM-Libya-Okla     01-13 0406</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Libya-Okla,0417</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.S. Company Says German Affiliate Being Investigated In Chem Warfare
Case</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Germany-Libya, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRETT J. BLACKLEDGE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TULSA, Okla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A West German affiliate of a company here is
being investigated as a source of at least one piece of equipment
used in a suspected Libyan chemical weapons plant, officials said
Thursday night.
   West German officials are investigating material used in the
Libyan factory that may have come from Frankfurt Zink, a European
affiliate of John Zink Inc., said John Zink President Bernard Benson.
   The United States says the plant at Rabta, about 35 miles
southwest of the Libyan capital of Tripoli, is a chemical weapons
factory. Libya has denied the accusation, saying the plant is
designed to produce pharmaceuticals.
   NBC News reported Thursday night that U.S. intelligence officials
determined as early as the summer of 1987 that Libya had obtained
the chemical components of poison gas.
   Information obtained by the United States included the names of
companies in West Germany and other countries which sold supplies,
equipment and expertise to the Libyans, the network said.
   NBC showed film footage of a Zink company sign in Frankfurt. The
New York Times also has reported that Frankfurt Zink was among a
number of companies from which Libya obtained materials for the
plant.
   Benson said Zink officials in the United State were informed by
West German authorities that the Frankfurt affiliate was being
investigated. He said it is believed, but had not been confirmed,
that a flare manufactured by the company was used in the Libyan
plant.
   ``It's a fairly small part of the plant,'' Benson said. ``A
typical device used in chemical plants to burn off waste gas.''
   The West German government, which had denied that any West German
firms were involved with the Libyan plant, announced Thursday that
it had found traces of West German complicity in building the
factory.
   Benson said company records indicate that the flare, valued at
about $100,000, was to be shipped to a pharmaceutical company in
Hong Kong.
   ``Whether that actually went to Hong Kong or went to Libya, I
just can't verify,'' he said. ``We have no proof that it did end up
there (Libya). It's early in the discovery process for us.''
   John Zink is a worldwide distributor and manufacturer of
combustion equipment and environmental control devices, and about
half of its equipment is shipped outside the United States, Benson
said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
