<FIRST>r a PM-HudsonSuit     01-13 0297</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Hudson Suit,0303</SECOND>
<HEAD>Rock Hudson's Lover Believed He Would be Bequeathed Actor's Mansion</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rock Hudson's lover testified that he expected
to receive the actor's hilltop mansion after Hudson died of AIDS in
1985.
   Marc Christian, 35, said Thursday that Hudson never discussed his
will with him, but hinted several times that he would bequeath his
Hollywood Hills home to him.
   Christian told Superior Court jurors that Hudson told him, ``I
hope one day you will be able to enjoy this house as much as I
have.''
   Hudson died of complications from acquired immune deficiency
syndrome in February 1985. His 1981 will left all of Hudson's estate
to a trust. The mansion was later sold to ``Twilight Zone'' director
John Landis for nearly $3 million.
   Christian, an aspiring musician, filed an $11 million lawsuit
against Hudson's estate and his former secretary, Mark Miller, for
failing to tell him Hudson had AIDS. Christian testified Wednesday
that he had unprotected sex with Hudson for nine months before
learning from television news that the screen idol had the fatal
disease.
   Christian has tested negative for AIDS. However, he is also
seeking damages for emotional distress that he claims he continues
to suffer because doctors have told him the incubation period for
the disease can be 10 years or more.
   ``When I really think about it and can't get it out of my mind, I
begin to sweat. At night, I have nightmares that I'll look like Rock
did _ like a cadaver,'' Christian said.
   Attorneys for the estate and Miller contend Christian and Hudson
stopped having sexual relatiions in February 1984, four months
before Hudson was diagnosed with the disease. They say Christian
filed the lawsuit after he learned he was left out of Hudson's will.
</TEXT>
