<HEAD>Arizona Governor, Chief Justice, House Speaker Form Car Pool</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PHOENIX (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Arizona's governor, chief justice and House
speaker will ride to work together for a week as part of an effort
to reduce pollution.
   Democratic Gov. Rose Mofford offered Thursday to have her car
pick up Chief Justice Frank Gordon Jr., a fellow Democrat, and
Speaker Jane Hull, a Republican, beginning Monday in the
neighborhood where all three live.
   Gordon and Mrs. Hull agreed , although Mrs. Hull warned it might
be complicated if she and Mrs. Mofford wanted to have their hair
done on the same day.
   Organizers hope car pools, bus trips and bicycling can help
reduce a brown haze that hangs over Phoenix for much of the winter,
making it one of the country's worst cities for air pollution.
   State officials hope the voluntary measures will forestall
federal pollution penalties without the need for stricter auto
emissions laws.
