<FIRST>u a AM-NerveGas-Arrest 2ndLd-Writethru a0748 01-13 0970</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Nerve Gas-Arrest, 2nd Ld - Writethru, a0748,0990</SECOND>
<HEAD>Man In Custody For Alleged Attempts To Buy Nerve Gas For Exportation</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 21st graf, ``Yun and ...,'' to CORRECT to $12,000 for each
sarin bomb sted $12,000 for 500 bombs; picks up 22nd graf, `Authorities
said ...'</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NR3</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DANIEL J. WAKIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEWARK, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Korean-American businessman was arrested
Thursday in an alleged international conspiracy to buy nerve-gas
bombs for export from the United States, possibly to Iran, officials
said.
   Juwhan Yun, 48, of Short Hills, was accused in a federal
complaint of conspiring to violate the Arms Export Control Act by
seeking to ship the gas sarin, which attacks the central nervous
system causing convulsions and death.
   ``It was a wide-ranging, trans-Atlantic conspiracy,'' said First
Assistant U.S. Attorney Michael Chertoff.
   The arrest came the same day the West German government reversed
itself and said it suspected that West German companies helped build
a Libyan plant that the United States believes is for manufacturing
chemical weapons.
   The turnaround followed the arrest Wednesday night of a Belgian
shipper tied to the case and confirmation by Libya that West German
firms aided the project. Libya says the plant is for producing
medicine.
   In the New Jersey case, Chertoff added that at one point in the
dealings with Yun, the purported destination was Iran but that this
had not been verified.
   Yun negotiated with an undercover customs agent posing as an arms
dealer to buy 500 quarter-ton bombs that use sarin, said Richard
Mercier, special agent in charge of the U.S. Customs Service's
office in Newark.
   Mercier described the gas as a ``very rapid, odorless, colorless
poison which can enter the body by inhalation, absorption or
injection.''
   Yun was arrested after his wife dropped him off at Customs
offices in Newark, where Yun believed he was to meet the undercover
arms dealer, Mercier said.
   If convicted, Yun faces up to five years in prison and a $250,000
fine. He was ordered held without bail by U.S. Magistrate Ronald
Hedges pending a hearing Tuesday.
   Yun told the court his Short Hills home was worth $650,000 and
that he also owns a $400,000 New York City condominium. He said he
has three children and has been in the United States for 17 years.
   According to the federal complaint filed in U.S. District Court
in Newark, a seven-month investigation began when an arms procurer,
a confidential informant, told Customs that Komex International
Corp. of Summit had contacted the informant about buying ammunition
for export to South Korea.
   Yun is identified as president of Komex, which sought information
on the purchase of 105mm and 106mm ammunition, the complaint said.
Chertoff said Komex is an import-export concern that had engaged in
legitimate arms dealings.
   On June 27, an undercover agent contacted Yun and said he could
provide information about the ammunition.
   Court papers said the agent taped a July 6 conversation with Yun
in which Yun said that four years ago Iran asked South Korea to
deliver 400 TOW missiles, electronically guided missiles designed
mainly as anti-armor weapons. The agent said that he had 20 TOW II
missiles ready for sale. Two weeks later, the agent told Yun he had
500 TOW II missiles available, and Yun said he would make inquiries
to find ``some right people'' at the ``right price,'' the complaint
said. Authorities said the deal was never completed.
   The complaint also alleged that Yun asked the undercover agent if
he could supply Stinger missiles to the same destination as the
TOW's. ``This is believed to be Iran,'' the complaint said.
   Stingers are portable anti-aircraft missiles. The suspects
allegedly also discussed importing Varian tubes, which are power
tubes used in military radar systems, the complaint said.
   Cooperating in the investigation were the U.S. Department of
Defense, the Army and Navy, and French and British customs officials.
   British officials were involved because according to the
complaint on Nov. 27 Yun phoned a Briton, Charles Caplan, who
operates Domino Associates of London. Caplan asked Yun if he could
obtain 200 to 500 bombs of sarin, the complaint said, and three days
later Yun asked the undercover agent if he could obtain the sarin.
   Yun was communicating throughout the alleged negotiations with
K.Y. Joo, president of Kwang Jin Trading Co. in Seoul, the complaint
said. French officials entered the investigation when Yun discussed
the deal via facsimile with Joo, who was staying in a hotel in
France.
   Yun and Caplan discussed in other fascimile messages during
December the purchase of a minimum of 500 sarin bombs for $12,000
each.
   Authorities said Yun met with Caplan and two other people in a
London hotel earlier this month. The identities of the others, who
are described in the federal complaint as co-conspirators, were not
released. Caplan also was charged in the complaint, and Chertoff
said officials were discussing whether to extradite him.
   The London Daily Telegraph reported in March that a Charles
Caplan served nine months in prison for plotting to supply gun
silencers to a government official in Libya through a company known
as Domino Avionics.
   Efforts to reach officials at Komex were unsuccessful. A man who
answered the telephone at the company's offices declined comment and
hung up.
   Messages were left on a telephone answering machine at Domino
Associates Holdings Ltd. Defence Suppliers' offices in London. They
were not immediately returned.
   Last month, the St. Louis Post-Dispatch reported that U.S.
Customs officials were investigating an alleged scheme to ship
thiodiglycol, a chemical precursor of mustard gas, from the United
States to Iran via Singapore and Pakistan.
   Customs officials filed documents in U.S. District Court in St.
Louis requesting a search warrant for records between Alcolac
International Inc., a Baltimore company that manufactured the
chemical, and two companies in West Germany and Singapore.
</TEXT>
