<FIRST>r a PM-Lites     01-13 0362</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Lites,0379</SECOND>
<HEAD>On The Light Side</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LEXINGTON, Ky. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An all-expenses-paid vacation to ...
Lexington?!?
   ``The heart of thoroughbred country,'' the announcer for the TV
game show ``Jeopardy'' intoned in revealing the weeklong vacation
won by Charlie Schwartz, 38, of Venice, Calif.
   ``I was surprised, obviously,'' said Schwartz, a demographer for
a Los Angeles bank who won the $3,500 trip Friday. ``Why Lexington,
Kentucky?''
   Why not? game show officials say.
   Traditional vacation spots such as New York, San Francisco and
Florida are mixed with more unusual destinations to ``promote
awareness across the country,'' said Rocky Schmidt, a spokesman for
the show.
   Although Schwartz drove through Lexington 25 years ago, he
remembers very little about it. Schwartz said he probably would
visit Lexington with his wife and 9-month old son in late April.
   Schmidt said ``Jeopardy'' contestants two other times have won
trips to Lexington.
   Trips usually go to second-place contestants, Schmidt said. The
first-place winner Friday received $12,800 cash, and the third-place
winner got a sofa.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>CHIPPEWA FALLS, Wis. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   They held an election and no voters
came.
   The two people who requested the referendum held Wednesday never
arrived, as planned.
   Charles and Patricia Schunk live on property within a 200-acre
parcel annexed in December to the neighboring city of Eau Claire. An
annexation can be vetoed by residents of the property, and that's
what the Schunks did by not voting.
   Polls at Hallie town hall opened at 9 a.m. and stayed open for 11
hours on the referendum question of whether the land ought to remain
attached to Eau Claire.
   The Schunks are the only residents of the tract. Town Attorney
David Raihle declared the election outcome a 0-0 tie. Under state
law, the tie nullified the annexation, Raihle said.
   In an ordinary election, Hallie is a suburb of 4,500 eligible
voters. The 200-acre parcel includes vacant lots, a few businesses
and the Hallie Golf Course.
   The nullification of the annexation through the non-vote saves
the town from taking Eau Claire to court, Raihle said, because some
non-resident property owners would have insisted on suing.
   The referendum cost the town about $125, said Town Clerk Shirley
Sippel.
</TEXT>
