<FIRST>u i AM-Japan-Markets     01-13 0306</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Japan-Markets,0316</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Rises, As Do Tokyo Shares</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. dollar rose Friday against the Japanese
yen, while share prices also gained on the Tokyo Stock Exchange,
with the market's key barometer setting a record high.
   The dollar finished at 126.65 yen, up 0.53 yen from Thursday's
close of 126.12 yen. The U.S. unit opened higher at 126.70 yen, up
0.58 yen from the previous day, and moved within a range of 126.45
yen to 127.08 yen.
   On the stock exchange, the Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected
issues, which closed Thursday unchanged from Wednesday's
31,143.45-point record high close, added 154.93 points, or 0.5
percent, to close the day's trading at 31,298.38 points, a record
high for the market's key index.
   The dollar dipped briefly on a report from Washington that a West
German official had said he did not expect the U.S. to raise its
discount rate in the near future.
   Tokyo's higher opening followed overnight gains on overseas
markets, dealers said.
   Traders predicted currency trading would be thin throughout the
day ahead of a three-day weekend and the release of U.S. trade
figures on Wednesday.
   Japan's markets and most businesses will be closed Monday for an
extra day off due to a national holiday that falls on Sunday.
   Friday morning's trading was dominated by investors adjusting
their positions ahead of the weekend and the dollar was trading in a
narrow range, said Minori Takeuchi of Chemical Bank.
   In the stock market, early trading was led by individual and
foreign investors, but as the session advanced, participation
widened to include Japanese institutional investors.
   Trading was moderately active.
   Investors have not reacted with alarm to the market's rapid
advance this week. The Nikkei has added more than 900 points during
the week and climbed above the 31,000-point mark for the first time.
</TEXT>
