<HEAD>Special Dog Toilets Installed For Tourist Town</HEAD>
<DATELINE>IMPERIA, Italy (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   This seaside town plans to install special
toilets for dogs in an effort to keep its streets clean, a newspaper
reported.
   Dogs were banned last week from Imperia's historic center, but
that prohibition was lifted two days ago after a protest by animal
rights groups.
   La Repubblica newspaper reported Thursday that the city plans to
install toilets _ described as self-cleaning cylindrical structures
about five feet wide, filled with sand and containing deodorants and
``attractive substances'' _ to induce a dog to use it and not the
sidewalk.
   The newspaper quoted one resident as grumbling, ``There aren't
enough public toilets for humans, but they want to build them for
dogs.''
   The city, on the northwest coast near Monte Carlo, also said it
would provide free plastic bags to dog owners to clean up after
their pets.
