<FIRST>u i PM-Japan-Markets     01-13 0317</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Japan-Markets,0326</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Up Against Yen, Stocks Hit Another Record High</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. dollar rose today in Tokyo against the
Japanese yen, while stock prices closed at another record high.
   The dollar finished the week at 126.65 yen, up 0.53 yen from
Thursday's close of 126.12 yen. The U.S. currency opened the day
higher at 126.70 yen and moved within a range of 126.45 yen to
127.08 yen.
   Dealers said the dollar dipped briefly on a report from
Washington that a West German official said he didn't expect the
United States to raise its official discount rate in the near future.
   The dollar's higher opening in Tokyo followed overnight gains on
overseas markets, dealers said. In New York, the dollar closed at
126.38 yen after rising 0.50 yen.
   Trading in Tokyo was dominated by investors adjusting their
positions ahead of the weekend, Minori Takeuchi of Chemical Bank
said.
   Japan's markets and most businesses will be closed Monday because
of a national holiday that falls on Sunday.
   Bank of Japan Governor Satoshi Sumita today said stable exchange
rates were necessary for orderly growth of the world economy, Kyodo
News Service reported. If currency rates fluctuate wildly, Japan's
central bank will ``take necessary steps to stabilize the market,''
it quoted him as saying.
   On the Tokyo Stock Exchange, the Nikkei Stock Average of 225
selected issues, which closed Thursday unchanged from Wednesday's
31,143.45-point record high finish, added 154.93 points, or 0.5
percent, closing at 31,298.38, another record high.
   Today's bullish market was due in part to boosted confidence on
the part of individual investors who had stayed on the sidelines
during the months before Emperor Hirohito's death on Saturday, said
Michio Katsumata of Nomura Securities.
   January is traditionally a busy month in the market for foreign
institutional investors, who returned to the market after receiving
their business results at the end of December, Katsumata added.
</TEXT>
