<FIRST>r i PM-Peru     01-13 0426</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Peru,0441</SECOND>
<HEAD>Coup Possibility Talks Spread In Insurgence-Plagued Peru</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT SEAVEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LIMA, Peru (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Leftist guerrillas killed five policemen in an
attack northeast of Lima, bringing to 41 the number of people killed
since Saturday in the intensified insurgency, the government said.
   The attack by the Maoist Shining Path occurred Wednesday near
Huaraz, 190 miles to the northeast, the government said Thursday. It
did not elaborate.
   The U.S. Embassy said Thursday that the guerrillas likely
sabotaged a train and caused a crash in the Andes Mountains that
killed a New Jersey mayor's wife.
   Anna Cucci was killed and her husband, Jersey City Mayor Anthony
Cucci, was injured Dec. 1 when the rail car they rode derailed and
tumbled down a ravine near Cuzco, 350 miles southeast of Lima.
   The announcements came the same day as Prime Minister Armando
Villanueva and the army commander, Gen. Artemio Palomino, moved to
dispel speculation that the military might take over the government.
   President Alan Garcia is widely blamed for mismanaging Peru's
fragile economy and causing a severe recession, marked by record
high inflation last year of 1,722 percent, and for failing to curb
the 8-year guerrilla insurgency.
   ``The nation and the armed forces are united. There is no danger
of a military coup,'' Villanueva said Thursday. Palomino said talk
of a coup was without credibility.
   Vice President Luis Alberto Sanchez and former President Fernando
Belaunde also issued statements in recent days denying a coup was
afoot and appealing for calm.
   Nearly all political parties have demanded Garcia resign or make
drastic changes in his center-left government.
   In another development Thursday, Soviet spokesman Oleg Tkachev
said the Soviets would respect a ban against its ships fishing off
Peru.
   Last week, a Peruvian judge issued a restraining order
indefinitely suspending a three-year Soviet-Peruvian accord, which
permits 20 Soviet trawlers to annually catch 400,000 tons of mainly
mackerel and Pacific hake inside Peru's 200-mile limit.
   Fishermen argued that the contract provided unjust profits to the
Soviets.
   The government responded by soliciting another court order
barring 50 Peruvian fishing boats from leaving their home port of
Paita, 600 miles north of Lima, until the contract dispute is
resolved.
   The Lima daily El Comercio said nearly all of Paita's fishing
boats, which supply more than half of the fish consumed
domestically, began a sympathy strike Tuesday.
   Fishing is one of Peru's most important industries and more than
4 million tons of fish are caught yearly. Peru exports nearly $300
million worth of fishmeal annually, the Ministry of Fishing said.
</TEXT>
