<FIRST>r i PM-Japan-Scandal     01-13 0358</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Japan-Scandal,0370</SECOND>
<HEAD>Rightist Severs Finger To Protest Corruption</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A political scandal involving leading government
officials has prompted one irate citizen to protest by chopping off
part of a finger and mailing it to the prime minister, police said
today.
   A member of a rightist organization admitted severing the top of
his little finger on the right hand and sending it to Prime Minister
Noboru Takeshita, along with a message protesting political
corruption, a police official said.
   The official, speaking on condition of anonymity, said the
47-year-old protester was a member of an extreme rightist group. But
he refused to identify him ``because the act was obviously aimed at
seeking publicity.''
   The protester included a return address on the package, the
official said.
   A package containing the finger was delivered to Takeshita's
official residence on Tuesday with a letter describing Japan's
leaders as ``dirty politicians'' involved in a stock-profiteering
scandal, the official said.
   Scores of politicians and business leaders were offered the
opportunity to buy unlisted stocks of Recruit Cosmos Co., a real
estate subsidiary, and then reaped hefty profits after public
trading began.
   The scandal has led to the resignation of two Cabinet ministers
and 16 others from the top echelons of the bureaucracy, business and
news media. A relative and aide to Takeshita also have been
implicated, but the prime minister maintains he was not personally
involved.
   The rightist was also quoted as saying in his protest message:
``I urge you to reflect gravely (on the situation) at the beginning
of a new era.''
   Emperor Hirohito died at age 87 on Saturday and his eldest son
Akihito immediately succeeded to the throne.
   Police said there were no plans to file charges against the
protester, a resident of the Saitama region near Tokyo and a member
of a right-wing group known as Kokuyukai, or ``concern for the
country group.''
   Japan's rightist groups often drive around cities in
military-style jeeps and trucks, blaring recorded marching songs and
anti-communist slogans.
   Many extreme rightists advocate revision of the pacifist
constitution to re-militarize Japan and restore the emperor to his
pre-World War II status as a living god.
</TEXT>
