<FIRST>r a PM-US-Libya-Chemical     01-13 0303</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-US-Libya-Chemical,0311</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.S. Has Evidence Of German Involvement In Libyan Plant</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Germany-Libya, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. government has evidence implicating West
German companies in the construction of a Libyan chemical factory
and indicating that the plant began test production of poison gas,
according to news reports.
   Intelligence sources said a toxic spill occurred during an
attempt to make poison gas in August and led to frantic phone calls
to West German companies for clean-up help, NBC News reported
Thursday.
   Imhausen-Chemie, a chemical company whose officials have denied
any connection with the disputed plant, was one of those the Libyans
called for help, the TV network's news said.
   Officials, in confirming the NBC report to The New York Times,
said the evidence included extensive intercepts of telephone
conversations between the Libyans and their suppliers.
   The United States has charged that the plant at Rabta, about 35
miles southwest of the Libyan capital of Tripoli, is a chemical
weapons factory. Libya has denied the accusation, saying the plant
is designed to produce drugs.
   NBC said U.S. intelligence officials determined as early as
summer 1987 that Libya had obtained the chemical components of
poison gas.
   The United States was able to compile detailed evidence of the
Libyan operation through electronic eavesdropping, satellite
surveillance and the use of spies in Libya and Europe, NBC reported.
The information obtained included the names of companies in West
Germany and other countries which sold supplies, equipment and
expertise to the Libyans.
   Earlier this month, The Washington Post also reported that a
chemical spill occurred at the plant in August.
   The West German government had denied any German firms were
involved with the Libyan plant, but Chancellor Helmut Kohl announced
Thursday that authorities had seized documents that may show West
German companies helped build the plant.
</TEXT>
