<FIRST>r i PM-BRF--MurmanskRun     01-13 0161</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-BRF--Murmansk Run,0164</SECOND>
<HEAD>Soviets Award 30 Canadians For Murmansk Run Efforts In WWII</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LENNOXVILLE, Quebec (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   About 30 Canadians who manned Arctic
Circle naval convoys that supplied Soviet allies during World War II
have received awards from the Soviet Union.
   Igor Liakin-Frolov on Thursday pinned his country's Commemorative
Medal on the veterans, who served on some of the 900 ships that
sailed from Scotland for the Soviet port of Murmansk, on the Barents
Sea.
   ``The aid of these soldiers and merchants was very important,''
said Liakin-Frolov of the Soviet Embassy in Ottawa. ``It was not
decisive, but it was major, and the Soviet people are grateful.''
   The Murmansk Run continued until the spring of 1944, and one of
every five ships was sunk by the Germans, he said.
   ``It was very hard _ the cold, the darkness, and especially the
Germans,'' said Maurice Vaudry, who served aboard the Royal Canadian
Navy destroyer HMCS Le Huron. ``But we were young.''
