<HEAD>Winds Whip West; Rain in South</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Californians were recovering today from 100-mile-an-hour Santa
Ana winds that wrought havoc with traffic and travelers, while much
of the South was getting out the umbrellas.
   Thousands of truckers, campers and air travelers were stranded in
Southern California Thursday when hurricane-force winds damaged
buildings, turned over big trucks, forced authorities to close many
roads and shut the Ontario International Airport for 10 hours.
   High-wind warnings were posted this morning for the mountains of
Southern California, as well as for the northern third of the
Pacific Coast, Montana and parts of New Mexico.
   In the South, rain was falling across the Virginias, the
Carolinas, Tennessee, northern Georgia, northern Alabama, northern
Mississippi, southeast Arkansas and northern Louisiana.
   Flash flood watches were posted in northern Louisiana, much of
Mississippi and northwest Alabama. Heavy rainfall was to make the
Cumberland River crest 3 to 4 feet above flood stage this morning
near Fourmile, Ky.
   Snow continued during the early morning in Michigan. Scattered
snow was falling in New York, western Kentucky, southeast New Mexico
and portions of Idaho.
   Today's forecast called for rain in the Rio Grande Valley of
Texas, the Carolinas, Georgia and northern Florida. Snow and
freezing rain was predicted over southwest Texas, southeast New
Mexico and southern Oklahoma.
   Snow showers were expected to be scattered over Maine.
   Sunny skies were forecast for the remainder of the nation.
   High temperatures were predicted in the teens over northern Maine
and northeast Minnesota; in the 20s and 30s for the remainder of New
England and New Jersey, the Ohio Valley, the Great Lakes, the upper
half of the Mississippi Valley, much of the Northern Plains, the
upper Missouri Valley, northwest Texas, the Oklahoma Panhandle and
the Rocky Mountains.
   Highs elsewhere were expected to be in the 40s, 50s, and 60s.
   Temperatures around the nation at 2 a.m. EST ranged from 18
degrees below zero at Craig, Colo., to 89 degrees at Key West, Fla.
   Other reports:
   _East: Atlanta 54 rain; Boston 45 windy; Buffalo 27 fair;
Charleston, S.C. 60 foggy; Cincinnati 28 fair; Cleveland 28 partly
cloudy; Detroit 27 cloudy; Miami 67 fair; New York 41 cloudy;
Philadelphia 42 foggy; Pittsburgh 31 windy; Portland, Maine 38
foggy; Washington 47 cloudy.
   _Central: Bismarck 08 fair; Chicago 24 fair; Dallas-Fort Worth 36
partly cloudy; Denver 11 fair; Des Moines 20 fair; Indianapolis 26
partly cloudy; Kansas City 25 fair; Minneapolis-St. Paul 04 fair;
Nashville 37 cloudy; New Orleans 68 foggy; St. Louis 25 fair.
   _West: Albuquerque 22 fair; Anchorage 12 cloudy; Las Vegas 31
fair; Los Angeles 44 fair; Phoenix 40 fair; Salt Lake City 10 fair;
San Diego 45 fair; San Francisco 38 fair; Seattle 41 rain.
   _Canada: Montreal 25 windy; Toronto 25 partly cloudy.
