<FIRST>u i PM-Dollar-Gold     01-13 0397</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Dollar-Gold,0417</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Higher On West German Comments, Gold Off Slightly</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. dollar rose in European trading this
morning as the market continued to react positively to comments in
Washington by West German Finance Minister Gerhard Stoltenberg,
dealers said.
   The stronger dollar depressed gold prices slightly.
   Foreign exchange dealers said the dollar surged in Asian dealings
and continued to rise in Europe in response to Stoltenberg saying he
would like to see the dollar remain at around 1.80 West German marks.
   Dealers in Frankfurt and Milan said the market's rally was being
curbed by fears of central bank intervention.
   A trader with the Milan branch of a major U.S. commercial bank
expressed surprise at the strength of the dollar's rally so far this
year, spurred mainly by high U.S. interest rates.
   ``Let's not forget that the dollar has risen without the benefit
of a long-expected hike in the U.S. discount rate,'' she said. The
discount rate is the interest rate charged by the Federal Reserve on
loans to commercial banks.
   But another trader in Milan said the primary motive behind the
dollar's rally is speculation.
   ``The U.S. still has a big trade deficit and says it wants a
lower dollar. The west Germans have a huge trade surplus and want a
stronger mark. But the dollar surges and the mark falls,'' he said.
   In Tokyo, where trading ends before Europe's business day begins,
the dollar rose 0.53 yen to a closing 126.65 yen. Later, in London,
it was quoted higher at 126.75 yen.
   Other dollar rates at mid-morning, compared with late Thursday:
   _1.8375 West German marks, up from 1.8355
   _1.5680 Swiss francs, up from 1.5510
   _6.2705 French francs, up from 6.2150
   _2.0743 Dutch guilders, up from 2.0590
   _1,350.50 Italian lire, up from 1,339.50
   _1.2000 Canadian dollars, up from 1.1957
   In London, the British pound fell to $1.7730, compared with
$1.7880 late Thursday.
   Gold opened in London at a bid price of $403.50 a troy ounce and
at midmorning, the city's five major bullion dealers fixed the same
recommended price. It was down from $404.50 bid late Thursday.
   In Zurich, the bid price was $403.25, down from $404.20 bid late
Thursday.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold fell $1.18 to close at a bid $405.18.
   Silver was quoted in London today at a bid price of $5.90 a troy
ounce, down from Thursday's $5.95.
</TEXT>
