<FIRST>r i PM-Czechoslovakia-Britain     01-13 0172</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Czechoslovakia-Britain,0177</SECOND>
<HEAD>Czechoslovakia Wants International Convention On Plastic Explosives</HEAD>
<DATELINE>COLOGNE, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Czechoslovakia and Britain will
propose an international convention to control exports of plastic
explosives, Czechoslovakia's ambassador to West Germany was quoted
as saying today.
   Semtex, a Czechoslovak-made plastic explosive, is believed to
have been used in the bombing of Pan Am Flight 103, which blew up
over Scotland Dec. 21, killing all 259 people on board and 11 on the
ground.
   Czechoslovak experts have traveled to Britain to help in crash
investigation.
   Ambassador Dusan Spacil, in an interview with the Cologne-Bonn
Rundschau newspaper, was quoted as saying his country's rigorous
controls prevented exports of Semtex.
   Worldwide exports of plastic explosives should be regulated by an
international convention, and Czechoslovakia and Britain plan to
present such a proposal to the United Nations, Spacil was quoted as
saying.
   ``Producers of such explosives should be obliged to make an
annual report to the United Nations on the deliveries and the
recipients (of plastic explosives),'' the ambassador was quoted as
saying.
</TEXT>
