<FIRST>r i PM-Non-AlignedMovement     01-13 0319</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Non-Aligned Movement,0329</SECOND>
<HEAD>Foreign Ministers Meet To Modernize Non-Aligned Movement</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NEIL MacFARQUHAR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The non-aligned movement today recognized
an official as representing the PLO's declared state of Palestine at
the opening of a conference called to modernize the 101-member
organization.
   The head of the political department of the Palestine Liberation
Organization, Farouk Kadoumi, received a warm welcome. Foreign
Minister George Iacovou of Cyprus descended from the podium to hug
him.
   Kadoumi, considered the PLO's foreign minister, told the meeting
of foreign ministers the non-aligned movement cannot lose sight of
its goal of ``ending colonialism.''
   It was the first such high-level meeting of the non-aligned
movement since the Palestine National Council declared an
independent Palestinian state in November.
   About 90 countries, most from the non-aligned movement, have
recognized Palestine, and Kadoumi thanked them for their support. He
expressed ``gratitude for the role of the non-aligned movement in
strengthening the militancy of our Palestine people'' in trying to
establish a state in territory occupied by Israel.
   Foreign Minister Nathan Shamuyaria of Zimbabwe read a message
from President Robert Mugabe, the head of the non-aligned movement,
calling for a permanent headquarters for the organization.
   Iacovou, in his opening address, said the conference was designed
to ``make suggestions as to how the movement will become more
effective and more dynamic.''
   At the foreign ministers' conference held in Nicosia in
September, delegates complained the organization was bloated,
churning out endless documents that nobody read and adopting
resolutions nobody followed.
   The conference on updating the movement emerged from those
complaints.
   Foreign Minister Narasimha Rao of India said the movement ``is at
a crossroads. One road leads to irrelevance, the other to the role
it has played in contributing new ideas to international problems.''
   The non-aligned movement, founded in 1961, initially was designed
to represent countries that did not want to choose sides in the
U.S.-Soviet superpower rivalry.
</TEXT>
