<FIRST>r a PM-CDC--Measles     01-13 0556</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-CDC--Measles,0572</SECOND>
<HEAD>CDC Recommends Changes In Vaccinations For Measles, Which Isn't Going
Away</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT BYRD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A decade after predicting measles was on the verge
of eradication, federal health officials have proposed two new steps
to try to wipe out the disease.
   The recommendations, issued Thursday by the Centers for Disease
Control, could mean an extra measles shot for thousands of infants
and older children.
   According to the CDC, the major outbreaks of measles in the
United States in recent years have occurred among infants under the
15-month vaccination age and among school-age children who have been
vaccinated but got measles anyway. As many as 10 percent of all
vaccinations fail to provide the intended protection.
   To try to stop the outbreaks, the CDC's Immunization Practices
Advisory Committee has recommended:
   _Infants younger than 15 months, in areas where recurrent measles
is a problem, should get two measles shots instead of one _ a shot
of measles vaccine alone at 9 months, and a second dose at 15 months
in the commonly used measles-mumps-rubella vaccine.
   _In schools experiencing outbreaks and in nearby schools where
the disease might spread, all students whose measles shots came
before 1980 should be revaccinated, along with their siblings.
   That 1980 cutoff was chosen because vaccinations before then may
not have been as effective either because the vaccine subsequently
was improved or because the vaccinations came earlier in life
according to U.S. policy at the time, the CDC said.
   In the late 1970s, CDC measles specialists believed the once
common childhood disease could be eradicated by fall 1982. But that
goal was not met; from 1983 to 1988, between 1,497 and 6,282 measles
cases have been reported in the United States each year.
   Dr. Sonja Hutchins, a CDC measles specialist, could not predict
how many children would be affected by the new recommendations,
adding, ``We're in the process of analyzing that now.''
   The CDC's recommendations are not binding on local health and
education officials, but are widely recognized as health policy in
the United States.
   Local health officials will be responsible for monitoring measles
in their communities and spreading the word about the new
recommendations, Ms. Hutchins said.
   The CDC's immunization committee is recommending the two-dose
routine for infants in any county that has had five preschool
measles cases in each of the previous five years, and is urging
revaccination of certain students at any high school or college
where an outbreak is taking place or might spread from a nearby
school.
   About one in 10 counties reported at least one measles case in
1987. More than 800 cases occurred in California alone, another 469
in New York City, 452 in Texas and 318 in New Mexico.
   The nation's measles-eradication strategy, which stresses
vaccination of infants, surveillance for measles and aggressive
outbreak control, is unchanged, Ms. Hutchins said.
   ``These three elements are still important,'' she said. ``These
two major recommendations are modifications to the current
strategy.''
   The two modifications come with alternatives, the CDC said.
   In affected areas where a two-dose infant schedule isn't
possible, vaccination should come at 12 months, not 15, the agency
said. And if a school fighting a measles outbreak can't revaccinate
all students whose shots came before 1980, it should at least target
students vaccinated before the age of 15 months.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890113-0076 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-01-13-89 0724EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-Brite-Loftus     01-13 0214</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Brite-Loftus,0221</SECOND>
<HEAD>Democrat Leader Mislabeled Republican</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MADISON, Wis. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democratic legislator Thomas A. Loftus found
it troubling enough to be called ``Tommy'' by the Reagan White
House. Now Republicans rate him a ``sustaining member'' of their
national committee.
   Loftus, speaker of the state Assembly, is preparing to run in
1990 against Republican Gov. Tommy G. Thompson.
   For several years, Loftus said Thursday, the Reagan White House
sent letters addressed to Rep. Tommy Loftus.
   ``Tommy is the name my mother used to sew in my underwear,'' he
said.
   He said he tried unsuccessfully to persuade the GOP its
computerized address system was amiss. As an alternative, he
suggested Republicans address the correspondence to Thomas or Tom.
   To boot, he is among recipients of a form letter signed by
Republican Party strategist Lee Atwater, telling him: ``You have a
noteworthy record of support for Republican principles.''
   Loftus said the only part of the letter that really appealed to
him was its declaration that he has ``a special grasp of the issues
and a keen understanding of the challenges we will face as America
moves into the 1990s.''
   The Atwater letter contained a plastic card that identifies
Loftus as a ``sustaining member'' of the Republican National
Committee, to which he was invited to contribute money.
</TEXT>
