<FIRST>r a PM-Steinberg     01-13 0235</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Steinberg,0241</SECOND>
<HEAD>Psychiatrist: Nussbaum Did Not Need Psychiatric Hospitalization</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Trial scheduled to resume at 10 a.m.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SAMUEL MAULL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hedda Nussbaum, the live-in companion of alleged
child killer Joel Steinberg, did not require psychiatric
hospitalization after the beating death of the couple's daughter, a
psychiatrist testified.
   Dr. Azariah Eshkenazi, testifying for the defense, said Thursday
that Ms. Nussbaum could benefit from outpatient psychiatric care but
that in November 1987 she was oriented and coherent with
``absolutely no thought disorder.''
   Steinberg, 47, is accused of fatally beating the couple's
illegally adopted, 6-year-old daughter, Lisa. His lawyers have tried
to shift the blame onto Ms. Nussbaum, 46, who has spent the past
year in a psychiatric facility.
   The defense has argued that Ms. Nussbaum is a ``malingerer'' who
remains hospitalized to win sympathy and avoid prosecution.
   She was charged with Steinberg in the girl's death, but charges
were dropped and she became the government's star witness.
Prosecutors said she was so physically and emotionally battered by
Steinberg that she was unable to harm Lisa.
   ``I did not find any mental disorder that would require her to be
psychiatrically hospitalized,'' testified Eshkenazi, head of mental
health services for women prisoners at Elmhurst Hospital Center.
   He said he based his opinion on reports of two other Elmhurst
psychiatrists and his 45-minute interview with Ms. Nussbaum 10 days
after her arrest.
</TEXT>
