<FIRST>u i PM-Germany-PlaneCollision 3rdLd-Writethru a0531 01-13 0529</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Germany-Plane Collision, 3rd Ld-Writethru, a0531,0539</SECOND>
<HEAD>URGENT</HEAD>
<HEAD>British, German Warplanes Collide, Two Killed</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: New thruout to UPDATE with more background on military crashes
in West Germany and upcoming government report on the problem. No pickup.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BREMEN, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A British Tornado warplane flew into
a group of eight West German jet fighters today and collided with
two of them, killing the two British crewmen and injuring a German
pilot, officials said.
   Several houses were slightly damaged on the edge of the northern
village of Wiesmoor by debris from the Tornado but there were no
civilian casualties, local police said.
   The Tornado crashed into a field just outside Wiesmoor, while one
German plane came down a few miles away, the defense spokesman said.
The other plane involved in the crash managed to land safely, he
said.
   The pilot of the German jet that crashed was injured, he said.
   The accident came amid growing complaints among the West German
public about the dangers to civilians from NATO training flights
over this densely populated country. More than 100 people were
killed in military-related plane crashes last year in West Germany.
   A spokesman at the West German Defense Ministry in Bonn said the
British plane flew into a group of eight German Alfajet fighters
preparing to land at Wittmund air base near Wiesmoor, 50 miles
northwest of the port city of Bremen.
   The Defense Ministry spokesman, who asked not to be identified by
name, said the Tornado plane collided with two of the Alfajets.
Earlier reports indicated the British plane crashed with only one
German fighter.
   A spokesman at the British forces headquarters in Rheindahlen
confirmed the Tornado had crashed after the collision, killing the
two-man British crew.
   ``We can confirm that a Royal Air Force Tornado jet from No. 14
Squadron at the Royal Air Force base Brueggen crashed near the
village of Wiesmoor, killing the pilot and the navigator,'' the
spokesman said.
   Brueggen is near the West German border with the Netherlands, 210
miles south of the crash site.
   The spokesman, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said the
Tornado was on a routine training mission when it crashed.
   A Wiesmoor police spokesman said the injured German pilot had
been taken to a nearby hospital. It was not immediately clear
whether the pilot sustained his injuries while ejecting from the
airplane.
   Identities of the British crew killed in the crash ``will not be
released pending notification of next of kin,'' the British forces
spokesman said. He said a team of experts was traveling to the scene
to investigate the crash.
   In the worst military crash in West Germany last year, 70 people
died after three Italian air force stunt jets collided during an air
show at the U.S. Air Force base in Ramstein that was attended by
thousands of people.
   The last major NATO plane crash occurred on Dec. 8, when a U.S.
Air Force A-10 Thunderbolt slammed into a residential neighborhood
in the city of Remscheid, killing the pilot and five people on the
ground.
   The West German Defense Ministry is expected next week to submit
a report on ways to reduce military aircraft training flights.
</TEXT>
