<FIRST>u i PM-East-WestTalks 1stLd-Writethru a0525 01-13 0668</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-East-West Talks, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0525,0683</SECOND>
<HEAD>Human Rights Accord Accepted With New East Bloc Freedoms</HEAD>
<BYLINE>Eds: New throut to ADD diplomats' views on significance of agreement,
CLARIFY that final accord possible this week. No pickup. ^By ALISON SMALE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>VIENNA, Austria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A conference of Eastern and Western
nations today informally accepted a landmark accord on human rights
and security, diplomats said. The pact calls for freedom of travel
and religion in the East bloc.
   However, a Greek-Turkish dispute still blocked a final agreement
among the 35 nations that is to include a mandate for new European
talks on conventional weapons, said the diplomats, who spoke on
condition of anonymity. If the deadlock is broken, a final pact
could be signed on Saturday, they said.
   The disagreement between Greece and Turkey over a Turkish port in
the eastern Mediterranean has prevented negotiators from the 16 NATO
and seven Warsaw Pact nations from approving the new East-West talks
on reducing conventional troops and weapons across Europe.
   Twelve non-aligned nations are also attending the conference.
   Agreement on the human rights and security accord came after more
than two years of tough East-West bargaining at the Helsinki review
conference, which opened in November 1986.
   A copy of the accord, obtained by The Associated Press, showed
landmark agreements on the freedom of East bloc citizens to travel,
practice religion and monitor their countries' compliance with human
rights.
   Western diplomats called the Vienna document a milestone. Its key
test, however, will be whether the Soviet Union and its allies
actually stick to the new commitments.
   The pact ``refined and defined the humanitarian undertakings in
far greater detail than ever possible before,'' said Canadian envoy
William Bauer.
   He and other Western diplomats said reforms in the Soviet Union
played a major role in securing the agreement.
   The diplomats also said the human rights provisions contained in
the Vienna document are more specific than any others since the
Helsinki process began with the signing of the Helsinki Final Act in
1975.
   The document also provides a mechanism by which any two of the
signatories can raise human rights issues. Western diplomats
described that agreement as a major achievement.
   The conference is scheduled to wind up next week with a three-day
closing ceremony attended by foreign ministers from all the
signatories of the 1975 Helsinki Final Act: the Soviet Union, the
United States, Canada and all European nations except Albania.
   But that ceremony was put in jeopardy today because of the
failure to break the deadlock between Greece and Turkey. If the
impasse is broken, a final document could be accepted in a public
meeting on Saturday, diplomats said.
   Turkey agreed with the Soviet Union that the eastern
Mediterranean port of Mersin, which is close to Syrian border,
should be excluded from the new East-West arms talks.
   But Greece insists the port must be considered. It says Mersin is
a key port for shipping supplies to northern Cyprus, which is
controlled by Turkey. The rest of the island is controlled by Greece.
   Greek Ambassador Evangelos Frangoulis denied at a news conference
today that Athens raised its objections at the last minute. He said
Athens would be happy to put aside the issue until the East-West
arms talks open, probably in March. Diplomats say, however, that
Turkey will not accept this compromise.
   In an attempt to break the deadlock, the 35-nation conference
worked into the night Thursday.
   A draft document presented on behalf of the non-aligned nations
early today was informally accepted by caucuses of NATO, the Warsaw
Pact and the 12 nations of the European Economic Community,
diplomats said.
   The only outstanding human rights issue remained Canada's
acceptance of a controversial human rights conference in Moscow in
1991.
   Bauer, the Canadian envoy, said this morning he expected firm
assurances from the Soviets during the day that they would permit a
Leningrad couple waiting for 10 years for exit visas to emigrate.
   He indicated that Canada would then agree to the Moscow
conference.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
