<FIRST>r i PM-Israel-Shamir     01-13 0415</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Israel-Shamir,0426</SECOND>
<HEAD>Shamir: Peace Plan May Be Unveiled in U.S.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir was quoted today
as saying he may unveil a peace plan during a visit to Washington
but will ``swim against the tide'' in opposing a role for the PLO.
   The English-language daily Jerusalem Post quoted Shamir as saying
in an interview that the U.S. decision to start a dialogue with the
PLO gave new impetus to the 13-month-long Palestinian uprising, or
intefadeh, in the occupied West Bank and Gaza Strip.
   ``I must say that their recent step with the PLO caused grave
damage to peace, grave damage to us. I think they prolonged the
intefadeh,'' he was quoted as saying, adding that he believed the
Palestinians had been on the verge of giving up.
   He said he was developing specific peace proposals that included
his view of a final settlement for the West Bank and Gaza Strip but
refused to disclose his ideas, saying publicity would invite Arab
rejection.
   ``I'm thinking in complete frameworks, but I do not think that it
is worthwhile today to make any plan public because this will kill
it off ... they will say `no' and that's it,'' he was quoted as
saying.
   Shamir said he would make his ideas clear when he visits
Washington. Aides said he is expected to travel to Washington in
late February or March to meet with President-elect George Bush.
   ``It could be that I will propose certain ideas, or even more
than that, when I go to Washington,'' Shamir was quoted as saying.
   In a sign of flexibility on procedural questions, the hard-line
prime minister said he would welcome help in arranging the talks
from U.N. Secretary-General Javier Perez de Cuellar. But he was
adamant in opposing U.N. involvement in negotiations because he
believed the U.N. is hostile to Israel.
   ``I will never trust any decision made by the U.N. or by any U.N.
institution, because we know in advance that any U.N. body, no
matter what its composition, is against us,'' he was quoted as
saying.
   Shamir was sharply critical of European countries for insisting
that Israel speak with the PLO, which he considers to be a terrorist
organization bent on destroying Israel, despite recent PLO
statements of moderation.
   He said Israel would resist pressure from West European countries.
   ``This is perhaps our historical destiny, to swim against the
tide. But we keep on swimming. We have not drowned yet,'' he was
quoted as saying.
</TEXT>
