<FIRST>r a PM-RunawayReturns     01-13 0320</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Runaway Returns,0332</SECOND>
<HEAD>11-Year-Old Artist, Missing Three Weeks, Turns Self In</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MILWAUKEE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A troubled 11-year-old came in from the cold
after three weeks as a runaway, having captured the city's
imagination with drawings and a letter that were published in the
newspapers while he was on the streets.
   Jason Allen ``indicated he was tired, tired of living on the
streets,'' said Mark J. Voelz, his psychiatric social worker, after
the boy telephoned him Thursday and asked to be picked up at a
suburban shopping center.
   ``He is a fairly upset young man who needs treatment,'' Voelz
added.
   Jason bolted from his mother, Trudy Allen, on Dec. 23 as he was
being admitted to a treatment center for children with emotional
problems.
   The boy, ``a very bright young man'' suffering from depression,
apparently was afraid of being ridiculed for being treated there,
center, Voelz said.
   Jason's talents as an artist were apparent earlier this week when
Milwaukee newspapers published portrait sketches obtained from the
boy's family.
   One of the detailed drawings was of an elderly bearded man in a
tweed hat, holding a dog. The other sketch was of a downcast
adolescent.
   Police attempted to locate some of the people shown in the
sketches in hopes they could lead to the boy.
   On Thursday, the Milwaukee Journal published a long, rambling
letter Jason had written the newspaper.
   In it, he complained about being misunderstood, pleaded for
understanding and reminded readers, ``I am just one runaway among
thousands of others whose stories go untold.''
   Voelz said the boy took a few hundred dollars with him when he
ran away. Jason still had $65 Thursday and was wearing warm clothes,
insulated mittens and a wool hat, having ``prepared himself like a
good Boy Scout,'' Voelz said.
   Officials said the boy would be admitted to the psychiatric
center for about a week and later will be seen on an outpatient
basis.
</TEXT>
