<FILEID>AP-NR-01-13-89 0959EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-TimesSued     01-13 0209</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Times Sued,0215</SECOND>
<HEAD>NAACP Sues New York Times Over Ads</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The NAACP has sued The New York Times, charging
that its real estate ads promote discrimination by picturing whites
almost exclusively.
   The Times said in statement that its advertising conforms with
anti-discrimination laws and that the complaint appeared to be
without merit.
   The plaintiffs, who also included a housing rights group, said
photographs and drawings that accompany real estate ads in the Times
``depict whites almost exclusively as potential residents, thus
indicating a preference based on race.''
   ``Decades ago homeowners could hang up signs, or run ads that
said `Whites Only.' The fair housing laws were designed to change
all that,'' Benjamin Hooks, director of the National Association for
the Advancement of Colored People, said in a statement Thursday.
   ``But now developers run ads that say with pictures what they can
no longer say with words.''
   The plaintiffs said they recently negotiated an agreement with
the Washington Post and some of its advertisers to have black models
included in real estate ads. It said the Times declined to enter
into such an agreement.
   The civil rights suit, filed in U.S. District Court, was joined
by the New York Open Housing Center and four individuals.
</TEXT>
