<HEAD>Judge Gives Man Maximum Term For Vandalism of Jewish Temple</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A white-supremacist ``skinhead'' raised his arm in
a Nazi salute after a judge gave him the maximum, 10 years in
prison, for vandalizing a synagogue.
   Judge Joe Kendall on Thursday also fined 19-year-old Daniel Wood
$5,000. He was convicted of criminal mischief for the Oct. 8
incident at Temple Shalom.
   ``It's not illegal to hate, but it is illegal to act on that
hatred,'' the judge told Wood, who testified he was a member of the
Ku Klux Klan.
   After hearing the sentence, Wood gave Kendall a raised-arm
salute. Wood's attorney, Larry Boyd, explained that his client was
``very hurt'' and added, ``I'm sure it was just an immature,
emotional reaction.''
   Wood admitted during the trial that he and two friends spray
painted anti-Semitic slogans and swastikas on the synagogue, but he
renounced the philosophy of hate and said he hd ``gotten rid of most
of those beliefs.''
   Wood also pleaded guilty to three other incidents of criminal
mischief involving a Jewish community center, an Islamic mosque and
the breaking of the car windshield of a racially mixed couple.
   Temple Shalom's senior rabbi, Kenneth Roseman, said Wood's Nazi
salute proved the sentence was appropriate. ``He obviously is not a
repentant person,'' Roseman said.
