<SECOND>PM-Lebanon, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0547,0653</SECOND>
<HEAD>Car Bomb Kills At Least Six in Capital</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with 10 grafs to UPDATE with 2 more wounded, details.
Pickup 8th graf pvs, ``There was...''</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MOHAMMED SALAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A car bomb exploded today in a suburban
district of south Beirut controlled by the pro-Iranian militia
Hezbollah, killing at least six people and injuring 14, police said.
   The blast came on the sixth day of fierce fighting between
Hezbollah, or Party of God, and the rival Amal militia for control
of south Lebanon. Police said two civilians were killed as the
militias battled with mortars and machine guns, and another three
were wounded.
   The afternoon blast in Beirut's Bir El-Abed neighborhood came a
half hour after thousands of Hezbollah supporters demonstrated
against the Syrian-backed Amal, a police spokesman said.
   He said the demonstrators, who included hundreds of women clad in
black chadors from head to toe, had disappeared from the streets
when the car bomb went off.
   The protesters chanted ``Death to America, the great satan'' and
``Death to (Amal chief Nabih) Berri'' as they marched through the
streets following noon prayers.
   ``If it happened during the demonstration, it would have been a
much greater disaster with plenty more casualties,'' said the
spokesman, who cannot be named under standing rules.
   He said the bomb-laden car was a dark blue Mercedes-Benz, rigged
with 220 pounds of TNT.
   The explosion touched off several fires in Bir el-Abed's Roweiss
neighborhood and many shops and cars parked nearby were gutted,
police said.
   Reporters saw at least 10 cars that had been reduced to piles of
twisted metal. Twenty-six others also were damaged on both sides of
the street where the explosion occured.
   Police said the wounded included a driver for a Western news
agency and a photographer from a local Beirut newspaper. Both are
Lebanese.
   There was no immediate claim of responsibility for the car
bombing, the first in Lebanon this year. By police count there were
20 car bomb explosions in Lebanon last year that killed 116 people
and wounded 488.
   Another police spokesman said the Amal gunners slammed 120mm
rounds at the rate of 10 per minute into the village of Jbaa, held
by Hezbollah fighters. Jbaa is 30 miles southeast of Beirut.
   The new casualties in the south raised the toll to 114 killed and
230 wounded since the clashes broke out Sunday on the western edge
of Israel's self-proclaimed security zone.
   The police spokesman said thuds from exploding shells and
staccato bursts of machine gun fire echoed across the valleys of
Iklim Tiffa.
   The spokesman said Hezbollah's firepower was ``much weaker than
that of Amal's ... Hezbollahis responded by shelling Amal
positions.''
   ``It appears that Amal has started a war of attrition to force
the isolated Hezbollahis to consume their stocks of ammunition
before trying to storm their positions again,'' the spokesman added.
   Most of Jbaa's 6,000 residents fled the village after Hezbollah
gunmen captured it Sunday along with nearby hamlets.
   In a counterattack Monday, Amal recaptured four villages west of
Jbaa, 10 miles southeast of the port of Sidon, but have failed to
dislodge Hezbollah fighters from the mountain stronghold. Jbaa is
the key to a 9-square-mile enclave controlled by around 500
Hezbollah fighters.
   On Thursday, Hezbollahis repulsed a 1,000-strong Amal force, the
police spokesman said.
   Amal, or hope, has cut off supply lines to the Hezbollah enclave
by blocking its northern, western and southern approaches. Hostile
Israeli-backed militiamen of the South Lebanon Army man positions to
the east.
   Hezbollah's Shiite zealots aim at creating an Islamic republic in
Lebanon along the lines of Ayatollah Ruhollah Khomeini's state in
Iran.
   The more secular Amal favors a government that would give
Lebanon's Moslems and Christians equal shares in running the nation.
</TEXT>
