<HEAD>Engine Apparently Fell Off Cargo Plane Before Crash, Officials Say</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: UPDATES throughout with National Transportation Safety Board
finding engine, other details.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES HANNAH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Assciated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DAYTON, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An engine apparently fell off a cargo plane
before it crashed, killing both crewmen, the National Transportation
Safety Board said today.
   The twin-engine turboprop bound for Montreal went down after
takeoff Thursday morning a half mile from Dayton International
Airport.
   ``They found one of the engines away from the impact site,'' Alan
Pollock, an NTSB spokesman, said in a telephone interview from
Washington. He said that suggests the engine broke loose before
impact.
   Airport spokeswoman Sharon Caudill said NTSB investigators
recovered the ``black box'' flight recorder and also obtained
recordings of conversations between the crew and the control tower.
She did not say what they contained.
   The plane was owned by Bradley First Air of Canada and was flying
cargo for Emery Air Freight Corp. Killed were pilot Ian Grant, 37,
of Richmond, Ontario, and co-pilot Ken Bhuller, 54, of Chelsea
Pirrefondes, Quebec.
   Bruce Jonasson, manager of Bradley First Air, said the Hawker
Siddeley plane had been used by Bradley for about nine years and had
been reliable.
   The plane tore into woods several hundred yards from a row of
houses.
   ``We thought we were dead,'' said Dewey Meade, who stood at his
window as the plane cleared his roof by a few feet and crashed no
more than 200 yards away.
   ``That's how close it was. We've got debris all over the roof and
everything,'' he said.
</TEXT>
