<FIRST>u i PM-Libya-USPilot 3rdLd-Writethru a0513 01-13 0618</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Libya-US Pilot, 3rd Ld-Writethru, a0513,0635</SECOND>
<HEAD>Libya Says It Will Today Hand Over Body Of U.S. Pilot</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: New thruout to UPDATE with body arriving. No pickup.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARY BETH SHERIDAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ROME (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Libya today flew the body of a U.S. pilot killed in
the 1986 raid on Tripoli to Rome, where a Vatican representative
turned over the flag-draped coffin to Italian officials.
   The body was to be handed over later to U.S. officials.
   The Libyan military plane, a white Soviet-built Ilyushin with a
tiny green Libyan flag near one window, arrived at Rome's Ciampino
Airport at 3:45 p.m.
   The Libyan news agency JANA said Thursday that Libya was
returning the body, but did not identify the pilot. However, JANA
reported on Dec. 24 that Libyan leader Moammar Gadhafi was offering
to return the body of Capt. Paul Lorence, 31, of San Francisco.
   Libya's gesture comes during increasing international debate over
a suspected poison gas factory in Libya, and only nine days after
U.S. warplanes shot down two Libyan jets over the Mediterranean Sea.
   JANA also has complained that a Libyan Airlines plane en route
from Tripoli to Istanbul on Tuesday was buzzed over the
Mediterranean by U.S. fighter planes. The Pentagon said it had no
knowledge of such an incident.
   At the airport, a delegation including two Vatican officials and
several Italian diplomats and air force officers met the plane. No
U.S. officials were present.
   The white coffin, draped with an American flag and topped with
wreaths of red and orange flowers, was carried off the rear section
of the plane by the Italian air force officers in blue uniforms and
Libyans in green fatigues.
   The casket was set on the ground briefly before the air force
officers tranferred it to a blue police mortuary van. The body was
to be taken to a morgue for identification.
   One of the Vatican officials, Monsignor Francesco Mointerisi,
said Italian officials would later turn over the body to the
Americans.
   The Vatican said it was acting as an intermediary for
``humanitarian reasons.'' Vatican sources said the Libyans first
approached the Vatican around Dec. 15.
   JANA said Thursday that: ``In the framework of the humanitarian
initiatives to which the Great Fatah September Revolution (Libyan
government) devotes a fundamental interest, the body of the American
pilot will be handed tomorrow, 13th January, to the representative
of the Vatican, representing His Holiness, the pope.''
   Lorence and Fernando Ribas-Dominicci, 33, of Utuado, Puerto Rico,
were in an F-111 that disappeared during the April 15, 1986, raids
on Tripoli and Benghazi. Witnesses reported seeing an F-111 crash
into the Mediterranean soon after the plane being hit during the
raid.
   The other 17 U.S. Air Force bombers returned safely to their
bases after dropping about 100 tons of bombs on the cities.
   Three months after the 1986 U.S. attack, Libyan television showed
pictures of a body it said was Lorence's. Libyan authorities have
made no mention of Ribas-Dominicci.
   President Reagan said the attack was in retaliation for what he
called Libya's support for international terrorism.
   Libyan authorities said the raids killed about 40 people.
   Gadhafi was quoted as saying in the Dec. 24 dispatch that he was
returning the body ``especially since this occasion coincides with
the end of the rule of the Reagan administration.''
   The move follows the Jan. 4 downing by U.S. jets of two Libyan
planes over the Mediterranean. U.S. authorities said the attack was
in self-defense, but Libya claimed the American craft launched a
``premeditated'' attack.
   The Libyan gesture also comes after Washington threatened
possible military action against a nearly completed plant in Rabta,
40 miles from Tripoli, that it says is intended for chemical weapons
production.
</TEXT>
