<FIRST>u i PM-Germany-Libya 4thLd-Writethru a0524 01-13 0562</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Germany-Libya, 4th Ld-Writethru, a0524,0581</SECOND>
<HEAD>Prosecutor Opens Probe of Company in Chemical Weapons Plant</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: New thruout with details, corrects location of Libyan plant.
No pickup. Adds byline.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KEVIN COSTELLOE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>FRANKFURT, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A prosecutor today said he has
opened a criminal investigation into the Imhausen-Chemie company,
which the United States claims helped build a chemical weapons plant
in Libya.
   Werner Botz, chief prosecutor in Offenburg, said he opened the
probe after reading a report on the dispute in this week's Stern
magazine.
   Stern, a nationwide news magazine known for its investigative
reporting, said Imhausen-Chemie was involved in the Libyan plant,
along with I.B.I. Engineering of Frankfurt and the Hamburg-based Pen
Tsao medical material company.
   Imhausen-Chemie has denied any connection to the plant in Rabta,
60 miles outside Tripoli. News reports and U.S. government sources
have said Imhausen-Chemie provided much of the technical equipment
for the facility, which U.S. officials said was built to manufacture
poison gas.
   Libya said the plant will produce pharmaceuticals.
   Hans Frey, a spokesman for the prosecutor's office in Karlsruhe,
near Offenburg, said the possible charge being investigated is ``a
violation of the export control law.'' He said he had no other
information about the probe.
   Imhausen-Chemie, I.B.I. and Pen Tsao have been named by U.S.
officials in their accusations that West German companies aided
Libya in building the plant.
   Federal officials have audited Imhausen-Chemie and said they
could find no evidence of wrongdoing on the part of the Lahr-based
company.
   Federal officials also cleared Pen Tsao of suspicions of
wrongdoing but said investigators were examining records seized from
I.B.I., which is no longer in business.
   TV and magazine reports have shown bank documents and other
records said to establish Libyan financial links with
Imhausen-Chemie and I.B.I.
   Chancellor Helmut Kohl said Thursday authorities uncovered new
documents implicating West German companies in deliveries of
equipment for the plant.
   His spokesman, Friedhelm Ost, today conceded that Bonn officials
first learned of ``indications'' in October that West German
companies were involved with the plant.
   Ost was asked about reports alleging Bonn officials have known
for as long as two years that Imhausen-Chemie and other West German
companies may have been involved in the project.
   He said intelligence sources mentioned the possibility of West
German involvement in October but contended they had no evidence
then or now that can be used for legal action against any West
German companies.
   Today's announcement followed the arrest of a Belgian shipping
agent linked to the case and confirmation Thursday by Libya's U.N.
ambassador that West German companies assisted in the project.
   The ambassador, Ali Treiki, told CBS that West Germany ``did help
us, not only in this plant, in other plants also.''
   Federal officials said this week that Belgian authorities had
arrested and charged Jozef Gedopt, director-general of Cross Link NV
of Antwerp, with forging shipping documents for goods delivered to
Libya.
   The ZDF television network said Gedopt's company allegedly used a
Cyprus-registered freighter to deliver West German equipment to
Libya in February 1986 after forging destination papers.
   NBC News reported Thursday that Libyan officials contacted West
German companies for clean-up help after a dangerous chemical spill
in August at the facility.
   Both NBC and The New York Times quoted unidentified officials as
saying the evidence included extensive interceptions of telephone
conversations between the Libyans and their suppliers.
</TEXT>
