<FIRST>r i PM-Britain-Crash     01-13 0281</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Britain-Crash,0291</SECOND>
<HEAD>Investigators Report Wiring OK in Engines in Crash</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Investigators have determined that the engines of a
Boeing 737 that crashed Sunday north of London were correctly wired,
a newspaper said. The report, if true, would rule out a possible
cause of the disaster.
   Meanwhile, the plane's engines were crated for shipment today to
France, where the manufacturer will search for clues to the cause of
the crash.
   The British Midland Airways jet, flying from London to Belfast,
crashed into a roadside embankment while attempting an emergency
landing at an airport 100 miles north of London. The disaster killed
44 people and injured 82.
   Investigators are now trying to solve a major mystery in the
crash: why the plane's right engine shut down when the left engine
was on fire.
   U.S. and British authorities earlier this week ordered checks on
the wiring of similar aircraft engines. That move prompted
speculation that a faulty alarm system may have misled the British
Midland Airways crew into shutting down the wrong engine, causing
the crash.
   The pilot had reported his right engine on fire, but evidence of
a fire was found afterward only in the left engine.
   The Times of London said investigators were ``as certain as can
be'' that the engines were correctly wired after checks on similar
engines ended Thursday.
   Investigators are still no nearer to discovering the cause of the
engine problems and do not know if the cockpit misinterpreted
instruments in the control panel, the paper said.
   The CFM56 engines, jointly made by U.S.-based General Electric
and SNECMA of France, will be stripped down at SNECMA's plant south
of Paris, the British Transport Department said.
</TEXT>
