<HEAD>Man Shot After Apologizing For Bumping</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JACKSON, Miss. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man apologized for bumping into another
customer at a convenience store but was shot nine times as he left,
police said.
   Bennie Wansley, 32, was in stable condition today with
.22-caliber gunshot wounds to the shoulder, forearm, chest, waist,
wrist, thighs and abdomen, University of Mississippi Medical Center
officials said.
   Michael Anderson, 28, was arrested and charged with aggravated
assault in the shooting Thursday afternoon, police said. He was
jailed without bail.
   Wansley ``supposedly apologized to the individual,'' police
spokesman Robert Graham said. ``The individual became belligerent
because the guy bumped into him. He left and came back with a
rifle.''
   The man began shooting as Wansley left the store, Graham said.
Anderson surrendered to police after learning that he was being
sought, he said.
