<FILEID>AP-NR-01-13-89 1224EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-BlackMemorial     01-13 0256</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Black Memorial,260</SECOND>
<HEAD>Financial Push Begins For Black Patriots' Memorial</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Backers of a planned memorial honoring blacks
who served in the Revolutionary War banked their first major
corporate contribution Friday and said they hoped to build it in
Washington by 1991.
   Design and construction of the Black Revolutionary War Patriots'
Memorial is expected to cost about $4 million, said Bill Noack, a
spokesman for General Motors, which contributed $25,000 to the
project.
   GM also plans to sponsor a dinner in Washington on May 23 aimed
at raising another $250,000, Noack said.
   The memorial is intended to honor the 5,000 black soldiers and
sailors who fought in the Revolutionary War as well as black slaves
who ran away or petitioned for freedom during the era, according to
Maurice A. Barboza, president of the Black Revolutionary War
Patriots' Foundation.
   GM Group Vice President Marina Whitman, who presented the $25,000
check to Barboza at a news conference, said, ``We are here today to
correct the historical record, if you will. The 5,000 or so black
Americans who served in the Revolution and the many who gave their
support are not prominent in the pages of history ... (yet) they
made a meaningful contribution to our freedom as a nation.''
   Barboza said he hoped other corporations will contribute funds
``that will help us memorialize these forgotten Americans.''
   President Reagan signed a law on March 25, 1988, authorizing
construction of the memorial, which is expected to be in the area
between the Lincoln Memorial and Washington Monument.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
