<SECOND>PM-Bush Visit, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0448,0491</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush Plans Weekend Of Relaxation, Fishing</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 7 grafs to UPDATE with Bush arrival; PICKS UP 3rd
graf pvs, `Fishing guide ...'; No pickup.</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Bush, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CATHERINE WILSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ISLAMORADA, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President-elect Bush arrived this morning
for a pre-inaugural weekend of fishing to ``clear the mind'' for the
task ahead.
   ``I doubt I'll get another chance to come here as president,'' he
said in this self-proclaimed sportfishing capital. ``There won't be
any winter or summer White House anywhere. I have no intention of
building something else.''
   Bush arrived at Marathon Airport aboard Air Force Two. He was
dressed casually in a blue blazer, gray slacks and boat shoes.
   ``Why go fishing?'' asked Bush, whose inauguration is Jan. 20.
``Contentment, environment, total relaxation, peace of mind, clear
the mind for the decisions ahead.''
   He said he was looking forward to ``splendid isolation'' on his
visit to the Florida Keys.
   Bush was greeted by pigtailed 6-year-old Melissa DeFoor, daughter
of the local sheriff. Wearing a flowered dress and black patent
leather shoes, she said she was ``very excited'' about the
president-elect's arrival.
   The vice president and a crew of Washington fishing buddies
planned to drive 32 miles north, check into a townhouse, then head
for the shallows of Florida Bay.
   Fishing guide George Hommell, who has taken Bush out before, said
he had his 17-foot skiff ready for excursions into Everglades
National Park waters and the home of ``bonefish, which is probably
the fastest fish in the world.''
   Weather permitting, Bush will spend all three days of his weekend
pursuing redfish, snook, sea trout, ladyfish, jack and barracuda,
Hommell said.
   ``These are all fish that you use light tackle for, with 8- or
10-pound test line, and you cast in shallow water,'' he said.
   Treasury Secretary Nicholas Brady was expected to join Bush,
along with Sen. Alan Simpson, R-Wyo.; Dr. Burton James Lee III of
Memorial Sloan-Kettering Cancer Center in New York; Fred Zeder, a
senior transition adviser and longtime friend; and the usual
entourage of Secret Service agents and reporters.
   The excursion is Bush's third fishing or hunting trip since his
election two months ago. He went fishing in Gulf Stream, Fla., in
November and went hunting and fishing in Texas and Alabama the week
after Christmas.
   It was not the first stay for Bush in this island community of
5,000. Bush also spent time last April at Tarpon Flats, a townhouse
development where prices start at $425,000.
   J.W. ``Jim'' Gibbs, executive director of the Islamorada Chamber
of Commerce, was elated at the prospect of another Bush visit.
   ``We've had him here many times before and we've enjoyed his
visits,'' he said. ``The nice thing about our area is they come to
relax and escape all the hubbub, and that's what we allow them to
do.''
</TEXT>
