<HEAD>Oklahoma Football Player Accusd of Shooting Teammate</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 3 grafs to UPDATE with charge filed; PICKS UP 4th
graf pvs, ``At the ...'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NORMAN, Okla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A University of Oklahoma football player
shot a teammate in the chest in an argument at a dormitory for
athletes today, officials said.
   Zarak Peters was in stable condition at Norman Regional Hospital,
a bullet lodged in his ribs, said spokeswoman Paula Bowles.
   Teammate Jerry Parks, 20, was charged with shooting with intent
to injure, which carries up to 10 years in prison, said District
Attorney Tully McCoy. Parks was jailed for arraignment later today
and suspended from the university.
   ``At the University of Oklahoma we go to great lengths to protect
our students,'' interim President David Swank said in a statement.
``Possession or use of a firearm on the OU campus is in violation of
the student code.
   ``In enforcing the student code, the University of Oklahoma is
more stringent on student athletes than any other students with
frequent room visitations by members of the coaching staff.''
   The university said the two students, who attended high school
together in Houston, were arguing in the dorm for reasons still
unclear. Parks got a handgun from a vehicle parked outside and
returned, the university said.
   Peters is a lineman, Parks a defensive back.
