<FILEID>AP-NR-01-13-89 1359EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-InvestmentFundLoss     01-13 0603</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Investment Fund Loss,0620</SECOND>
<HEAD>W.Va. Governor Says `2 Sets of Books' Contributed to Investment Fund
Loss</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By A.V. GALLAGHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHARLESTON, W.Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Contradictory bookkeeping procedures and
a desire to boost commissions within the treasurer's office
contributed to losses of $279 million in the state's investment
fund, Gov. Arch Moore said.
   Moore, who leaves office Monday, announced the findings of a
private audit of the fund Thursday. It was the Republican's first
public comment on the investment fund loss since it became public
after the Nov. 8 election, in which Moore was defeated by Democrat
Gaston Caperton.
   State officials haven't said yet which state agencies and local
governments will absorn the losses, so the effect of the missing
money is not clear, said House Finance Chairman George Farley, a
Democrat.
   Even without taking into account the missing $279 million, the
state has been experiencing financial problems so severe that income
tax refunds were delayed up to five months in 1988.
   House of Delegates Speaker Chuck Chambers, a Democrat, said after
the governor's announcement that it appeared the Board of
Investments wasn't paying attention when the investment fund was
losing money.
   Moore chairs the board, whose other members are Treasurer A.
James Manchin and Auditor Glen Gainer. The board has nominal control
of the investment fund.
   Moore said at a news conference that Manchin's office was making
inflated and unrealistic interest payments to local governments,
even when the losses were piling up, so the treasury could attract
commissions.
   The consolidated fund's losses totaled $279 million through Nov.
30, said Moore. The audit by Touche Ross &amp; Co. ``ascertained that
the treasurer's office kept two sets of books,'' said Moore. ``They
kept one set of books to determine what they paid out in interest.
Another set (was kept) as related to their transactions and they
never reconciled the two methods.''
   For example, the central investment pool in the consolidated
investment fund paid out rates of 9 percent, 8.3 percent, and 7.8
percent respectively in April, May and June 1987, when the losses
were severest and the fund had no earnings, the audit showed.
   ``You will find that the treasurer's office was paying out
tremendously large sums of money that they were not earning,'' Moore
said.
   Manchin, however, was unhappy with the reference to ``two sets of
books.''
   ``I would like to believe that it was one accounting system which
took care of profits and the losses. There was another accounting
system which took care of the distributions. The distributions never
have shown where the losses were,'' the treasurer said.
   Under the guidelines of the fund, created in 1978, the treasurer
could go to an outside agency to handle investments or he could
charge a commission on what investments he could gather from local
governnments.
   The commissions ``were not monitored by the Legislature. They
were a fund out of which the treasurer's office could do essentially
what he wanted to do,'' said Moore.
   The fund generated from commissions was used to pay for
day-to-day expenses in the treasurer's office.
   Moore said the investment office borrowed billions of dollars'
worth of funds from brokerage houses to help buy the huge amounts of
securities transactions that were being handled by the investment
office. The $1.7 billion fund saw sales of $80.5 billion in 1987.
   The audit showed that $27.2 billion was borrowed in 1986 and
1987, including $10.8 billion in April 1987, the month in which the
largest loss was recorded. An addition, $4.3 billion was borrowed in
1988.
   Moore said much of the borrowing occurred without the knowledge
of the Board of Investments.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
