<FIRST>u w AM-US-ANC     01-13 0549</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-US-ANC,540</SECOND>
<HEAD>Internal Argument Surfaces In U.S. Agency Over African National Congress</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RUTH SINAI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A disagreement surfaced Friday within the State
Department about whether the African National Congress is a
terrorist organization or a legitimate freedom-fighter.
   The State Department's internal argument arose following
inclusion of the ANC in a book, ``Terrorist Group Profiles,'' issued
this week by the Defense Department.
   Officially, spokesmen for both departments said they agreed the
ANC should be in the book.
   ``That was an information document,'' said State Department
spokesman Charles Redman. ``It's not meant to be a policy
publication,'' he added.
   But within the State Department, counterterrorism officials
disagreed with professional diplomats concerned with maintaining
ties to South Africa's black majority.
   The section on the ANC, one of some 50 groups in the compilation,
says that the ANC's indiscriminate attacks on civilians in recent
years could endanger Americans caught in the cross fire.
   A Pentagon spokesman said the group was included in the book
because authorities wanted to warn Americans of the danger from the
ANC and other organizations around the world. The spokesman, Lt.
Cmdr. Jim Kudla, said the book had been ``fully coordinated'' with
the State Department.
   The office of counterterrorism at the State Department concurred
that the inclusion of the ANC had been approved, saying that while
the group is ``a political guerrilla organization, it also has used
terrorist tactics.''
   Redman also said that ``there's no question that certain (ANC)
acts ... would be considered terrorist acts.''
   But he also read a statement prepared by the department's Africa
Affairs Bureau which said ``the United States government has not
determined that the ANC is a terrorist organization.''
   The statement added that ``we regard the ANC as a politically
diverse organization ... with substantial political support in South
Africa.
   ``Some of the ANC's political objectives, such as ending
apartheid and establishing a non-racial government in South Africa
are goals we share,'' the statement said.
   ``We strongly differ with the ANC on some of the methods they
have used to pursue these objectives, including the use of
violence,'' the statement added.
   A bureau official, asked by a reporter if the statement was at
odds with the position of the counterterrorism office, said ``I
can't go any further.'' The official declined to be identified by
name.
   A counterterrorism office official, who also declined to be
identified by name, indicated that there was a difference between
the positions.
   Despite periodically condemning the ANC's car bombings and other
attacks, Secretary of State George Shultz met in Januray 1987 with
ANC leader Oliver Tambo, and State Department officials maintain
contacts with the group.
   The ANC also has support among liberals in Congress, but
conservatives condemn the group as a communist organization armed by
the Soviet Union.
   The Pentagon book says the ANC is armed with Soviet weapons and
gets most of its training in Marxist-oriented Angola.
   The South African government in 1960 banned the then-peaceful
ANC, and one year later the group began a sabotage campaign. In
recent years the ANC's attacks have expanded to include random
bombings in busy public places such as fast-food restaurants and bus
depots.
   There have been 180 bombings in South Africa over the past 31
months, killing 35 people and injuring at least 665.
</TEXT>
