<FIRST>r i PM-Britain-ComputerVirus 2ndLd-Writethru a0601 01-13 0288</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Britain-Computer Virus, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0601,0292</SECOND>
<HEAD>`Friday the 13th' Virus Strikes Computers</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Subs 6th graf, `A spokesman ...,' to CORRECT that IBM spokesman
said virus affected computers made by IBM, sted at IBM location.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A ``Friday the 13th'' computer virus struck
personal computers in Britain on Friday, wiping out program files
and annoying businesses, a computer expert said.
   Hundreds of personal computer users found the virus was
programmed to delete files on Friday the 13th, said Alan Solomon,
managing director of S and S Enterprises, a data recovery center in
Chesham.
   The virus, which might be a new species, has been slowing down
computers made by International Business Machines Corp. and
compatible models, said Solomon, who also is chairman of an IBM
personal computer users group.
   Telephone lines to the center were busy with calls for help from
businesses and individuals whose computers were struck by the virus,
he said.
   ``It has been frisky and hundreds of people, including a large
firm with over 400 computers, have telephoned with their problems,''
he said.
   A spokesman for IBM in Portsmouth, who asked not to be
identified, confirmed that the virus had wiped out files in personal
computers made by IBM and compatible machines. He said he didn't
know whether larger computers were affected.
   In the United States, several computer-security experts said
today they had not heard any reports the virus had crossed the
Atlantic.
   Solomon said his company would try to figure out how the virus
operates and then attempt to kill it. The identity of the hacker who
devised the virus might never be known, he said.
   ``It is just a pesky nuisance and is causing a lot of problems
today,'' Solomon said.
</TEXT>
