<FIRST>r i AM-Israel-Church     01-13 0463</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Israel-Church,0479</SECOND>
<HEAD>Church of Nativity Roof Leak Causes Dispute</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By G.G. LaBELLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A leaky roof on the church built over the grotto
where Jesus is believed to have been born has revived an ancient
dispute among three Christian communities over control of the church.
   When the Greek Orthodox Church recently tried to repair the roof
on the Church of the Nativity, Roman Catholics and the Armenians
complained. Now the Israeli government has taken responsibility for
repairs, an Israeli spokesman said Friday.
   ``The workers who were on the roof had to be ordered off,'' said
Shmuel Hamburger, religious affairs officer for the military
government of the occupied West Bank, where the church in Bethlehem
is located.
   Hamburger said the argument dates to before 1852, when the
then-Turkish government of Palestine stepped in to settle disputes
among the three churches.
   An agreement known as ``the status quo'' was established to
assign such responsibilities as cleaning the church, but roof
repairs have always been disputed.
   ``The procedure in which the roof is repaired, from the time of
the Turks, was done by the government,'' Hamburger said.
   Construction on the Church of the Nativity began in the 4th
century. The Greek Orthodox Church gained title in 1672, but the
Roman Catholics obtained partial ownership in 1852. The Armenians
control a southern section of the church.
   The grotto where tradition says Jesus was born is under the Greek
Orthodox part of the church.
   The three churches jealously guard their rights as outlined in
``the status quo,'' and roof work done in 1983 also caused a dispute.
   The Rev. Claudio Baratto, director of the Roman Catholic
Christian Information Center, said his church and the Armenians
consider the roof common property and believe any repairs should be
approved by all three churches.
   Baratto said the roof has been leaking for years and referred to
it as part ``an ancient question'' over which the churches continue
to argue.
   ``Some parts pretend to have rights that the other parts
contest,'' he said.
   ``We hope in the future to reach a sensible solution,'' Baratto
added. But for now, he said, the Israeli government will have to
take responsibility for the repairs.
   Hamburger said they should be made after the rainy winter weather
subsides.
   A spokesman for the Greek Orthodox Church could not be reached
for comment. Bishop Timothy, secretary to the Greek Orthodox
Patriarch, told the Jerusalem Post that the church was not trying to
repair the roof but only to clean out rain gutters.
   He added, however, that the church has the right to make roof
repairs if it wishes.
   ``If we wanted to do something, we would do it. I don't think
they had the right to complain,'' the newspaper quoted him as saying.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
