<SECOND>AM-Bulgaria,0271</SECOND>
<HEAD>Human Rights Activists Arrested in Bulgaria</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SOFIA, Bulgaria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Authorities arrested seven human rights
activists, and they face prosecution on charges of telling lies
about the state, the government said Friday.
   The activists, reported arrested in Plovdiv, are connected with
the Independent Society for the Protection of Human Rights in
Bulgaria, according to a Western diplomat and newspapers in Sofia.
   BTA, the official news agency, carried an Interior Ministry
statement on the arrests of the seven. It identified four of them as
Ilia Stoyanov Minev, Grigor Simov Bozhilov, Dimiter Tomov Yordanov
and Blagoy Vassilev Topouzliev.
   An exile source, speaking on condition of anonymity, said Minev
was president of the human rights group and had spent 27 years in
jail.
   The Otechestven Front newspaper linked Menev to Eduard Genov, a
leading Bulgarian dissident who spent 10 years in internal exile. He
and another activist, Ivan Yankov, were expelled and arrived in
Vienna on Oct. 20.
   In an interview then, Genov told The Associated Press that
Bulgarian officials appeared poised to stifle dissent out of fear it
might snowball into a growing opposition.
   The BTA announcement said most of those arrested had been
previously convicted of various crimes and investigators would
``undertake the necessary actions for clarifying the facts and
circumstances (for) charging these people with criminal offenses.''
   It added, ``In complicity and internationally, they have
disseminated untruthful allegations with the aim to create mistrust
of authorities and their work.''
   The allegation apparently referred to interviews given by some of
those arrested to Western reporters or radio stations.
</TEXT>
