<HEAD>Tyson `All Smiles' After Heeding The `Lovebird Whistle'</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: RAISES reference to `lovebird whistle.' CORRECTS `affected'
to `effected' in next-to-last graf. No pickup. A version also moving on
sports wires.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LAS VEGAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mike Tyson was said to be ``all smiles'' today
after heeding the ``lovebird whistle'' and rushing off to see Robin
Givens in Canada, where the champ also got in some sparring practice
with news cameras.
   The 22-year-old fighter left training camp Wednesday without
luggage or entourage to go to Vancouver, where his estranged wife
was filming an ABC movie.
   Tyson, who is scheduled to fight Frank Bruno of Britain Feb. 25
at the Las Vegas Hilton, arrived back in town Thursday night, said
Bruce Banke, hotel executive director of publicity.
   ``He was all smiles, very calm, very gracious,'' said Banke, who
talked with the champion briefly today before Tyson got into a
sports car and drove away.
   Tyson is involved in divorce proceedings against Givens, who
recently filed a $125 million libel suit against him.
   ``Tyson went to Vancouver for the simple reason that there is a
thing called the lovebird whistle,'' Al Braverman, a fight promoter,
said from New York.
   In Vancouver, Tyson threw a photographer's camera and snapped the
viewfinder off a TV camera as he entered a hotel. No charges were
filed.
   Jasper Vance, an ABC publicist, said Tyson visited Givens on the
set, but ``I don't know whether this means they have effected a
reconciliation.''
   A member of the movie's production staff who refused to give his
name said the couple were ``very affectionate'' on the set.
