<FIRST>r w AM-MissileTreaty     01-13 0458</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Missile Treaty,460</SECOND>
<HEAD>Helms Says Soviets Violating Treaty At Missile Plant But US Is Satisfied</HEAD>
<HEAD>By LAWRENCE L. KNUTSON</HEAD>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sen. Jesse Helms, R-N.C., said Friday the
Soviet Union is preventing U.S. inspectors from X-raying containers
leaving a Soviet missile assembly plant and is therefore violating
the treaty banning medium-range, nuclear-armed missiles.
   But the State Department said it expects full Soviet cooperation
when the X-ray equipment is ready to be installed and is satisfied
that existing procedures will enable the detection of any banned
medium-range SS-20 missile attempting to leave the factory.
   ``The United States is satisfied with the implementation of the
... treaty to date,'' said department spokesman Charles Redmond.
   Helms, in a letter to President Reagan, called inspection rights
at Votkinsk the ``heart and keystone'' of the treaty's verification
system and said that under the treaty's terms the U.S. inspection
team should have been able to X-ray all items leaving the factory by
last Dec. 1, six months after the treaty went into effect.
   ``The package of procedures that the Soviets obligated themselves
to allow have not been agreed, in part because the Soviets have made
unacceptable demands for other procedures and provisions,'' Helms
said.
   ``Because of this failure to agree to the U.S. X-ray rights, the
U.S. X-ray equipment is still not installed at Votkinsk,'' he said.
   Helms asked Reagan what he intends to do to ``prevent the Soviets
from continuing to exploit their potential to cheat at Votkinsk''
and added:
   ``Due to Soviet intransigence, the U.S. has been totally unable
to monitor effectively or verify whether the Soviets have continued
to manufacture or deploy perhaps dozens of banned SS-20 missiles
from the Votkinsk factory for the last eight months that the treaty
has been in force.''
   But at the State Department, Redmond said that any problem was a
minor one.
   ``The Soviet Union agrees fully with the right of the United
States to install that kind of equipment,'' Redmond said, adding
that the Soviets will have the same X-raying privileges at the U.S.
facility at Magna, Utah.
   ``We are now in the final stage of working out of the details of
implementing this right,'' Redmon said. ``The United States is in
the final stage of testing the appropriate equipment for this
particular verification method.''
   ``When we are fully ready to install our equipment we expect the
Soviet Union will cooperate with us fully,'' he said.
   A 30-person U.S. team continuously monitors the Votkinsk facility
and has inspected every vehicle leaving it large enough to contain
an SS-20, Redmon said.
   Additionally. he said the inspection team is ``opening randomly
selected SS-25 canisters.''
   ``This particular monitoring activity is but one element of a
comprehensive set of verification procedures,'' Redmond said.
</TEXT>
