<SECOND>AM-Bus Wreck,0240</SECOND>
<HEAD>Driver of Bus Involved in Accident Had Suspended License</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LEXINGTON, Ky. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A school bus driver involved in an accident
that injured 45 people faces a charge of driving with a suspended
license, authorities said.
   Two students remained in a hospital Friday in serious but stable
condition, one day after a coal truck and the bus collided as the
bus pulled into a rain-drenched intersection in London, Ky.
   Enoch Smith, 33, is to appear in court Jan. 23 on a charge of
driving with a suspended license, London Police Chief Bill Smith
said.
   Enoch Smith had not been told that his license had been revoked
for failing to pay a $15 fee for a speeding ticket, said Laurel
County school Superintendent Joe McKnight, who said Smith had paid
his fine but not a reinstatement fee.
   No decision has been made on what action may be taken against
Smith, McKnight said.
   The accident happened at the entrance of North Laurel Junior High
School a few minutes after school let out. Truck driver John B.
Massey tried to swerve to avoid the bus, but he jackknifed and hit
it at an angle, police said.
   ``The (bus) driver pulled out in front of the truck,'' the police
chief said. ``No question about that.''
   Inspectors from the state departments of Transportation and
Education examined the 1987 bus early Friday at the school's garage.
