<FIRST>r a AM-PaganArrests     01-13 0489</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Pagan Arrests,0504</SECOND>
<HEAD>Officials Arrest 19 Members Of Biking Club</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MATT HARVEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHARLESTON, W.Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Authorities in three states arrested 19
motorcyle club members or their associates early Friday on federal
racketeering, drug and firearms charges.
   A federal indictment names 29 members or associates of members of
the Pagan Motorcycle Club, including the group's national president
and vice-president, said U.S. Attorney Michael W. Carey. Authorities
have leads on the members not yet arrested, he said.
   Separate indictments name six non-club members as part of the
biker investigation, and it was not clear Friday afternoon how many
of the 19 were Pagan members.
   Carey said the Pagans, which has chapters throughout the East, is
considered among the most dangerous such clubs in the country.
   ``They've commited virtually any crime you can name,'' said Terry
Katz, a Maryland state police sergeant who has been involved in
operations against the Pagans for 13 years.
   More than eight kilograms of cocaine, 4,000 doses of LSD and
several ounces of methamphetamine were seized or bought during the
investigation, Carey said. Besides West Virginia, arrests were made
Friday in Ohio and Pennsylvania. And search warrants were issued in
Virginia in connection with the investigation.
   A federal grand jury in Charleston charged 29 people on Tuesday,
and the 85-count indictment was unsealed Friday, Carey said. The six
non-members were named in five indictments.
   Pagan membership stands at about 280, with 130 of that number in
prison, Carey said.
   Katz said the arrests would weaken the club, but he said
retaliation is possible.
   ``They have burned houses of witnesses, made threats. ... They
are a violent organization,'' Katz said. ``They react violently to
intimidation, and that's what they view this as.''
   Club President Daniel Delp of Alliance, Ohio, is charged with
racketeering, racketeering conspiracy, engaging in a continuing
criminal enterprise, conspiracy to distribute controlled substances,
interstate travel in aid of racketeering and distribution of
controlled substances. Delp is under arrest, according to a
spokesman for Carey.
   If convicted on all counts, Delp would face a life sentence and
fines of up to $7.75 million, Carey said.
   The vice president, Kenneth Blain McMillion, 41, of Charleston,
is charged with racketeering. McMillion would face 20 years in
prison and fines of up to $250,000 if convicted, Carey said.
McMillion is still at large.
   The 17 people who were arrested in the Charleston area probably
will be arraigned later this afternoon, a spokeswoman for the U.S.
Magistrate's Office said.
   Those arrested in other states will be arraigned at the nearest
magistrate court, she said. Members are being held by the U.S.
marshal in various locations.
   None of those arrested was available for comment until after
their court hearings, a spokesman for the U.S. Marshal's office in
Charleston said. Calls to three attorneys representing Pagans in the
Charleston area were not immediately returned. Others arrested had
not yet obtained counsel, according to the magistrate's office.
</TEXT>
