<FIRST>r w AM-GrazingFees     01-13 0261</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Grazing Fees,260</SECOND>
<HEAD>Grazing Fees Rising on Federal Land</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grazing fees on most federal land will be
raised by 21 percent March 1, partly because of higher beef prices,
two federal agencies said Friday.
   The Forest Service, part of the Agriculture Department, and the
Bureau of Land Management, part of the Interior Department, said the
new fee for grazing in national forests and on public land
administered by the bureau in the West will be $1.86 per animal per
month, up 32 cents from the previous year.
   By presidential directive, the two agencies use the same formula
to set grazing fees. The formula rises and falls with beef prices,
among other factors.
   F. Dale Robertson, chief of the Forest Service, said ``the prices
farmers and ranchers received for beef cattle increased by 9
percent, and private grazing land lease rates increased in most of
the states involved.''
   For grazing fees, the agencies consider one animal to be a horse
or burro, five sheep or goats, or a cow and a calf.
   The new fees apply to national forests in Arizona, California,
Colorado, Idaho, Montana, Nebraska, Nevada, New Mexico, North
Dakota, Oklahoma, Oregon, South Dakota, Utah, Washington and
Wyoming, and on bureau lands in those states plus Kansas and Texas.
   For national grasslands in Colorado, Kansas, Nebraska, New
Mexico, North Dakota, Oklahoma, South Dakota, Texas and Wyoming, the
Forest Service will charge $2.29, an increase of 46 cents or 25
percent.
   About 3 percent of the nation's beef supply is grazed on public
lands while on the hoof.
</TEXT>
