<FIRST>r a AM-TaliesinPlan     01-13 0343</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Taliesin Plan,0351</SECOND>
<HEAD>New Non-Profit Group Seen to Restore Taliesin</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MADISON, Wis. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Architect Frank Lloyd Wright's former home
at Taliesin needs a five-year, $16 million restoration and should be
opened as a tourist attraction, according to members of a state
commission studying the site.
   Commission members say they plan to recommend creation of a
non-profit corporation to undertake the restoration and oversee
operation of the landmark. Some state money would be involved, but
most would be raised from corporations, foundations and private
donors, commission members said.
   Taliesin, built in 1911 on 600 acres amid the rolling hills of
southwestern Wisconsin and declared a national landmark in 1976, now
is a school for architects.
   Commission members said they were optimistic the plan would win
the blessings of the Taliesin Fellowship, Gov. Tommy Thompson and
other state officials, and that restoration would start soon.
   The commission expects 200,000 to 250,000 people to visit
Taliesin annually. The site also would be available for national and
international conferences.
   ``There are some unknowns since there's quite a lot of logistics
involved in handling that many people,'' said Nicholas Muller, head
of the State Historical Society and a member of the study
commission. ``But the commission is not looking at the state as a
great pot of money.''
   There is some disagreement among commission members about how to
perform the restoration, said Marshall Erdman, a builder, architect
and former Wright student who heads the state commission.
   ``We want to do it right,'' he said. ``If we do it incorrectly,
there's no use doing it. On the other hand, we have to deal with
practicalities. And fortunately, unlike most restoration work, we
still have people who were there on the site, so we can save a lot
of effort and research.''
   Air conditioning, a new heating systems and better glass bonding
would make Taliesin comfortable year round, Erdman said.
   ``A lot of the things we're doing is the way it should have been
done had Mr. Wright had the resources and technology we have
today,'' Erdman said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
