<SECOND>AM-King Bust,0218</SECOND>
<HEAD>Philadelphia Sculptor's Bust of King To Be Unveiled In South Africa</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Philadelphia sculptor's life-size bust of
Dr. Martin Luther King Jr. will be unveiled at the U.S. Embassy in
South Africa to mark the slain civil rights leader's birthday.
   Sculptor Zenos Frudakis said the bronze bust, commissioned by the
embassy in Pretoria, will be installed permanently in the embassy's
outdoor garden.
   A State Department spokeswoman in Washington, Mary Swan,
confirmed Friday that the embassy would hold an unveiling ceremony
Monday.
   The bust is derived from a model Frudakis sculpted as one of
three finalists in a competition held by the National Endowment for
the Arts for a portrait of King for the U.S. Capitol.
   In a statement issued in Philadelphia, Frudakis said Anglican
Bishop Desmond Tutu, black activist Winnie Mandela, U.S. Ambassador
Edward Perkins and other dignitaries are expected at the ceremony.
   The artist, whose other works include a sculpture of Philadelphia
Mayor W. Wilson Goode, said he considers the King bust his most
important work.
   ``I felt compelled to re-create someone who has been lost to all
of us _ to bring back alive those qualities of character which are
embodied in his features and recognized by the world he changed
forever,'' he said.
