<FIRST>r i AM-Canada-Tritium     01-13 0522</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Canada-Tritium,0535</SECOND>
<HEAD>Canada Unlikely to Resolve Any U.S. Tritium Shortage</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SOLL SUSSMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TORONTO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Tritium, a gas that strengthens nuclear bombs, is
a byproduct of Canada's nuclear power plants, but the United States
shouldn't look to the north for a way to ease a shortage caused by
problems in U.S. weapons plants.
   ``It would not be amenable,'' said Atomic Energy Control Board
spokesman Hugh Spence. ``In peacetime certainly it would not be
amenable. Certainly we would not countenance sales directly to the
weapons system.''
   Anti-nuclear activists allege that any exports to the United
States would be virtually impossible to track in their civilian or
military uses.
   ``Even if our tritium isn't used directly in military weapons
systems, which we suspect it will be, it will free up their scarce
supplies,'' Irene Koch of the Nuclear Awareness Project said in a
telephone interview.
   The Savannah River Plant in Aiken, S.C., the only U.S. source of
the radioactive isotope of hydrogen, is closed because of safety
problems. The U.S. Department of Energy has recommended building two
new production reactors, at a cost of $8.6 billion. Meanwhile, the
Defense Department needs to replenish the tritium, which decays at a
rate of 5.5 percent a year, in its warheads.
   The U.S. nuclear industry is based on light-water reactors, which
use water as a coolant and other materials as moderators _ slowing
the neutrons enough so they cause fission. Canada's 18 reactors use
heavy water _ in which hydrogen is replaced by the isotope deuterium
_ as coolant and moderator.
   One byproduct of the reaction is tritium, which also has some
commercial and industrial applications, including in emergency
lighting devices.
   ``Right now the plan is to remove the tritium and then store it
on site,'' Young said in a telephone interview. ``We still haven't
made that decision to sell any of it, let alone export any of it to
the U.S.''
   The question of exports came up in the debate over the plant 47
miles east of Toronto, ``mainly from the critics who oppose this,''
he said.
   ``It's very much an issue for us. It has been for a couple of
years,'' said Koch, whose group is pressuring the Ontario provincial
government to refuse permission for any tritium exports.
   The federal government also would have to license exports of
radioactive materials, and Spence said Canada has one of the world's
most stringest systems of safeguards against nuclear exports for any
military purposes.
   It requires countries with recognized nuclear capacities _ the
United States, Britain and France _ to agree that no Canadian
materials will be used for weapons. In general, other countries must
have ``full-scope safeguards'' to obtain Canadian materials, and
must allow international inspection of all nuclear facilities. India
was cut off in 1974.
   It also is recognized that exports for peaceful uses free a
supply for weapons systems, although that has not come up in any
debate, Spence said. ``I know the Americans know our safeguard
concerns and in many ways share them.''
   Washington has not approached the Canadian government for
tritium, he said. ``It really hasn't come up.''
</TEXT>
