<FIRST>r w AM-CatastrophicIllness     01-13 0444</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Catastrophic Illness,450</SECOND>
<HEAD>Older People Support Program</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEBORAH MESCE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Most older Americans support a new national
health insurance program that pays the catastrophic costs of major
illness, according to a poll released Friday by the American
Association of Retired Persons.
   The new health insurance law, which took effect Jan. 1, will
cover extended hospitalizations and help pay high prescription-drug
bills. It will be financed by premiums paid by all Medicare
enrollees, a sore point among some retirees.
   The poll of 1,750 people age 45 and older found 71 percent
supported the program while 15 percent opposed it. Among the 657 who
were age 65 and older, 65 percent supported the program and 21
percent opposed it.
   AARP said the finding that concerns them most is that more than
half of those questioned said they were not familiar with the
program.
   ``There a great need to get the facts out,'' said John Rother,
AARP's director of legislation, research and public policy. ``Even
those familiar with it are in fact misinformed'' about aspects of
the program, he added.
   The 28-million-member AARP supports the catastrophic illness
program and has started a campaign to educate senior citizens about
its benefits.
   Some retirees are upset they will have to pay for coverage
whether they want it or not and say they could do better buying
private insurance.
   The major financing provision of the program has been the target
of most complaints. It requires everyone eligible for Medicare who
pays more than $150 in federal income taxes to pay an extra premium
based on the amount of tax they own.
   The maximum surtax on any person is $800 this year, or $1,600 for
a couple if both spouses are eligible. Such a couple would have
income of at least $70,000.
   Overall, 58 percent of those polled said they viewed the
supplemental premium based on tax liability as positive.
   However, a majority of those surveyed said they did not like
having only those over 65 pay for it. Overall, 52 percent viewed
this as a negative aspect of the program, compared with 42 percent
who said was it was positive.
   Sen. Lloyd Bentsen, D-Texas, said he was gratified by the poll
results and anticipates no change in the tax.
   ``It offers security and peace of mind to older Americans and the
vast majority of them understand and appreciate that,'' he said in a
statement.
   The poll was conducted by telephone Dec. 2-18. Results have a
margin of error of plus or minus 2.5 percentage points for the
entire group of 1,750 and 4 points for the subgroup of those age 65
and older.
</TEXT>
