<FIRST>r i AM-India     01-13 0340</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-India,0350</SECOND>
<HEAD>Four Killed, 200 Wounded In Sikh-Hindu Clash</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JAMMU, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hindus and Sikhs fought with guns and swords
Friday during a religious procession honoring two Sikhs executed for
the assassination of Prime Minister Indira Gandi, authorities and
witnesses said.
   Civil administrator N.R. Gupta said at least four people,
including a Sikh trapped in a burning truck, were killed. About 200
people were injured, and more than 200 shops were looted and set
ablaze, he said.
   The government of Jammu-Kashmir state imposed a curfew on the
northern city and ordered police to shoot violators.
   Police opened fire several times and used tear gas to try to stop
the fighting, but it continued until 1,000 army troops arrived more
than five hours later, Gupta said.
   Witnesses said the fighting started shortly after about 2,000
Sikhs left a temple on a procession in honor of Kehar Singh and
Satwant Singh, who were hanged last week and now are revered as
martyrs of the Sikh faith.
   Many carried pictures as the eight-mile procession moved through
a Hindu neighborhood, and a group of militant Hindus asked the Sikhs
to remove the pictures, the witnesses said. One Sikh pulled a dagger
and lunged at the Hindus, who retaliated, they said.
   Jammu, 40 miles north of Sikh-dominated Punjab state, has a
population of about 500,000. Of these, about 80,000 are Sikhs, about
300,000 are Hindus and the rest are Moslems.
   Kehar Singh and Satwant Singh were executed for the assassination
of Mrs. Gandhi, who was killed Oct. 31, 1984, in apparent
retaliation for an army raid she had ordered on the Sikhs' holy
Golden Temple.
   Sikh militants were using the temple as a base for their fight
for an independent homeland in Punjab state.
   The assassination caused anti-Sikh riots in many northern cities,
including Jammu. More than 2,700 people died, most of them Sikhs.
   Sikhs comprise 2 percent of India's 800 million people but are a
majority in Punjab. Sikh militants claim discrimination by Hindus,
who comprise 80 percent of the country's population.
</TEXT>
