<FIRST>u w AM-US-Germany-Libya     01-13 0497</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-US-Germany-Libya,500</SECOND>
<HEAD>Official Says Prosecution Of Firm Will Require ``Complete Evidence''
^With AM-Germany-Libya Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARRY SCHWEID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Diplomatic Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The West German finance minister said Friday
his government had ``some new information'' to link firms in his
country with the construction of a plant in Libya that the United
States says was designed to develop chemical weapons.
   But the West German official said criminal prosecution would
proceed only if there was ``complete evidence.'' Gerhard Stoltenberg
pledged after a one-hour meeting with Deputy Secretary of State John
C. Whitehead that ``whatever it takes to get information, it will be
followed.''
   Meanwhile, West German and U.S. experts held a second day of
meetings on the intelligence the Reagan administration has used to
support its claim that Libya was trying to develop chemical weapons
at the plant, some 60 miles southwest of Tripoli.
   ``We are trying to provide as much information as possible,''
Charles E. Redman, the State Department spokesman, said. He said the
talks at an undisclosed location would be ``useful and productive,''
but provided no other details.
   Separate British and Dutch investigations also point to an
attempt by Col. Moammar Gadhafi's country to develop chemical
weapons. Secretary of State George P. Shultz said last week the
Libyans had not reached the point of production.
   Stoltenberg, in a curbside news conference outside the
department, renewed allegations that West German firms had been
targeted for criticism by U.S. media.
   ``What we did not like in some American press comments,'' he
said, ``was to single out Germany because it is obvious that it
could have been a problem of quite a few other countries.''
   The finance minister said the United States and West Germany
should join in promoting international cooperation to prevent
technology transfers to countries which could produce chemical
weapons to endanger world security.
   Officials of the West German government last week registered
skepticism that the United States had evidence to link West German
firms to the plant, which Gadhafi said was producing pharmaceuticals.
   However, Chancellor Helmut Kohl said Thursday in Bonn that
authorities had seized new documents that may show firms helped the
North African country build a chemical plant.
   On Friday, Hans Frey, a spokesman for the prosecutor's office in
Karlsrube, told The Associated Press there would be an investigation
into the Imhausen-Chemie company.
   Frey said the possible charge being investigated was ``a
violation of the export control law.'' He did not elaborate.
   Imhausen-Chemie has denied any connection to the Libyan plant.
   Stoltenberg said the evidence came from West German sources.
``There was no proof a week ago,'' he said, ``and now there is some
new information in the last days ... which could lead to criminal
prosecution.''
   But he said ``it's not a final decision... We must have complete
evidence (to prosecute). Whatever it takes to get information, it
will be followed.''
   Referring to the dispute with the United States, the West German
official said ``we have really made progress in understanding.''
</TEXT>
