<FILEID>AP-NR-01-13-89 2018EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-AirlineSecurity     01-13 0605</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Airline Security,0623</SECOND>
<HEAD>Two Journalists Lied On Applications, Got Jobs At Heathrow</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EDITH M. LEDERER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two British journalists said Friday they got jobs
as airplane cleaners at Heathrow Airport using fake applications and
were able to wander on and off jets where they could easily have
planted bombs.
   One of them, a London Weekend Television researcher, said he left
a package on a Japan Airlines flight without being challenged.
   The other, Daily Express reporter Graham Dudman, said he was
hired by Skyliner Services after a 10-minute interview and found
``alarming holes'' in Heathrow security three weeks after a bomb was
planted on Pan Am Flight 103.
   The two journalists were not working together when they got their
airport jobs. The British Airports Authority, which operates
Heathrow, refused comment.
   Dudman said he decided to apply at the airport after a bomb blew
up Flight 103 on Dec. 21, killing all 259 people on board and 11
people on the ground in the Scottish town of Lockerbie.
   The New York-bound flight originated in Frankfurt and switched to
a bigger plane at Heathrow.
   Dudman said he was hired by Skyliner Services, a private cleaning
contractor, after an interview Jan. 4. He said his application,
which contained many lies, was never checked. Dudman said he
received a pass that allowed him access to all areas of the airport,
and he started work Jan. 9.
   ``As a part-time aircraft cleaner, it enabled me to board 12
jetliners on any one of which I could have planted a bomb under a
seat or in a locker,'' he said.
   ``I gained unchallenged access to luggage containers and the
cabin and flight decks of trans-Atlantic airlines where at times I
was alone and unsupervised,'' he said.
   Dudman said he carried bulky packages and a camera past security
posts and was never stopped or questioned, even when he took
photographs on the airfield. Several photographs appeared in the
paper, including one that showed the reporter posing near some Pan
Am luggage.
   ``Each member of the cleaming staff I spoke to about security
said they had never seen any and expressed amazement there had been
no clampdown after Pan Am,'' Dudman said.
   London Weekend Television said researcher Stewart Morris was
hired by Fernley Aeroclean, using a fake name. It said he planted a
parcel on Japan Air Lines Flight 402.
   Morris said he wasn't searched when boarding planes or supervised
while working and could have planted the parcel anywhere, except
possibly TWA which ran a metal detector over the cabin after the
cleaners had finished.
   Paul Ross, a reporter for London Weekend Television, said after
he received a call from Morris, he bought a ticket on Flight 402,
retrieved the package from under a window seat during the flight and
took it into the cockpit without challenge.
   ``It could have contained a bomb, a gun or a knife,'' he said.
``I could easily have blown up or hijacked the plane.''
   London Weekend Television said the incident was filmed and would
be shown Sunday, subject to approval by the Independent Broadcasting
Authority.
   After Dudman's disclosure, Heathrow's managing director, Alan
Proctor, announced that Heathrow had withdrawn security passes for
staff at Skyliner.
   Transport Secretary Paul Channon ordered the British Airports
Authority to tighten security to ensure no one had unsupervised
access to aircraft or checked baggage in restricted areas unless
they had held an airport pass for at least six months.
   Skyliner called the government's action ``a very harsh decision
because procedures for security are the same with us as they are for
all the other companies at Heathrow.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890113-0161 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-01-13-89 2018EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-UnmarriedCouples     01-13 0425</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Unmarried Couples,0442</SECOND>
<HEAD>Landlord Who Refused to Rent to Unwed Couple Challenges State Lawsuit</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MARSHALL, Minn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man being sued by the state for refusing
to rent to an unmarried couple is challenging the state Human Rights
Act, which he says violates his religious beliefs forbidding sex
before marriage.
   ``The Bible clearly states this is wrong,'' Layle French, 32,
said Thursday from his farm outside Marshall, in southwestern
Minnesota. ``I live with the Bible as my guide.''
   French said the Human Rights Act, which protects Minnesotans from
various forms of discrimination, violates his First Amendment right
to freedom of religion and is unconstitutional.
   The dispute began last February when Susan Parsons of Marshall
sought to rent a house owned by French. Parsons and French entered
into an agreement in which Parsons told French she intended to live
with her fiance and that his two children would stay with thempart
of every month, according to a Human Rights Department complaint.
   Two days later, French told Parsons he had changed his mind and
would not rent to her. French said he told her, ``Why don't you get
married and I'll let you rent it.''
   He and his attorney, James R. Anderson, filed a written response
Friday with the state attorney general's office to the lawsuit filed
Dec. 7 by the state Department of Human Rights.
   An administrative law judge is scheduled to hear the case April
11.
   Anderson said the law's lack of a provision for a jury trial
makes it unconstitutional.
   Human Rights Commissioner Stephen Cooper said juries do not hear
human rights cases because juries are supposed to reflect the
society's majority, and human rights laws are designed to protect
the minority.
   He said French was trying to control the lives of his tenants.
   ``Landlords often have exaggerated ideas of what their rights
are,'' Cooper said. ``They're trying to invent a constitutional
right to say, `I have the right to tell you what to think.'''
   French said he believes by living together the couple would
violate a little-known state statute that outlaws sexual intercourse
between unmarried adults.
   ``We contend it's a very schizophrenic state that on the one hand
outlaws fornication and on the other compels cohabitation,'' said
Anderson. ``It's against his religious convictions to rent on that
basis.''
   He conceded that the misdemeanor sex statute was rarely enforced
although still on the books.
   Cooper said French had no evidence Parsons and her fiance would
violate the law forbidding sex before marriage.
   Phone calls to Parsons' home for comment Friday went unanswered.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890113-0162 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-01-13-89 2019EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-MissileRecorder-Soviets     01-13 0328</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Missile Recorder-Soviets,330</SECOND>
<HEAD>Official Says Lost Missile Part Would Be Valuable To Soviets</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A flight data recorder missing from a 1987
long-range nuclear missile test would provide valuable information
to any U.S. adversary that might have recovered the device, an
Energy Department official said Friday.
   Although the recorder contained no classified information, ``it
is valuable,'' said Chris Sankey, a department spokeswoman. She
declined to describe the specific value of the recorder to the
Soviet Union or any other country.
   The Pentagon acknowledged earlier this week it was investigating
the loss of the recorder and said there was a possibility it may
have been found by the Soviets.
   Defense officials also said the recording device, which would
contain such information as the acceleration and velocity of the
missile during flight, was not classified. But a Pentagon source
indicated the data would be valuable to a U.S. adversary since the
missile was being tested under realistic conditions.
   ``Wouldn't you like to get your hands on that?'' asked the source.
   Sankey said a search for the device was continuing jointly by the
departments of defense and energy but there was no clear evidence it
had fallen into Soviet hands.
   The Energy Department is responsible for building and testing the
Pentagon's nuclear warheads. During test flights the missiles carry
a dummy warhead and not an actual nuclear weapon, although the rest
of the missile contents are real.
   Ms. Sankey said only the flight date recorder and ``some minor
debris'' were lost during the U.S. recovery of the Minuteman 2
missile that was launched July 7, 1987 from California toward
Kwajalein Atoll in the western Pacific Ocean.
   She said this was the first time that a missile's flight data
recorder had been lost in a test flight.
   ``It doesn't pose a loss of any technology for the United States,
but obviously there are a lot of things unclassified that we don't
want non-allied countries to have,'' Ms. Sankey said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
