<FILEID>AP-NR-01-13-89 2025EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-Debt     01-13 0396</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Debt,400</SECOND>
<HEAD>Stoltenberg Says US, Allies to Meet on Third World Debt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CARL HARTMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. Treasury Secretary Nicholas F. Brady will
meet with cabinet members from six major allies to prepare for a
major gathering on Third World debt, West German Finance Minister
Gerhard Stoltenberg said Friday.
   The ``Group of Seven'' includes West Germany, Japan, Britain,
France, Italy and Canada. Their ministers of finance and the heads
of their central banks meet at irregular intervals to try and bring
their economic policies closer together and coordinate policy on the
dollar and other currencies.
   Robert Levine, a spokesman for the U.S. Treasury, said no
decision has been made on the meeting. Support for it has now also
been voiced by Nigel Lawson, the British chancellor of the
exchequer, who saw Brady earlier this week.
   The presidents of seven major Latin American debtor countries
will be meeting in Caracas Feb. 2 at the inauguration of Carlos
Andres Perez as president of Venezuela.
   Perez and the recently inaugurated President Carlos Salinas de
Gortari of Mexico have taken the lead in urging relief from the debt
burden that has resulted in net payments of $20 to $30 billion a
year from poor countries to richer ones.
   Venezuela, one of the most regular with its payments, at length
joined many of the other debtor governments and suspended payments
of principal on most of its $30.3 billion debt on Dec. 31. There
have been reports that Perez is considering a stop on interest as
well.
   Dan Quayle, who will be inaugurated next week as vice-president,
will represent the United States at the inauguration.
   Latin American countries owe more than $440 billion of the $1.3
trillion of Third World debt. Brazil, Mexico and Argentina are the
biggest Third World debtors, with much of the money owed to U.S.
banks.
   In April, representatives of 151 countries, including many
cabinet members, will be in Washington for a semi-annual meeting of
the World Bank and the International Monetary Fund. The debt and how
to reduce it will be major topics there.
   The seven governments try to coordinate their buying and selling
of currencies to keep the prices as stable as possible. Stoltenberg
said that would continue while plans are worked out by the Bush
administration to reduce the U.S. budget deficit, a goal strongly
urged by the allies.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
