<FIRST>r a AM-BoneSuit     01-13 0417</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bone Suit,0437</SECOND>
<HEAD>Malpractice Settlements Reach $5.3 Million In Bone Peg Cases</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ST. PETERSBURG, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Four medical malpractice suits
against a doctor who replaced patients' spinal discs with bone taken
from cadavers have been settled for $5.3 million, said lawyers for
the plaintiffs.
   Aaron Schneider, an orthopedic surgeon, used a garden hose to
wash the bone pegs cut from pelvic bones of cadavers at the Pinellas
County morgue, after getting permission from next of kin, lawyers
said. He then stored the bone pegs in his kitchen freezer, they said.
   Three other malpractice suits against Schneider are pending.
   The latest settlement of $975,000 was reached Tuesday, 90 minutes
into the testimony from the first witness during the trial of a suit
brought by Dolores Nelson, 47, of St. Petersburg.
   Her lawyers said she suffered crippling pain and a severe loss of
mobility because of the procedure.
   ``Nobody that I know uses this procedure,'' testified Dr. Ronald
B. Greene, an orthopedic surgeon from the University of
Pennsylvania's medical school.
   Schneider's insurer, Florida Patients Compensation Fund, agreed
to settle while Greene was testifying.
   In earlier court proceedings, Schneider denied he committed
malpractice, but he declined to comment after the settlement.
   The procedure is not experimental but is considered difficult and
requires extensive training, said Miami lawyer Larry Stewart, who
represented Mrs. Nelson.
   Schneider performed the operation 107 times on 58 people, and his
own records showed a success rate of 24 percent, said another lawyer
for Mrs. Nelson, Larry Bianchi.
   Schneider told Mrs. Nelson, who injured her back in a 1981 fall,
that replacing a disc with a bone peg had a 90 percent chance of
alleviating her pain, according to court papers.
   Mrs. Nelson's pain, however, worsened after the operation at
Humana-Sun Bay Community Hospital in St. Petersburg, and she
sustained nerve injury, the suit said.
   She underwent two more operations, one using more bone pegs from
a cadaver and the other using bone chisled from Mrs. Nelson's hip.
In the end, she had 14 different bone pegs hammered in and nine
chisled out, the suit said.
   The hospital also was named in the suit but was dropped from the
case Monday after agreeing to a small settlement, that was not
disclosed.
   Prior settlements reached in the last six months have ranged from
$247,500 to $2,062,000. Three more cases are set for trial later
this year.
   The Florida Department of Professional Regulation has no public
record of any investigation or discipline involving Schneider, a
spokesman said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
