<FILEID>AP-NR-01-13-89 2039EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r p AM-DallasMayor     01-13 0366</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Dallas Mayor,0376</SECOND>
<HEAD>Strauss Announces Re-Election Bid, Hopes To Spend Less</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EVAN RAMSTAD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mayor Annette Strauss on Friday announced her
candidacy for a second term as the leader of the nation's
seventh-largest city, a day after a mayoral commission released its
plan to stem racial tensions.
   ``Dallas is on the move again,'' said Mrs. Strauss, 64, the
city's first elected woman mayor. ``We've regained the momentum of
the '60s, '70s and early '80s.''
   The mayor said she has worked hard to promote the city as a good
place to do business.
   ``Dallas is the best place anywhere for businesses to succeed,''
she said, but conceded that Dallas has been losing tax base to its
suburbs.
   ``At the top of my list of priorities are fighting crime and
drugs and economic development, which I believe are inextricably
tied together.''
   The second year of her first two-year term as mayor was one of
the most violent in the city's history. Five Dallas police officers
were killed and the city recorded a record number of homicides.
   She said progress has been made toward easing racial tensions and
praised the work of Dallas Together, a 76-member commission she
appointed to study race relations in the wake of the police
shootings and a dispute over the role of the Dallas Police Citizens
Review Board.
   The commission issued a report Thursday that recommended the
appointment of a charter review committee to study the number and
composition of city council districts. Dallas' City Council is now
comprised of the mayor, two at-large members and eight district
members.
   Expensive campaigns keep many people from running for city
office, Dallas Together said. Mrs. Strauss spent about $1.2 million
on her mayoral race in 1987, but she said she would not spend that
much for the May 6 election.
   She is the only announced candidate for the post.
   Mrs. Strauss served two terms as an at-large City Council member
and defeated Fred Meyer in a runoff for mayor in 1987. The
incumbent, Starke Taylor, did not run.
   A public relations consultant, Mrs. Strauss has been active in
Dallas civic and performing arts organizations for more than 20
years.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
