<FILEID>AP-NR-01-13-89 2102EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-UN-Parking 1stLd-Writethru   01-13 0361</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-UN-Parking, 1st Ld - Writethru,a0715,0367</SECOND>
<HEAD>Big Ticket Toll For Little Rwanda</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 8th graf, `The Soviet...' to CORRECT that Soviet Union
uses diplomatic plates; picks up 9th: The Parking...</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER JAMES SPIELMANN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Diplomats from the tiny African nation of
Rwanda collected more parking tickets per car than any other U.N.
mission in the city where the world body makes its home.
   Data released Friday by New York's Parking Violations Bureau show
the five cars of the East African nation's mission received 307
summonses in the first six months of 1988. The bureau said each car
collected an average of 10.2 tickets a month.
   Sudan, Bahrain, the Ivory Coast and Seychelles rounded out the
list of the top five parking scofflaws, according to bureau figures.
   Each of Sudan's five cars was ticketed an average of 8.47 times
per month, Bahrain's three vehicles each got 7.83 tickets a month,
the Ivory Coast's 13 vehicles each got 6.96 tickets, and Seychelles
with one car collected six.
   Figures for the last half of 1988 are not yet available.
   Consular and U.N. diplomats hold diplomatic immunity and thus
cannot be compelled to pay parking tickets. Few ever do, and the
Parking Violations Bureau does not try to collect the millions in
unpaid fines.
   New York parking tickets cost $10 to $40, depending on the
offense.
   The Soviet Union, with 110 vehicles, did not even make the list
of the top 20 offenders. The U.S. Mission does not issue diplomatic
plates to its employees, and did not appear on the list.
   The Parking Violations Bureau turns its list over to the New York
City Commission for the United Nations and Consular Corps, which
serves as liaison between the city and the foreign diplomatic
community.
   Officials in that commission, headed by Gillian Martin Sorensen,
talk to the worst offenders and have achieved some success in
reducing the number of offenses.
   The total number of parking tickets went down from 153,784 in
1978 to fewer than 65,000 in 1985, even though assigned diplomatic
parking spaces in midtown Manhattan were cut by 40 percent,
according to Mrs. Sorensen's office.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
