<FIRST>r i AM-6thFleetExercises     01-13 0286</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-6th Fleet Exercises,0295</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.S. Navy Conducting Exercises in Mediterranean</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GAETA, Italy (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. 6th Fleet forces are conducting routine
exercises in the Mediterranean, a spokesman said Friday.
   The maneuvers, code-named National Week, are being held in
international waters and air space, said Lt. Ray Kempisty.
   ``National Week is a routine, previously scheduled exercise that
has been held once or twice a year since 1967,'' he said.
   The maneuvers began Wednesday, a week after U.S. Navy jets shot
down two Libyan warplanes over the Mediterranean. Libya's ambassador
to the United Nations, Ali A. Treiki, has called the operations a
provocation.
   Tensions were high even before the jet downing, as Washington
raised the possibility of a military strike against an alleged
chemical weapons factory near Tripoli.
   Defense officials said the exercises were taking place well away
from Libya and that Washington had canceled a missile-firing
exercise in the central Mediterranean north of Libya.
   Kempisty said the exercises are to end Tuesday.
   He said the maneuvers are designed to ``train the incoming
carrier battle group in Mediterranean operations.'' He provided no
other details.
   A 13-ship battle group headed by the aircraft carrier Theodore
Roosevelt sailed into the Mediterranean early Wednesday, joining the
carrier John F. Kennedy and its support ships.
   Defense officials in Washington said Wednesday that the two
carrier battle groups would participate in joint operations for a
few days before the Kennedy sails for home.
   The Roosevelt is accompanied by six destroyers, two cruisers, a
frigate, an ammunition ship, an oiler and a repair ship. The Navy
said about 15,000 sailors and Marines were with the carrier group.
   A Marine amphibious group accompanying the Theodore Roosevelt has
not yet entered the Mediterranean, Kempisty said.
</TEXT>
