<FIRST>r i AM-BRF--Britain-Bomb     01-13 0149</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--Britain-Bomb,0154</SECOND>
<HEAD>Villagers Evacuated After World War II Bomb Found</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PLYMOUTH, England (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A World War II bomb was found Friday in
a quarry outside the port city of Plymouth, and residents of nearby
Brixton village were evacuated pending the arrival of an army bomb
squad, police said.
   No one was allowed within one mile of the site.
   Plymouth residents said they thought the 600-pound bomb marked,
``1941'' and ``Rhine,'' was one of two dropped by a German aircraft
to lighten its load as it was chased by fighter planes.
   Plymouth, in southwestern England, has a naval dockyard and was
heavily bombed during World War II. Wartime bombs and unexploded
anti-aircraft shells are found regularly.
   A 500-pound bomb was found in east London's old docklands in
November.
   Authorities evacuated hundreds of people, blocked streets and
halted air traffic and construction work until the bomb could be
defused.
</TEXT>
