<FIRST>r i AM-IdiAmin     01-13 0284</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Idi Amin,0293</SECOND>
<HEAD>Former Ugandan Dictator Leaves Senegal</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DAKAR, Senegal (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Airport authorities said former Ugandan
dictator Idi Amin left Dakar on Friday apparently bound for
Kinshasa, the Zairean capital, from which he was just deported.
   The authorities said on condition of anonymity that Amin flew out
on the same Falcon 50 plane that brought him to the Senegalese
capital on Thursday. It belongs to the Zairean state mining company
Gecamines.
   Amin, accompanied by one of his sons, was detained in Kinshasa on
Jan. 3 as he tried to enter Zaire on a false passport, one of a
batch reported stolen.
   Zairean officials said they established that Amin intended to
return to Uganda through Zaire. The two countries share a common
border.
   Officials in Kinshasa made it clear Amin's presence was unwelcome
and an embarrassment. They assured neighboring countries of
continuing cooperation and good will.
   Calling himself ``Dada'' (Big Daddy), the 300-pound Amin seized
power in a 1971 coup and ruled until 1979, drawing world accusations
of human rights atrocities and corruption. Uganda's president now is
Yoweri Museveni.
   Amin was supposed to take a flight from Dakar to Saudi Arabia,
where he has been living in exile for years, but the plane left for
Jidda, the Saudi capital, without him, the authorities said.
   They said the pilot would not accept him as a passenger because
he did not have a Saudi visa. They said when the Falcon 50 left they
presumed it was returning to Kinshasa.
   Elaborate security precautions at the airport prevented reporters
from talking to Amin.
   Saudi diplomats said authorities in Jidda were not pleased at the
manner he left the country and are not happy about accepting him
back.
</TEXT>
