<FIRST>u i AM-Afghanistan 1stLd-Writethru   01-13 0850</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Afghanistan, 1st Ld - Writethru,a0700,0869</SECOND>
<HEAD>Red Army Leaves Kabul in the Cold</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: INSERTS four grafs after 5th, `They (</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MAUREEN JOHNSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KABUL, Afghanistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Alongside the icy runway at Kabul's
airport, about 500 Soviet soldiers laden with equipment lined up
Friday in front of giant transport planes waiting to take them back
to the Soviet Union.
   Downtown, Afghans huddled in blankets against the biting cold,
forming long lines for bread or gasoline. Bread, the staple diet of
the poor, has become a precious and increasingly expensive commodity.
   Afghan guerrillas, assisted by a bitter winter, appear to be
making an increasingly effective attempt to blockade the city of 3
million, and some diplomats say the Soviet strategy is to get out as
quickly as possible, with as little publicity as possible.
   Indeed, Friday's troop departure was the latest in what Western
diplomats say is a rapidly accelerating pullout that belies hints
from Moscow it may not meet next month's withdrawal deadline.
   ``They (the Soviet troops) are leaving and they want to cover up
the Kabul end of it,'' said one Western diplomat. ``It could be that
with the acute shortages, they don't want to show the unpleasant
reality of Kabul.''
   But the Soviet news agency Tass said Friday: ``An extremely
difficult situation developed in Kabul in providing the population
with foodstuffs. Long breadlines appeared in the city.''
   It reported that the government imposed an anti-hoarding decree
under which ``people who deliberately hide surplus foodstuffs and do
not hand them over in time, are brought to court.''
   Tass said convoys of food, fuel and other necessities were being
rushed into Kabul, but ``groups of extremists attack convoys
virtually every day and are a constant threat to Kabul's supplies.''
   Afghan government forces killed or wounded 100 insurgents in
battles in Nangarhar and Kandahar provinces, and near Kabul seized
54 missiles intended for use against the capital city, the news
agency said. Another 170 resistance fighters were killed or wounded
in fighting among rival factions, Tass said.
   Under a U.N.-mandated agreement, the Red Army, which entered
Afghanistan in December 1979, is to be out of the country by Feb.
15. Soldiers began leaving May 15, and about half the estimated
100,000 were gone by Aug. 15.
   But the Moslem guerrillas fighting the Soviet and Afghan troops
this week broke off negotiations with Yuli Vorontsov, the Soviet
deputy foreign minister and the ambassador to Kabul. Vorontsov
hinted that if the insurgency continued, the Soviet troops might
delay their departure.
   Western diplomats say the current rate of withdrawal indicates
the bulk of the Soviet troops are likely to be gone ahead of
schedule.
   Soviet Foreign Minister Eduard A. Shevardnadze traveled to Kabul
on Friday. The nature of his visit was not disclosed by Tass.
   Friday's group of troops was lined up beside two blue and white
Ilyushin-76 transport planes. More than a dozen smaller Antonov
aircraft were nearby. Diplomats estimate that seven to eight Il-76
aircraft arrive and leave daily.
   This week, the Soviets shut down their 700-bed military hospital
in Kabul, pulled out all the medical staff and handed the facility
over to the Afghan administration. Soviet civilian advisers as well
as government ministers are also going. There are no firm numbers on
how many of the estimated 2,500 advisers remain.
   Diplomats say that in the past week, the number of advisers at
the Ministry of Health has been cut from 16 to two and at the
Afghan-Soviet Transport Company from 20 to five.
   The price of nan, the flat bread that along with sugar and tea is
all most Afghans can reguarly afford, has more than doubled to about
15 Afghanis. At the commonly used black market rate, a U.S. dollar
is worth 200 Afghanis.
   Sugar ran out at most stores about a month ago.
   On Sunday, a regular working day in this Moslem country, the
bread shortage was so acute that 80 percent of bread stores were
closed. Witnesses said a group of Afghan soldiers broke into and
robbed one store that still had supplies.
   Large parts of the city are without power for up to six hours
daily. In what appears to be part of an effort to conserve power,
the university closed in November, a month early, and won't reopen
until March, a month late.
   Thos who can afford it are exacerbating the shortages by stocking
up.
   People join cars at gas stations, filling up two-gallon cans to
lug home.
   One Western diplomat estimated that up to 7,000 of the remaining
50,000 Soviet soldiers may have left since the new year. The U.S.
State Department said Jan. 11 that the Soviet Union had renewed its
withdrawal from Afghanistan.
   Army Gen. Vitaly M. Shabanov, a deputy Soviet defense minister,
told a Moscow news conference Friday: ``It is our intention to abide
by the Geneva agreements. This is our duty and indeed this is the
firm opinion and strong intention of our leaders. So there can be no
doubts in this regard.''
</TEXT>
