<FIRST>r w AM-YoungAtHeart 1stLd-writethru a0720 01-13 0229</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Young At Heart, 1st Ld-writethru, a0720,220</SECOND>
<HEAD>Eds: Subs 4th graf to CORRECT date of firing airing to 1987</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An academy-award winning documentary about the
romance of an elderly Michigan couple will be broadcast by Soviet
television in late January or early February, a cable television
said Friday.
   The documentary, ``Young at Heart,' tells of the romance and
marriage of artists Louis Gothelf and Reva Shwayder of Franklin,
Mich.
   Gothelf emigrated from Russia to the United States at the age of
13. The pair are each in their 80s.
   Detroit producer Sue Marx, Gothelf's daughter, made the
documentary, which was first aired on The Learning Channel in 1987
and won an Academy Award for the best short documentary in 1988.
   The chairman of The Learning Channel, Harold Morse, said he
believes the Soviet decision to show the documentary ``will mark the
beginning of an ongoing program exchange between The Learning
Channel and the Soviet Union.''
   Marx's camera follows Gothelf and Shwayder, both coping with the
loneliness that followed the death of their spouses, as their common
interest in art blossoms into a love affair.
   The couple move in together, prompting Gothelf's granddaughter to
ask, ``Why can you live with someone and I can't?''
   In the end, Gothelf and Shwayder decide to marry, and the
documentary concludes with an exchange of vows in a garden ceremony.
</TEXT>
