<FILEID>AP-NR-01-13-89 1838EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Soviet-Afghan     01-13 0563</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet-Afghan,0578</SECOND>
<HEAD>Shevardnadze Arrives In Afghanistan</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Afghanistan, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KABUL, Afghanistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soviet Foreign Minister Eduard A.
Shevardnadze arrived in the capital on Friday, the Afghan news
agency said, and more fighting was reported between government and
rebel forces.
   Tass,the Soviet news agency, also said the government has
reopened a main supply line to Kabul that had been cut by heavy snow
and resistance attacks. The break in the supply line had created
long bread lines.
   Shevardnadze's trip, reported in a one-sentence statement by
Tass, had not been announced previously. Tass gave no indication of
his itinerary.
   ``Soviet Foreign Minister Eduard Shevardnadze left Moscow for
Kabul on a working visit today,'' the Tass dispatch said. Radio
Kabul reported his arrival.
   The trip came after the U.S. State Department said Jan. 11 that
the Soviet Union had renewed its withdrawal from Afghanistan.
   Under agreements signed in Geneva, the Soviet Union withdrew half
of its 100,000 soldiers between May 15 and Aug. 15 and the remainder
are to leave by Feb. 15.
   But Soviet officials have accused Pakistan and the United States
of violating those agreements by continuing to provide military aid
to the Afghan resistance, and have raised the possibility that the
withdrawal will not be completed on time.
   Army Gen. Vitaly M. Shabanov, a deputy Soviet defense minister,
told a Moscow news conference on Friday: ``It is our intention to
abide by the Geneva agreements. This is our duty and indeed this is
the firm opinion and strong intention of our leaders. So there can
be no doubts in this regard.''
   Asked to comment on the State Department report that the second
stage of the withdrawal had begun, he said, ``The first stage of the
withdrawal is over and I am sure the second stage will begin soon.''
   Yuli Vorontsov, first deputy foreign minister and the Soviet
ambassador to Afghanistan, has urged the formation of a broad-based
government including representatives of the ruling pro-Soviet
People's Democratic Party of Afghanistan.
   But the resistance refused to continue talks with the Soviets,
saying Vorontsov was trying to secure a place for its ally in any
post-war government.
   Tass reported Friday that a car bomb exploded in the Afghan city
of Herat, killing or wounding 20 people. In another report, Tass
said a main supply route to Kabul from the northern village of
Hayraton, closed by heavy snow and rebel attacks, had been reopened.
   ``An extremely difficult situation developed in Kabul in
providing the population with foodstuffs. Long breadlines appeared
in the city,'' Tass said. It reported that the government imposed an
anti-hoarding decree under which ``people who deliberately hide
surplus foodstuffs and do not hand them over in time, are brought to
court.''
   Tass said convoys of food, fuel and other necessities were being
rushed into Kabul, but ``groups of extremists attack convoys
virtually every day and are a constant threat to Kabul's supplies.''
   Afghan government forces killed or wounded 100 insurgents in
battles in Nangarhar and Kandahar provinces, and near Kabul seized
54 missiles intended for use against the capital city, it said.
Another 170 resistance fighters were killed or wounded in fighting
among rival factions, Tass said.
   Soviet troops entered Afghanistan in 1979 to replace a faltering
Marxist regime with a new government and stayed behind to fight an
anti-communist insurgency. They agreed to withdraw under a
U.N.-brokered accord reached last year.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
