<FIRST>r w AM-Justice-Press     01-13 0432</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Justice-Press,430</SECOND>
<HEAD>Official Uses Private Firm for News Release</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES ROWLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A departing Justice Department official used a
private public relations firm Friday to announce a press conference
that was not officially cleared with the attorney general.
   The public relations company that issued the release for
Assistant Attorney General Roger J. Marzulla had recently prepared
an announcement that the outgoing head of the land and natural
resources division was joining a local law firm to start an
environmental-law practice.
   Without telling the Justice Department's public affairs staff,
Hartz@Meek International Inc., told news organizations the land
division planned to file a court action against the District of
Columbia's sewage treatment plant.
   Department spokesman Loye Miller said use of a private public
relations firm to announce an official Justice Department action was
unprecedented and ran counter to established procedures.
   The firm got involved in official Justice Department business
just four days after the agency announced deep cuts in its public
affairs staff that would take effect in 30 days.
   Later Friday, Marzulla appeared before television cameras in his
office to discuss the court action even though department officials
said he had not received clearance to hold a press conference.
   At the outset, Marzulla said he was conducting a briefing, not a
press conference. But he read a prepared statement and took
questions during a session filmed by two local TV camera crews.
   The Hartz@Meek press release was distributed before the Justice
Department issued its formal release announcing the government was
seeking a $3.1 million contempt-of-court judgment against the D.C.
government for failing to upgrade the sewage plant.
   Miller said he was unaware of the private company's news release.
Miller said he had been unable to get clearance from the attorney
general's staff for Marzulla to hold a press conference.
   Miller said Marzulla had sought clearance from Attorney General
Dick Thornburgh's office to hold a press conference. The spokesman
said he was prepared to advise Marzulla not to hold a press
conference when he was told the assistant attorney general had
withdrawn his request for clearance.
   Marzulla said he asked Hartz@Meek to issue the release to give
local news organizations notice that the department's action was
being taken.
   More publicity is needed, Marzulla said because the department's
anti-pollution efforts have been ``eclipsed by the wrong notion that
there has not been enough enforcement.''
   He denied seeking to promote his new career as an environmental
lawyer by using the public relations firm to summon local reporters
to the briefing.
   ``It does not strike me as inappropriate,'' Marzulla said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
