<FILEID>AP-NR-01-13-89 1855EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-East-West 2ndLd-Writethru a0706 01-13 0759</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-East-West, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0706,0784</SECOND>
<HEAD>Human Rights, Security Accord Informally Accepted</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 10 grafs to move up material on accord. Pick up 5th
pvs, ``Shultz could...' Edits thereafter to conform and trim.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALISON SMALE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>VIENNA, Austria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   NATO, the Warsaw Pact and 12 other
European nations on Friday informally accepted a landmark human
rights and security accord designed to enhance freedom in the Soviet
bloc and boost East-West contacts.
   But a lingering dispute between Greece and Turkey continued to
block final agreement on a mandate for new East-West arms talks.
   The accord includes provisions that would increase religious
freedom; speed emigration procedures and the issuance of visas for
important family reasons; allow independent monitoring; encourage
tourism; allow freer spread of information; and give all prisoners
humane treatment.
   Another provision would stop the abuse of psychiatry against
political prisoners. Soviet authorities have been accused of using
mental hospitals to punish dissidents.
   Western diplomats hailed the document as a major advance on human
rights, but noted the key test was whether the Soviet bloc would
stick to it.
   The 1975 Helsinki Final Act, signed by the Soviet Union, the
United States, Canada and all European nations bar Albania,
contained commitments to free travel, information and other human
rights that the East bloc often violated.
   The Vienna document ``refined and defined the humanitarian
undertakings in far greater detail than ever possible before,''
noted Canadian Ambassador William Bauer, who played a prominent part
in Western efforts to achieve good human rights agreements.
   Reforms in the Soviet Union played a major role in securing the
agreement, Bauer and other Western diplomats said.
   Diplomats trying to resolve the dispute between Greece and
Turkey, NATO allies, reported no firm progress Friday, and scheduled
their next session of NATO-Warsaw Pact talks for Saturday.
   The U.S. ambassador to the talks, Stephen Ledogar, said Secretary
of State George Shultz will not come to Vienna next week to wind up
the 35-nation Helsinki review conference and formally approve the
final document unless the dispute is solved.
   ``Shultz could decide at any moment that the U.S. could wait no
longer,'' Ledogar told reporters. ``Time is running out.''
   Greece and Turkey are arguing over whether to include a strategic
triangle of Turkish territory close to the Syrian border and the
disputed port of Mersin in new East-West talks on reducing
conventional forces in Europe.
   Ledogar said Greece and Turkey will have to share the bame if
their dispute unravels the arms talks and Helsinki conference
agreements.
   Polish Ambassador Wlodzimierz Konarski, speaking on behalf of the
Warsaw Pact, said late Friday, ``We have done all we can'' to reach
agreement in Vienna.
   ``The problem remaining ... is not East-West,'' he said. ``You
can't blame the East for it.''
   Konarski said the session set for Saturday was ``the final
deadline'' for advising foreign ministers whether or not to come to
Vienna next week.
   The ministers are scheduled to end the meeting in a three-day
session next week. The meeting opened in Vienna in November 1986.
   The mandate for the new arms talks is supposed to be included in
the final document of the conference.
   NATO and the Warsaw Pact gave provisional agreement to the final
document _ minus the mandate for arms talks _ on Friday after the 12
neutral and non-aligned nations at the conference worked late into
the night to resolve outstanding differences.
   Even as the East bloc informally accepted the accords, reports
came from Bulgaria of the arrest of at least seven independent human
rights activists in that nation.
   Communist authorities in Czechoslovakia also have banned a rally
planned Sunday by independent groups in Prague who want to
commemorate a student who burned himself to death in January 1969 to
protest the 1968 Soviet-led invasion.
   If finally approved, the Vienna accord contains provisions to:
   _ Allow religious education, the spread of religious literature
and charity action by churches.
   _ Resolve outstanding emigration applications within six months,
and grant visas for family reunification within one to three months.
   _ Facilitate tourism, allowing Western visitors to stay in East
bloc homes.
   _ Provide much more information needed by Western businessmen
trading in the East.
   _ Allow independent groups to monitor their governments' human
rights behavior, and the state of the environment.
   In addition, the agreement provides for the first time a formal
mechanism allowing any Helsinki signatory to take up human rights
matters with any other signatory.
   Annual conferences on human rights are planned before the next
Helsinki review conference, scheduled in Helsinki in 1992.
</TEXT>
