<FIRST>u w AM-Navy-Gulf     01-13 0214</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Navy-Gulf,210</SECOND>
<HEAD>Navy Withdrawing Another Ship From Persian Gulf</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Reagan administration has decided to
withdraw another warship from the Persian Gulf, citing the
continuing cease-fire between Iran and Iraq.
   The USS Josephus Daniels, a guided missle cruiser, was ordered
out of the Persian Gulf Friday, said Lt. Col. Keith Schneider, a
Pentagon spokesman.
   The spokesman said the move was approved by Defense Secretary
Frank C. Carlucci. He acted after a month's experience with new
convoy monitoring procedures inside the gulf, Schneider said.
   The Daniels' departure leaves 14 American Navy ships still
operating inside the Persian Gulf and another 10 deployed with an
aircraft carrier battle group nearby in the Arabian Sea. The 14
still inside the gulf include six warships, six minesweepers, one
amphibious landing ship and one flag ship.
   The United States has very gradually reduced its naval task force
inside the gulf since Iran and Iraq agreed to a truce last August in
their seven-year war. Last month, with the cease fire still holding,
the Navy ships relaxed their convoy procedures for U.S. flag tankers
to a system of very loose radio and radar monitoring.
   Before the cease fire, the Navy had been accompanying the
merchant ships on each transit of the gulf to provide maximum
protection.
</TEXT>
