<FIRST>r w AM-Reagan-Students 1stLd-Writethru a0708 01-13 0311</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Reagan-Students, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0708,310</SECOND>
<HEAD>Talks to US, Soviet Students</HEAD>
<HEAD>DESK: ADDS 3 grafs to update with Shultz, Dubinin remarks.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan told Soviet and American high
school exchange students Friday that as they get to know one
another, they will discover ``that most of the problems in this
world between countries do not exist between people.''
   Turning to the Soviet youngsters, Reagan said, ``What with our
political parties and our open elections, all of the independent
media, free labor unions, private businesses and private
organizations of every type and size, America has more different,
independent participants in our system than we have flavors of ice
cream.''
   ``And believe me we have a lot of flavors of ice cream,'' he
added.
   To the Americans, who will spend time in Soviet homes, Reagan
said, ``I think you will find that as people we share so much _
above all, we share our common humanity and our dreams of peace and
freedom and a decent life for ourselves and our children.''
   Reagan proposed the high school exchange program to Soviet leader
Mikhail Gorbachev when they met in Moscow last year and told the
students he is happy to see it under way before he leaves office.
   Later Friday, Secretary of State George P. Shultz and Soviet
ambassador Yuri Dubinin spoke to a welcoming assembly at a high
school in suburban Bethesda, Md., where 15 Soviet students will be
visiting for the next several weeks.
   ``You're part of something quite significant,'' Shultz said. He
told the Soviet students ``you have a job to do ... to learn as much
as you can'' about the United States.
   Dubinin said ``this exchange is one of the spectacular results''
from the Moscow summit, promoting ``intensified people-to-people
contacts.'' He added that the program was ``in the spirit of new
thinking'' being promoted by Gorbachev.
</TEXT>
