<FILEID>AP-NR-01-13-89 2004EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a AM-TeamstersTrial 3rdLd-Writethru a0737 01-13 0602</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Teamsters Trial, 3rd Ld - Writethru, a0737,0610</SECOND>
<HEAD>Teamsters Officials Convicted In Payroll Padding Case</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 5 grafs to CORRECT that both were convicted on once
count of conspiracy to to commit labor racketeering, sted labor racketeering;
SUBS 5th graf, `Friedman faces ..., to UPDATE with maximum penalties; picks
up 6th graf: `When the ...</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DOROTHY GAST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CLEVELAND (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two Teamsters union officials were convicted
Friday of federal charges they participated in a $700,000 payroll
padding scheme that involved hiring ``ghost employees'' who were
paid but did little or no work.
   A U.S. District Court jury found Harold Friedman, 66, a Teamsters
international vice president and president of the Ohio Council of
Teamsters, guilty on four counts: labor racketeering, conspiracy to
commit labor racketeering, embezzlement and filing false reports. He
was acquitted of one count of embezzlement and one count of filing
false reports.
   Teamsters Local 507 Recording Secretary Anthony Hughes, 52, was
found guilty of all three charges against him: labor racketeering,
conspiracy to commit labor racketeering and embezzlement, which
could carry penalties of up to 45 years in prison and a fine up of
to $60,000.
   Hughes was accused of being a ``ghost employee,'' an employee
paid for doing no work.
   Friedman faces a maximum sentence of 46 years in prison and fines
up to $70,000 on the convictions. No sentencing date has been set.
   When the verdict was announced, Hughes looked down and shook his
head, but Friedman showed no emotion. A couple of women in a crowd
of supporters cried, and another ran out of the courtroom sobbing.
   Jackie Presser, Teamsters international president until his death
of brain cancer July 9, was indicted with Friedman and Hughes on May
16, 1986, but was never tried. His illness prompted repeated delays
in the trial, which started Oct. 24 and heard from 80 witnesses.
   Court documents have indicated that Presser, also
secretary-treasurer of Local 507, and Hughes were FBI informants.
Presser's former attorney, John R. Climaco, has said Presser's
defense would have been that he was authorized by the FBI to hire
``ghost employees'' to enhance and protect his informant status.
   The prosecution contended that Presser couldn't have been
authorized to hire ``ghost employees'' because they were on the
payroll as early as 1972 and Presser didn't begin informing until
1977. Friedman's attorney said Presser was a government informant in
1963.
   Lawyers for Friedman and Hughes asked U.S. District Judge George
W. White to release documents about Presser's work as an informant,
but the judge declined, preserving the mystery over who Presser
informed on and when.
   When White declined to release the documents, Friedman and Hughes
rested their case without using the defense planned by Presser.
Friedman testified that as far as he knew, the alleged ``ghost
employees'' worked for their pay.
   The jury deliberated Wednesday afternoon and all day Thursday
before returning to court Friday, when they asked White if they
would be permitted to deliberate on Monday, Martin Luther King Jr.
Day. The judge said no.
   Friedman, in addition to being one of 16 Teamsters international
vice presidents, is president of Teamsters Joint Council 41 in
northeast Ohio and president of both Teamsters Local 507 and Bakery
Workers Local 19. The two locals share offices and have a combined
membership of about 12,000.
   A union officer must relinquish his union positions for 13 years
if convicted of certain felonies, including embezzlement, a Labor
Department official said.
   Among the prosecution witnesses were three alleged ``ghost
employees'' who testified that they were paid by the union and did
little or no work.
</TEXT>
