<FIRST>r a AM-EspositoHearing     01-13 0502</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Esposito Hearing,0522</SECOND>
<HEAD>Alleged Italian Crime Boss Says He is Innocent and Afraid</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Organizzata is cq.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRENDA C. COLEMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man prosecutors call ``the Al Capone of Italy''
claimed Friday at a deportation hearing that he was framed for
crimes in his homeland and faces certain death from mobsters or
corrupt police if he is deported.
   Carmine Esposito, 32, told Immigration Judge Craig Zerbe that the
Nuova Camorra Organizzata, a criminal clan similar to the Mafia that
operates in and around Naples, wanted him to join them but that he
rebuffed their overtures.
   Esposito testified that he once was asked to saw off a shotgun
for a customer of the auto body shop owned by his father in Acerra,
Italy.
   When he refused, the customer _ who allegedly controlled the
local police force _ had him harassed by police and eventually
framed, Esposito said.
   ``That's why I escaped from my country, because this happens
every day,'' said Esposito. If he is forced to return to Italy, he
added, ``they kill me.''
   Italian authorities charge that he ordered or committed 12
killings in his homeland from April 1982 through June 1983. Esposito
has not been convicted of those crimes.
   An attempt to have him extradited last year failed because the
charges on which the extradition warrant was based were dropped.
   Esposito, wearing handcuffs, testified for an hour Friday in a
small federal hearing room guarded by a sentry with a shotgun.
   Zerbe said he would issue a written opinion in the case next week.
   The judge ruled earlier Friday that Esposito cannot be deported
on the basis of weapons convictions in Italy, because the
convictions occurred after he was living in the United States.
   Esposito, who moved here in April 1984, still could be deported
because he entered the country on a fraudulent passport, said Craig
Oswald, a government attorney.
   Italian courts convicted Esposito of associating with criminals
and of forging license plates for cars engaged in criminal activity,
in addition to the weapons violations.
   The murder charges have not gone to trial, and warrants that were
issued for them have expired, though the charges still stand, Oswald
said.
   Esposito was arrested almost two years ago and has been
incarcerated ever since in solitary confinement at the federal
Metropolitan Correctional Center.
   A federal prosecutor at time of the arrest called Esposito the
``Al Capone of Italy.'' Esposito denied the accusation.
