<FIRST>u a AM-Reagan1stLd-Writethru a0742   01-13 0616</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Reagan 1st Ld-Writethru, a0742,640</SECOND>
<HEAD>Reagan Hopes Abortion Decision Will Be Overturned</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 3rd graf to past tense speech as delivered; INSERTS grafs
6-7, bgng, In an xxx etc., to UPDATE with Reagan comment in interview;
ADDS 2 grafs with material on award, organization.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MERRILL HARTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan said Friday night he hopes the
Supreme Court will overturn the landmark 1973 decision legalizing
abortion so ``the voice of life'' could be heard ``over all the
others.''
   Appearing at the annual dinner of the Knights of Malta, a Roman
Catholic civic organization that helps the poor, Reagan urged church
people to join forces in fighting for the rights of the unborn.
   ``Our critics call themselves pro-choice, but have they ever
stopped to think that the unborn never have a choice?'' he said.
   Referring to the 1973 Supreme Court decision legalizing abortion,
the president said, ``When Roe versus Wade goes _ as I have faith it
must _ the way of Dred Scott and `separate but equal,' a new debate
will rise in the state houses of our land.''
   ``And the voice that I believe must be heard, and in the end
shall be heard over all the others, is the voice of l ife,'' Reagan
said.
   ``The Knights can be part of that voice,'' he said.
   In an excerpt of an interview that Reagan gave to Cardinal John
O'Connor, for broadcast on O'Connor's Sunday television show here,
Reagan was asked about criticism that he shown little sensitivity to
the care of children after they're born.
   ``Well, some of the people have said that are the same ones who,
for example in the Congress, have supported a bill with regard to
child care, that the goverment would require a grandmother to be
licensed in order to be given the care of her own grandchild,'' he
replied. ``This is just ridiculous.''
   The president replied by repeating his criticism of the proposed
Act for Better Child Care, circulating in Congress.
   Reagan said that the bill would require a grandmother to be
licensed to care for her grand child.
   It was Reagan's last official out-of-town business trip. The
president and his wife, Nancy, will travel to Camp David, Md.,
Saturday, and the pair will remain at the White House next week
until Reagan attends President-elect Bush's inauguration on Friday.
   Reagan said that while he may be leaving office, he ``won't leave
the battle.''
   ``In just seven days, I will lay down the mantle of this great
office the American people have bestowed upon me,'' Reagan said. ``I
won't leave the battle. As long as there is breath in me, I will
fight for the principles in which I believe.''
   ``But if I may, in this moment of leaving office make two special
requests of you. The first is that you prepare now to be part of
that voice of life in the great debate ahead. And the second, that
you help America find a way out of the trap of the welfare state.
Help it find a way to open the doors of hope and love, open them as
no state, any state, ever can, for those in need. Help open the
promises of this land of shining opportunity to all,'' he said.
   Reagan was presented with the organization's highest honor _ the
Grand Cross of Merit Special Class _ ``for his vigorous defense of
the pro-life cause and his strong support of traditional Christian
family values.''.
   The Knights of Malta order is a worldwide philanthropic
organization which seeks to serve ``the least of thy brethren.'' The
organization is comprised of 10,000 members in 40 countries and is
headquartered in Rome.
</TEXT>
