<FIRST>u i AM-CostaRica-Hull 1stLd-Writethru   01-13 0713</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Costa Rica-Hull, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0707,0731</SECOND>
<HEAD>Indiana Man Who Aided Contras Arrested For Drugs, Espionage</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with eight grafs to UPDATE with Hull's lawyer saying charges
filed, comment; picks up 10th pvs, `All the...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JUAN MALTES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN JOSE, Costa Rica (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   John Hull, an American linked to an
illegal arms-supply network aiding the Nicaraguan rebels, was being
held Friday under charges of drug trafficking and violating Costa
Rican national security, his lawyer said.
   Attorney Ciro Casas Zamora said Hull was formally charged in the
4th Federal District Court and was being held in the San Sebastian
Jail, where he will remain until a Monday bail hearing.
   A source in the Office of Judicial Investigations said on
condition of anonymity that Hull was arrested Thursday for
investigation into charges of drug and weapons trafficking and
spying for the U.S.-backed Contras fighting the Nicaraguan
government.
   The Office of Judicial Investigations acted after residents near
his farm on the Nicaraguan border denounced activities by Hull that
were seen as possibly endangering relations between Costa Rica and
Nicaragua's Sandinista government, the source said.
   Hull's lawyer called his client's arrest ``politically
motivated'' and said he plans to appeal.
   ``This is a simple case of political persecution in which the
government of President (Oscar) Arias is trying to defend the
political interests of the Sandinista government and the Costa Rican
Marxists,'' Casas Zamora said.
   A U.S. embassy official said on condition of anonymity that an
American consular official was seeking permission to visit Hull.
   The official dismissed suggestions that the arrest was
politically motivated, contending that the Office of Judicial
Investigations has an honorable reputation.
   All the embassy can do, the official said, is ensure Hull has
access to a lawyer and that he is treated the same as a Costa Rican
citizen.
   Hull, a former Indiana resident who is about 69 years old, has
lived in Costa Rica for 20 years and has said he is a Costa Rican
citizen. He has acknowledged he supported the Contras and has said
that in the past he let them use his property in Los Chiles, 81
miles northwest of San Jose.
   F. Andy Messing, who heads the conservative National Defense
Foundation in Washington, said he and Rep. David Dreier, R-Calif.,
met with Hull during a fact-finding trip to Central America last
month.
   He said Hull assured them he stopped assisting the Contras when
the Iran-Contra case broke. In the case, Reagan administration
officials sent arms to Iran for money to be sent to the Contras.
   Hull said in 1986 interviews that authorities twice raided his
home looking for evidence of rumored gun running and drug smuggling.
The searches turned up nothing, he said.
   Hull's wife, Mariella, of Patoka, Ind., confirmed that her
husband was being held, the Evansville (Ind.) Courier reported
Friday.
   Mrs. Hull would not reveal details about the case, but said she
was informed by telephone that her husband was arrested, the
newspaper said.
   Witnesses testifying before Congress on illegal arms shipments to
the anti-Sandinista rebels have said Hull's ranch was a way station
for gun smugglers and cocaine traffickers.
   Hull was not among 13 men indicted in September in Miami on
charges of running an illegal arms network for the Contras. Reports
said Hull was granted immunity by the special prosecutor in the case.
   ``I would be extremely upset if that were true,'' Jack Blum,
counsel on the case for the Senate Foreign Relations Committee, said
after the indictments. ``Witnesses say (Hull) was all over the place
in this case.''
   Convicted cocaine pilot Gary Betzner has testified that Hull once
met his plane when it landed on the ranch to exchange Contra arms
for Colombian cocaine.
   Hull has denied any connection to drug trafficking.
   Hull also was among 29 people named in a civil suit filed last
year by two journalists. Tony Avirgan filed the suit with his wife,
Martha Honey, after being wounded in a 1984 bombing blamed on the
defendants.
   A U.S. district judge in Miami ruled in favor of the defendants.
He ruled the plaintiffs failed to prove that a wide-ranging
conspiracy was behind the news conference bombing in Nicaragua that
injured Avirgan. Eight people were killed but the apparent target,
Contra leader Eden Pastora, only was wounded.
</TEXT>
