<FIRST>b w AM-BodyIdentified     01-13 0291</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Body Identified,300</SECOND>
<HEAD>URGENT</HEAD>
<HEAD>Body Returned By Libya is Ribas-Dominicci</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-US-Libya</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NORMAN BLACK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Military Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The individual whose remains were turned over
to the United States on Friday by Libya has been identified as the
pilot of an F-111 bomber which took part in the raid over Libya in
1986, Pentagon sources said Friday night.
   The officials, speaking only on condition of anonymity, said
Libya had been wrong in tentatively identifying the remains as those
of Capt. Paul Lorence.
   Rather, the sources continued, the remains have now been
positively identified as those of Maj. Fernando Ribas-Dominicci, of
Utuado, Puerto Rico.
   Ribas-Dominicci, who was 33 at the time of his death, was the
pilot of the lone F-111 bomber that was lost in the bombing raid on
Tripoli. Lorence, 31, of San Francisco was the other U.S. airman in
the only plane lost during the April 15, 1986 raid.
   At the time he disappeared during the raid, Ribas-Dominicci held
the rank of captain. He was posthumously promoted to the rank of
major.
   ``A forensic identification has been performed and reveals that
the remains are those of Ribas-Dominicci _ and not those of Capt.
Lorence,'' said one Pentagon source.
   ``We just got the word that it's not the one they had claimed it
was. We don't know if they also ever found the remains of Capt.
Lorence,'' said the source.
   The official said the Pentagon would not have any other details
Friday night on arrangements for Ribas-Dominicci's funeral.
   The F-111 was one of 18 F-111s that flew from Great Britain to
bomb Libya in retaliation for what President Reagan said was Libya's
involvement in the bombing of a West German disco frequented by
American service personnel.
</TEXT>
