<FIRST>r a AM-AbortionProtest 1stLd-Writethru a0638 01-13 0366</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Abortion Protest, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0638,0373</SECOND>
<HEAD>Anti-Abortion Group Defies Judge; Blocks Clinic Entrance</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with 5 grafs to UPDATE arrests, totals; picks up 5th graf:
`Group spokesman ...</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   About 1,000 members of an anti-abortion group
defied a federal judge's order Friday and twice blocked the entrance
to a Planned Parenthood clinic.
   Demonstrators from Operation Rescue gathered at about 7:15 a.m.
in front of Planned Parenthood's Margaret Sanger Center in
Manhattan, snarling morning rush-hour traffic. A few abortion rights
demonstrators also showed up.
   The clinic was not able to open until 10:15 a.m. because the
demonstrators blocked the building's entrance, a Planned Parenthood
spokeswoman said.
   Police moved in to make some arrests and protesters who were not
arrested left the scene en masse. But they returned several hours
later and lay down, blocking the clinic's front door.
   Police moved in again. A total of 176 people were arrested and
charged with disorderly conduct and resisting arrest. They refused
to give their names and were held for arraignment, said Officer
Edward Feeney, a police spokesman.
   Group spokesman Harry Brock said more protests were planned for
Saturday.
   U.S. District Judge Robert Ward on Tuesday issued a permanent
injunction against the Binghamton-based group, forbidding members to
obstruct access to health clinics in the area or harass clients
trying to get inside. The order calls for a fine of $25,000 a day
for violations.
   Ward issued a temporary restraining order against the group in
May and ordered organizers to tell police where they would be
demonstrating so police could place officers at the site. When they
failed to do so, the judge fined the group $50,000 for violating his
order and $19,000 to pay police overtime.
   The group did not inform police of their protest site Friday, so
officers in buses followed demonstrators to their destination.
   The action against the group was brought by the National
Organization for Women and other abortion rights groups.
   The judge ordered that the $50,000 fine be donated to NOW and the
other groups.
   Operation Rescue spokesman Randall Terry said Thursday that the
group was being discriminated against because of politically
unpopular views. It has not paid any fines yet.
</TEXT>
