<FIRST>r a AM-BRF--PitBulls     01-13 0181</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--Pit Bulls,0185</SECOND>
<HEAD>New Rules Could Wipe Out Pit Bull Population</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The estimated 10,000 pit bulls in the city could
slowly disapppear if the Board of Health succeeds in requiring the
terriers be registered, photographed and tattooed.
   The proposed Health Code amendment, which could be in effect by
March, would require photographs, identifying tattoos, mandatory
registration and proof that the animal had been spayed or neutered.
   The proposed regulations also call for owners to be at least 18
years old and that they carry $100,000 in liability insurance.
   The rules would eventually ban all pit bulls from the city after
those who are registered die or are moved out.
   ``If a pup was born after the registration period, that pup would
have to be taken out of the city or disposed of,'' said Dr. Stephen
Joseph, the city's health commissioner.
   Pit bulls were cited in 422 bite cases involving humans between
November 1987 and September, said Health Department counsel Irwin
Davison. That's about 14 percent of the 3,057 bite cases reported in
that period, he said.
</TEXT>
