<FIRST>r i AM-Salvador-Rebels     01-13 0309</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Salvador-Rebels,0319</SECOND>
<HEAD>Guerrillas Advise Civilians to Avoid Military Targets</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN SALVADOR, El Salvador (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Leftist guerrillas battling the
U.S.-backed government vowed on Friday to increase attacks in this
capital city and advised civilians to stay clear of possible
military targets.
   The rebels, broadcasting on the clandestine Radio Farabundo
Marti, told street vendors and passers-by to avoid the capital's
military bases and the U.S. Embassy. The guerrillas consider
Washington the sponsor of what they call the counterinsurgency
campaign against them.
   A 9-year-old civil war has killed an estimated 65,000 people,
most of them civilians.
   Urban commandos of the Marxist-led Farabundo Marti National
Liberation Front increased actions last year, bringing what had been
a primarily rural war to the capital. In November and December, they
attacked three major armed forces installations in San Salvador,
causing about 40 casualties among military personnel.
   Two civilians were killed and about 40 wounded in the attacks,
which employed vehicles equipped with explosive charges.
   The government considers such attacks terrorist acts. But the
rebels say the vehicles serve as ``mobile artillery'' _ launching
platforms for rudimentary mortars. They say the explosion in the car
is a charge that catapults the bomb toward the military target.
   The explosion of the launching charge destroys the vehicle and
creates a shock wave that shatters surrounding windows and in some
cases has killed and wounded passers-by.
   Also Friday, authorities of the National University said they
have received death threats, and blamed a new death squad that
announced its formation last month.
   Bombs exploded Thursday night at the homes of the dean and
assistant dean of the university's humanities college. The bombs
damaged property but caused no injuries.
   University rector Luis Argueta Antillon, in a press conference,
blamed an anti-communist terror group for placing the bombs and the
death threats.
   Rightists consider the university a haven for leftist
revolutionaries.
</TEXT>
