<FIRST>r i AM-Nicaragua     01-13 0244</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Nicaragua,0252</SECOND>
<HEAD>Opposition Leader Denies Charges that U.S. Will Finance Sunday Protest</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RODOLFO GARCIA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANAGUA, Nicaragua (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The secretary-general of the opposition
Democratic Nicaraguan Coordinate on Friday denied government charges
that the U.S. Embassy is financing a Sunday protest march.
   Official Sandinista government news media have ``mounted a smear
campaign against the opposition because they lack the ideological
bases to face it,'' Roger Guevara said.
   ``The Sandinistas use these methods to try and cloud their
administrative and political collapse,'' he said.
   The pro-government newspapers El Nuevo Diario and Barricada,
among other Sandinista media, said opposition political leaders
received huge sums of money, including $25,000 from the U.S. Embassy
in Managua, to pay for the Sunday protest.
   The U.S. government in the past has financed opposition groups in
Nicaragua, including the anti-Sandinista guerrillas known as Contras.
   Without specifying amounts, Guevara acknowledged that his group
has received funds from European sources. He did not elaborate.
   The opposition leader said the march will commemorate the 11th
anniversary of the killing of journalist Pedro Joaquin Chamorro
Cardenal, who was assasinated by the administration of former
President Anastasio Somoza. The leftist Sandinista government has
been in power since overthrowing Somoza in 1979.
   ``But at the same time it will be a demonstration in protest of
the misery, the need and the repression'' in Nicaragua, Guevara said.
   Fourteen opposition groups of varying ideologies on the left and
right planned to participate in the march.
