<FIRST>r a AM-SinksTrial     01-13 0332</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Sinks Trial,0341</SECOND>
<HEAD>Man Convicted Of Killing His Wife, Burying Body In Office Building</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DAYTON, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man accused of killing his wife and burying
her body under concrete in the newspaper building where they worked
was found guilty of murder Friday.
   Theodore P. Sinks, 40, was convicted after more than eight hours
of jury deliberation. He was sentenced to 15 years to life in prison
and fined him $15,000.
   Sinks was charged with murder in the death of his wife, Judy, 44,
whose body was found in a concrete-encased pit at the Dayton Daily
News, where she was a clerical worker and he was a building
superintendent.
   Her body was unearthed in April by police acting on an anonymous
tip more than five months after Sinks reported her missing.
   The body was found in a seventh-floor utility room, an area that
Sinks supervised, in a small pit used as an overflow reservoir for
the heating and cooling system.
   Prosecutor Herbert Jacobson told the jury that Sinks had an
explosive temper and wanted out of his marriage, so he strangled his
wife, put her body in a 55-gallon drum, took the drum to the utility
room and buried her.
   ``He put her where nobody, nobody would ever know it,'' Jacobson
said.
   Prosecutors also cited the testimony of a jail worker who
testified that Sinks told him last August he had done something ``in
a fit of anger'' that he could not undo and that he had decided to
plead innocent by reason o insanity.
   Defense attorney Thomas Hansen said prosecutors had failed to
prove guilt beyond a reasonable doubt, and attacked the credibility
of an anonymous source who led police to the utility room pit.
   ``They don't know who he is, where he is or what he is,'' Hansen
said. ``There's a Mr. X out there someplace that knows a lot about
this.'' Hansen said Sinks could have fled if he had been guilty, but
did not do so.
</TEXT>
