<FIRST>r i AM-Obit-Little     01-13 0201</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Obit-Little,0207</SECOND>
<HEAD>Textron Founder Royal Little Dead at 92</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NASSAU, Bahamas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Royal B. Little, who founded Textron Inc.
and became the father of the modern conglomerate, has died at age 92.
   Little died Thursday after a brief illness at his winter home in
the Bahamas. He spent summers in Narragansett, R.I.
   His son, Arthur, who was with Little when he died, said his
father requested that no funeral service be held. ``He said he'd
like people to think he'd gone on a long trip,'' Arthur Little said.
   Royal Little built Providence, R.I.-based Textron from Special
Yarns Corp., which he founded in 1923. He retired as Textron board
chairman in 1961.
   Little overcame a lack of financing by using charitable trusts to
finance some of Textron's early acquisitions.
   In the 1960s, Little's personal fortune was estimated at $20
million, but he was known to borrow money for his train fare to
Providence from a friend waiting with him at the Kingston, R.I.,
station.
   After retiring from Textron, Little built Narragansett Capital
Corp. as the nation's largest publicly-held investment company
specializing in small businesses. He also was board chairman of
Amtel Inc., Bevis Industries and American Television and
Communications Corp.
</TEXT>
