<FIRST>r a AM-SoulScam     01-13 0467</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soul Scam,0482</SECOND>
<HEAD>Fortuneteller, Companion Convicted After Promises To Raise Souls</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PEORIA, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A vanished fortuneteller and her companion
were convicted of duping an elderly woman out of $150,000 after
telling her that the souls of her two dead husbands could be raised
from hell to heaven.
   Lena ``Marie'' Wilson, 53, and Joe Marks, 38, were not around
Thursday night to hear the verdicts. They disappeared last April and
the trial was held without them.
   ``Lena Wilson and Joe Marks perpetrated a scam on Jeane Dunton
the likes of which Peoria County has never seen,'' said Assistant
State's Attorney Angela Madison.
   Ms. Wilson, who operated a fortunetelling business in Peoria and
Galesburg since 1983, told Mrs. Dunton that she had the power to
raise the souls of her two dead husbands from hell to heaven,
multiply the widow's money and keep her, her two daughters and her
grandson from going blind.
   Mrs. Dunton, 69, said she believed Ms. Wilson's lies. The jury
determined Marks, Ms. Wilson's live-in companion, also helped
conceal the scam. Mrs. Dunton said during 20 months, she gave up
$150,000 in cash and property.
   Ms. Wilson was convicted of theft and conspiracy and Marks was
convicted of conspiracy. Judge James Bumgarner will sentence them
Feb. 24.
   Ms. Wilson claimed she had the power to remove a curse placed on
Mrs. Dunton and her family 44 years earlier by her first husband's
former girlfriend, Mrs. Dunton testified during the bizarre,
three-day trial.
   Mrs. Dunton said she turned over thousands of dollars in cash at
a time, supplied Ms. Wilson with new clothes and gave her a crystal
chandelier, according to testimony.
   Mrs. Dunton also bought a new Cadillac, which Ms. Wilson said she
needed to store the evil that she had exorcised from Mrs. Dunton,
according to testimony.
   The car eventually was transferred to Marks, Mrs. Dunton said.
   Not until last January, after a three-month investigation by
Illinois police, did Mrs. Dunton realize she was duped, she said.
   Last Feb. 8, police arrested Marks at the couple's Galesburg
home. Ms. Wilson was stopped in western Missouri several days later
with a bag filled with about $150,000 in jewelry.
   Ms. Wilson and Marks each posted bonds of up to $60,000 to remain
free pending trial in Mrs. Dunton's case.
   After a pre-trial hearing in April, Ms. Wilson fled the
courthouse moments before police were to arrest her on charges that
she stole from three other women. Marks also fled the area at the
same time, police said.
   Police said authorities across the United States and Canada have
been alerted to search for Ms. Wilson, her daughter, Ann Corricelli,
25, and Marks.
   Ms. Corricelli also faces a theft charge in the Dunton case and
several more in unrelated cases, but she not been arrested.
</TEXT>
