<HEAD>Former Redskin Selling Ring</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former Washington Redskin player Alvin Garrett,
who says he hasn't had a job in at least a month, has taken out a
classified newspaper ad to sell the ring earned from the 1983 Super
Bowl.
   Garrett, a wide receiver who caught a touchdown pass in the
Redskins' 27-17 victory over the Miami Dolphins in January 1983, put
an ad in the Washington Post earlier this week under ``Antiques and
Collectibles.''
   He said he's been offered $20,000, but wants more. ``It'll
climb,'' he said, adding that he is seeking $50,000.
   Garrett said he has only worn the diamond-and-ruby ring three or
four times and only displays it upon request. He claimed he's kept
in a safe for the past few years.
   ``It's just a ring,'' he said. ``When I got it, it was good to
have, but there's more to life than a gold band and a diamond...You
need to have enough money to have shelter, a car to drive, food to
eat.''
   Garrett, who now spends much of his time at two local places of
worship, said the sale would also help him spread his ``ministry.''
   ``To me, (the ring) is an earthly crown; I'm shooting for the
heavenly crown,'' he said.
   Garrett said he ran the ad to see what kind of response he would
get, and left open the possibility that he may not sell it.
   ``It's not guaranteed I'll sell the ring,'' he said. ``I might
not and I might. But if I do sell it to someone, I'd sell it to
someone who'll keep it, not bust it up.''
