<FIRST>u f AM-SportVehicles 1stLd-Writethru   01-13 0190</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Sport Vehicles, 1st Ld-Writethru,0194</SECOND>
<HEAD>Classification Change Considered</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: CORRECTS typo in Samurai in lede, and typo in final graf.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Treasury Department has taken under
advisement a Customs Service decision to classify imported sport
utility vehicles like the Suzuki Samurai, and most small vans as
trucks, subjecting them to duty rates 10 times higher than those for
cars, an agency spokesman said Thursday night.
   The spokesman, who requested anonymity, said the department
decided Thursday to review the ruling, will assess the case and make
a legal decision.
   Last week, Deputy Customs Commissioner Michael Lane said that in
the past, these vehicles sometimes had been classified as cars, upon
which a 2.5 percent duty is imposed, and at other times as trucks,
subject to a 25 percent duty.
   The deciding factor often was whether the vehicles were fitted
with back seats and other amenities.
   Lane said auto industry officials have estimated the ruling could
affect 100,000 to 250,000 or more vehicles, many of which would be
switched from the car to truck category and could net the government
hundred of millions of dollars in higher tariffs.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890113-0236 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-01-13-89 0234EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-BusinessHighlights 2Takes   01-13 0503</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Business Highlights, 2 Takes,0525</SECOND>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Drexel Burnham Lambert Inc. has offered the
chairman's job to the government official who first ordered an
intensive fraud probe of the financial giant more than two years ago.
   John S. R. Shad, former chairman of the Securities and Exchange
Commission and now ambassador to the Netherlands, confirmed through
a spokesman at the U.S. embassy there Thursday he had been
approached by Drexel about becoming chairman, but did not say
whether he would accept.
   The nation's fifth-largest securities firm also said it had asked
another ex-SEC chairman, Roderick M. Hills, husband of U.S. trade
representative-designate Carla Hills, about serving on its board of
directors.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>MANCHESTER, N.H. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Northeast Utilities, New England's
largest power company has offered to buy struggling Public Service
Co. of New Hampshire in a bid that values PSNH at nearly $2 billion.
   PSNH, forced into reorganization under federal bankruptcy law a
year ago because of debts from the stalled Seabrook nuclear power
plant, said Thursday it welcomed the offer.
   Under the Northeast Utilities proposal, PSNH's 36 percent share
of Seabrook would be spun off into a separate company to be owned by
PSNH's unsecured creditors.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Allegheny International Inc. announced plans to
cancel a merger agreement with a New York securities firm in favor
of a deal to sell its core Oster-Sunbeam division to Black &amp; Decker
Corp. for $260 million.
   The proposed sale is the centerpiece of an independent plan of
reorganization that management intends to present in bankruptcy
court.
   It had previously tentatively agreed to a merger proposal from
the securities firm Donaldson, Lufkin &amp; Jenrette Inc.
</TEXT>
