<SECOND>PM-Business Highlights, 1st Add,0523</SECOND>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. airlines began testing for faulty engine
warning systems in Boeing 737 airliners similar to one that crashed
in England. A spokesman for one U.S. carrier said 80 percent of its
737s had been tested with no problems found.
   Officials of other airlines said Thursday they were complying
with the testing as a precautionary measure but expected to find no
faulty wiring of fire and vibration warning lights that might
mislead a pilot into shutting down his only good engine if the other
one showed problems.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Employers increasingly need to tap the growing
pool of older workers to avoid major labor shortages but such
efforts are stymied because the elderly face many disincentives to
work beyond retirement age, say two government studies said.
   The reports released Thursday said the need to retain, and in
some cases retrain, elderly workers is particularly acute for highly
skilled jobs.
   One report was requested by Labor Secretaty Ann McLaughlin to
study trends among older workers and to suggest ways to encourage
later retirement. The second report was requested by Congress.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hazeltine Corp. has been suspended from bidding
on or receiving any new government contracts because of its guilty
plea last week in a federal probe of defense contract fraud, the
Pentagon said.
   The suspension also applies to two former executives of the firm,
the Pentagon said Thursday.
   Hazeltine, based in Greenlawn, N.Y., is a subsidiary of the
Emerson Electric Co. Inc. The suspension of contracting rights
applies only to Hazeltine and not other units of Emerson.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>PURCHASE, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   International Paper Co., which posted a
record 85 percent increase in 1988 profit, plans to launch a
takeover bid for Europe's largest paper maker.
   Details of the friendly tender offer for Aussedat-Rey SA,
Europe's leading manufacturer of photocopy paper, were not disclosed
in Thursday's announcement.
   Officials of the Paris-based company declined to comment on
whether the company would accept the offer.
</TEXT>
