<DOCNO> AP890113-0241 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-01-13-89 0317EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-PSNH-Northeast Bjt   01-13 0741</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-PSNH-Northeast, Bjt,0767</SECOND>
<HEAD>New England's Biggest Utility Offers $2 Billion for PSNH</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WENDY MITMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANCHESTER, N.H. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Public Service Co. of New Hampshire,
forced into bankruptcy court by debts from the stalled Seabrook
nuclear power plant, is pondering a bid from Northeast Utilities
that values the struggling PSNH at nearly $2 billion.
   PSNH's initial reaction Thursday to the bid from New England's
largest power company was positive.
   ``We are glad to see that Northeast Utilities, a serious,
qualified bidder, has valued PSNH Company of New Hampshire at a
level it describes as in excess of $2 billion,'' PSNH President John
Duffett said in a statement.
   Duffett said the PSNH board would consider the offer, which must
also be approved by federal and state regulators and PSNH's
creditors.
   Under the Northeast Utilities proposal, PSNH's 36 percent share
of Seabrook would be spun off into a separate company to be owned by
PSNH's unsecured creditors.
   Northeast Utilities pledged to buy Seabrook power through a
subsidiary which would be a New Hampshire-based utility owning
PSNH's assets other than Seabrook, Northeast Utilities officials
said.
   Northeast Utilities said it would pay $1.2 billion for the
non-Seabrook assets. The company valued the pledge to buy Seabrook
power at $750 million, making the total deal worth nearly $2 billion.
   PSNH has said about 10 companies have expressed interest in
acquiring all or part of the utility, including New England Electric
System; a pairing of Central Maine Power Co. and Central Vermont
PSNH Co.; and New Hampshire Electric Cooperative.
   A New England Electric spokeswoman said officials would not
comment on the Northeast Utilities proposal before reviewing it in
detail. Comment was not immediately obtained from any other possible
bidders.
   Seabrook, a $5.8 billion, 1,150-megawatt plant finished in 1986,
remains idle for lack of a federal operating license. PSNH went into
reorganization under Chapter 11 of the federal bankruptcy code last
year after state courts refused to allow the utility to pass on the
costs of Seabrook to ratepayers.
   PSNH is the biggest stakeholder in Seabrook; Northeast Utilities
owns 4 percent of the plant.
   PSNH, its creditors and the state are negotiating a financial
restructuring of the utility, but the talks have been punctuated by
harsh rhetoric and charges of bad faith.
   In his statement Thursday, Duffet criticized state officials for
failing to recognize a value anywhere near the range proposed by
Northeast Utilities.
   Northeast Utilities officials said their proposed buyout would
provide PSNH with an opportunity to speedily resolve virtually all
outstanding issues in the reorganization.
   Northeast Utilities President William Ellis said the state and
PSNH are ``now far apart on reaching a settlement,'' with the
utility wanting more money to settle up with creditors and the state
refusing to agree to the high rates being proposed by creditors.
   ``We firmly believe we can be the catalyst ... to bring
ratepayers and creditors together,'' Ellis said.
   Ellis urged PSNH to incorporate the proposal into its own
bankruptcy reorganization plan. If PSNH declines, Northeast
Utilities will press its case with PSNH's creditors and New
Hampshire officials, Ellis said.
   Northeast Utilities, based in Hartford, Conn., serves more than 1
million customers in Connecticut and 185,000 customers in
Massachusetts through subsidiaries, the Connecticut Light and Power
Co. and Western Massachusetts Electric Co.
   The company's electricity sales in the past year were more than
$2 billion, compared with PSNH's sales of under $600 million.
   The Northeast Utilities offer provides more money than had been
previously available for stockholders and creditors, and protects
PSNH's ratepayers from huge increases.
   Under the proposal, first-mortgage and general and refunding
mortgage bondholders _ who have been receiving interest since PSNH
filed for bankruptcy _ would recover their full principal, about
$440 million, Ellis said.
   Third-mortgage bondholders would receive all of their principal _
just over $400 million _ but substantially less than the total
interest that has accrued.
   Steven Davis, president of Consolidated Utilities and
Communications Inc., a substantial third-mortgage bondholders group,
said Thursday it was too early to comment on the proposal. However,
he said his group's position has been ``that as secured creditors
you deserve 100 percent of capital and accrued interest.''
   The unsecured creditors who would hold the Seabrook assets would
receive about $70 million in cash from Northeast Utilities and $75
million in preferred stock from the Northeast Utilities subsidiary.
Northeast Utilities would also pay them $165 million to pay for
Seabrook until it wins an operating license.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
