<DOCNO> AP890113-0243 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-01-13-89 0325EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-AlleghenyInternational     01-13 0488</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Allegheny International,0506</SECOND>
<HEAD>Plans to End Merger Pact, Sell Oster-Sunbeam to Black &amp; Decker</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Allegheny International Inc. has asked a
federal bankruptcy judge for permission to sell its keystone
Oster-Sunbeam division to Black &amp; Decker Corp. as part of a plan
management will devise to reorganize the troubled consumer products
company.
   Creditors, however, asked U.S. Bankruptcy Judge Joseph Cosetti
Thursday for permission to file their own plan to reorganize
Allegheny International, which has been operating under Chapter 11
of the federal bankruptcy code for nearly a year.
   At a hearing before Cosetti, unsecured creditors lashed out at
management for the rejection Wednesday of a merger agreement with
Donaldson, Lufkin &amp; Jenrette.
   ``This debtor is inept. It has no credibility,'' said Robert
Sable, representing Allegheny International's unsecured creditors.
   Lawyers representing unsecured creditors literally stood in line
to tell Cosetti they had no faith in the Allegheny International
board's ability to find an acceptable reorganization plan.
   Allegheny International asked Cosetti to allow the firm to sell
Oster-Sunbeam, a maker of irons, shavers and other small appliances,
to Black &amp; Decker for $260 million.
   In conjunction with that proposal, management said it has entered
an agreement under which its recent adversary, Spear, Leeds &amp;
Kellog, would help finance the management reorganization plan. The
New York firm had been battling the board as head of a shareholders'
committee.
   The board rejected the Donaldson, Lufkin &amp; Jenrette deal because
the securities firm struck a private bargain with a rival bidder,
the Paul S. Levy banker group, to carve up the company between them.
   Donaldson, Lufkin &amp; Jenrette planned to sell the lawn furniture
and gas grill business to Levy for $250 million and keep the rest of
the company, including the Oster-Sunbeam division.
   The board also objected to Donaldson, Lufkin &amp; Jenrette altering
its takeover proposal by lowering its common equity contribution to
the reorganized company by $30 million.
   Allegheny International said it would ask the bankruptcy court
for sanctions against Donaldson, Lufkin &amp; Jenrette and the Levy
group.
   The board announced a tentative merger agreement with Donaldson,
Lufkin &amp; Jenrette last November after the major creditor groups
scuttled an earlier management reorganization plan and forced the
board to offer the company for sale.
   Cosetti deferred ruling on any of the requests. He had set
Thursday as a deadline for management to choose among the bidders'
reorganization plans.
   Management's sole right to submit a plan expires today.
   It was not immediately clear what anti-trust considerations might
be raised by the merger of the Sunbeam-Oster division and Black &amp;
Decker.
   Allegheny International would use the proceeds of the
Oster-Sunbeam sale to reduce debt and emerge with a company with
about $500 million in annual sales from its remaining businesses,
which include gas grills, lawn furniture, weather instruments,
electric blankets and scales.
   Black &amp; Decker, based in Towson, Md., manufactures and sells
power tools, accessories, household appliances and lawn care
equipment.
</TEXT>
