<DOCNO> AP890113-0245 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-01-13-89 0843EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-Korea-Trade     01-13 0134</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Korea-Trade,0139</SECOND>
<HEAD>Government Plans To Expand Imports To Hold Down Trade Surplus</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The South Korean government has
promised to expand its imports whenever the country's current
account trade surplus exceeds quarterly targerts.
   Government officials said the United States was mostly likely to
benefit from the plan, which was contained in an annual economic
report presented to President Roh Tae-woo Thursday.
   Korea's trade surplus with the United States was estimated at
around $9 billion last year, down from nearly $10 billion in 1987.
The United States is Korea's biggest market, taking about 35 percent
of Korean exports which totaled $60.6 billion last year.
   The government said it will set up special task forces to remove
various non-tariff barriers and prepare a schedule for opening the
market for farm products.
</TEXT>
