<FIRST>r f PM-TradingScheme     01-13 0303</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Trading Scheme,0314</SECOND>
<HEAD>Six Board Of Trade Members Get Fines, Suspensions In Wig Case</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Six traders have been suspended from conducting
transactions at the Chicago Board of Trade and fined thousands of
dollars each for engaging in fraudulent practices.
   CBOT disciplinary authorities found all six had engaged in a
scheme involving a trader who wore a wig and fake identification to
conduct transactions, CBOT officials announced Thursday.
   The traders were linked through federal court testimony last
summer to the wig scheme masterminded by veteran trader Thompson B.
Sanders, who was sentenced in November to six years in prison.
   The disciplinary action, imposed Dec. 16 but announced this week,
followed revelations by prosecutors in the Sanders probe.
   The suspensions ranged from 15 days to 10 years and fines were
between $5,000 and $50,000 each.
   Investigators found all six engaged in ``fraud and dishonorable
and dishonest conduct'' and ``reckless and unbusinesslike dealings
inconsistent with just and equitable principles of trade.''
   Sanders, 45, was found guilty of setting up the scheme in which
Daniel Dewey, another former trader, donned a wig and used stolen
trader badges and jackets to gain access to a restricted area near
the Treasury Bond trading pit.
   The government claimed that because of the disguises, Sanders,
Dewey and others in the scheme were able to claim $30,000 in trading
profits without detection. Dewey was sentenced to five years in
prison.
   The six suspended traders were identified as David Schremser, Dan
Hayes, Patrick Bratta, Scott Bremner, Patrick Sutor and Robert
Kinkade. Schremser and Hayes testified under grants of immunity from
prosecutors at Sanders' trial, the CBOT said.
   The CBOT board of governors levied the stiffest penalty against
Bremner, who was suspended for 10 years, fined $50,000 and barred
from associating with other members of the exchange during the
suspension.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
