<FIRST>d f BC-EEC-BilateralPanel     01-13 0197</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-EEC-Bilateral Panel,0202</SECOND>
<HEAD>EEC Gives Cool Response To U.S. Proposal For Disputes Panel</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The European Economic Community has
given a cool response to a proposal made by a group of U.S.
congressmen to set up a bilateral panel to arbitrate trade disputes
between the United States and the EEC.
   A spokesman for EEC's External Relations Commissioner Frans
Andriessen, said Friday that the EEC was ``reluctant'' about the
plan.
   The EEC was more interested in strengthening the procedures of
the General Agreement on Tariffs and Trade (GATT), the Geneva-based
international trade body which normally arbitrates in trade
disputes, he said.
   The spokesman, who asked not to be named, said the U.S.
congressmen had discussed the issue with Andriessen on Thursday in
Brussels. He said that the congressmen suggested the panel could
arbitrate in what they called ``relatively minor'' disputes such as
the current quarrel about the EEC's ban on hormones in beef.
   In retaliation for the ban, the United States imposed 100 percent
tariffs affecting $100 million worth of trade in EEC goods. The EEC
will decide whether to take countermeasures at a meeting of its
foreign ministers at the end of January.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
