<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market was mixed today, faced with news
of a smaller-than-expected rise in retail sales last month.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials slipped .53 to 2,221.79
in the first half hour of trading.
   Gainers outnumbered losers by about 5 to 3 in nationwide trading
of New York Stock Exchange-listed issues, with 569 up, 344 down and
518 unchanged.
   Volume on the Big Board came to 21.60 million shares as of 10
a.m. on Wall Street.
   The Commerce Department reported that retail sales increased 0.2
percent in December, a gain much smaller than most analysts had
estimated. Stock traders seemed uncertain at first how to respond to
the news.
   In the bond market, investors reacted positively, sending
interest rates lower on the report's suggestion that economic
activity was a bit less robust than had been thought.
   But the dollar declined in foreign exchange after the figures
were made public.
   Brokers said blue-chip stocks also were faced with some selling
to cash in on the gains that have recently carried the market to its
highest levels since the October 1987 crash.
   Among actively traded blue chips, USX was up ] at 31]; General
Electric held steady at 45, and International Business Machines
dropped \ to 122~.
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks rose
.23 to 159.49. At the American Stock Exchange, the market value
index was up .20 at 315.20.
   On Thursday the Dow Jones industrial average climbed 15.89 points
to 2,222.32 _ less than 25 points shy of its close of 2,246.74 on
Oct. 16, 1987, just before it took a 508-point drop on Black Monday.
   Advancing issues outnumbered declines by more than 3 to 2 on the
NYSE, with 899 up, 569 down and 509 unchanged.
   Big Board volume totaled 183 million shares, up from 148.95
million in the previous session.
</TEXT>
