<FILEID>AP-NR-01-13-89 1039EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>a f BC-TickerTalk Adv16   01-13 0584</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Ticker Talk, Adv 16,0605</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv 16</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Monday Jan 16</HEAD>
<HEAD>Year's First Stock Market Barometer Signals Fair Weather</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHET CURRIER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The first ``barometer'' of 1989 has already
flashed a positive signal for the stock market.
   In the first five sessions of the year, the Dow Jones average of
30 industrials posted a net gain of 30.89 points.
   That marks the 24th time in the past 40 years that the market
gained ground in the first trading week, according to Yale Hirsch,
an Old Tappan, N.J. investment advisor.
   On only two of those occasions, in 1966 and 1973, did the market
fail to finish the year in the plus column.
   Hirsch describes the first-week performance as an ``early
warning'' system for his popular January barometer, which is based
on the premise that ``as January goes, so goes the year'' in the
market.
   In his annual Stock Trader's Almanac, Hirsch says the direction
stock prices take in January has foreshadowed the full year's
outcome correctly all but three times since 1950.
   This time of year is a peak period for the various indicators
people have adopted to try to solve the perpetual riddle of the
market outlook.
   When the Super Bowl is played in Miami on Jan. 22, many Wall
Streeters will be rooting, at least tongue-in-cheek, for the San
Francisco 49ers to beat the Cincinnati Bengals.
   That's because the 49ers trace their origins to the National
Football League before its merger with the former American Football
League.
   In the 22 years that the Super Bowl has been played, a victory by
a team from the original NFL has always been followed by an up year
for stock prices.
   Sober, right-thinking Wall Streeters try not to take the Super
Bowl indicator too seriously. It simply isn't fitting for people
with fiduciary responsibilities to be associating themselves with
anything so patently frivolous.
   Still, the Super Bowl indicator gets a lot of attention, if only
as an entertaining diversion from the rigors of a demanding business.
   Hirsch argues that there is considerably more logic to the
January barometer.
   ``Several events have been squeezed into January which affect our
economy and our stock markets, and quite possibly those of many
nations of the world,'' he observes.
   Congress convenes, the president presents his budget and his
State of the Union message, and ``national goals and priorities''
are set.
   ``Switch these events to any other month and chances are the
January barometer would become a memory,'' he concludes.
   That case fails to sway some skeptics, however, who question the
utility if not the validity of the January barometer.
   In 1987, for example, the market rose 13.2 percent in January.
Thanks to the crash that fall, stocks finished the year with a gain
of just 2 percent.
   So while the barometer's performance that year was technically a
correct call, prices actually were lower at yearend than they had
been 11 months earlier.
   If you had tried to act on the January barometer as soon as its
signal was known, in other words, chances are you would have lost
money.
   Even worse yet, from the viewpoint of many professional money
managers, the January barometer failed to alert investors in 1982 to
the impending start of a mighty bull market.
   Stocks fell 1.8 percent in January of that year. With an upsurge
that started in August, they closed out the year with a net gain of
14.8 percent.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Monday Jan 16</NOTE>
</DOC>
