<FIRST>r f BC-Japan-NTT     01-13 0268</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Japan-NTT,0278</SECOND>
<HEAD>NTT To Release Traffic Information To Boost Fair Competition</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TETSUO JIMBO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Japan's dominant phone company, under pressure from
the government, said Friday it would disclose market information
that would help its new long-distance competitors plan their
strategies.
   Nippon Telegraph and Telephone Corp. said it would reveal facts
such as the number of calls made between administrative districts
and the revenue from each district, as well as the number of phone
subscribers in each city.
   The utility, long owned by the government, was privatized in
1985, and its telecommunications monopoly ended at the same time,
but it held key traffic information as a corporate secret despite
pressure from competitors and the Ministry of Posts and
Telecommunications.
   ``The competition is getting quite severe for us in many
different aspects, but we decided to disclose some of information we
have to accommodate the needs of new common cariers,'' NTT President
Haruo Yamaguchi said at a news conference.
   NTT is the world's largest company in terms of its stock market
valuation.
   The company has been disclosing the total number of subscribers
nationwide, and the total number of calls made annually, but it
withheld other details.
   Three companies, Teleway Japan, DDI and Japan Telecom, have
started long-distance telephone services since 1986 in the 320-mile
corridor between Japan's two biggest cities, Tokyo and Osaka.
   NTT is reportedly losing its long-distance share to the three new
common carriers. The Tokyo-Osaka corridor covers more than 70
percent of Japan's 120 million population, and the new companies are
offering long-distance rates about 20 percent lower than NTT.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
