<FIRST>u f PM-BoardofTrade Open   01-13 0334</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Board of Trade, Open,0346</SECOND>
<HEAD>Crop Futures Open Higher On Soviet Wheat Talk, Argentine Dryness</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grain and soybean futures prices opened mostly
higher today on the Chicago Board of Trade amid reports of a Soviet
bid for U.S. wheat and drought damage to Argentina's soybean crop.
   The Soviet Union was said to be bidding for more of the wheat it
has been offered at prices subsidized by the U.S. government,
analysts said.
   An Argentine government report showing the first signs of damage
to that country's soybean crop gave the soybean market a boost,
analysts said.
   ``Argentina is extremely hot and dry,'' said Jon Horton, a
grain-market analyst with Research Department Inc. in Chicago.
   Trading activity was fairly subdued with many traders taking to
the sidelines ahead of this afternoon's Agriculture Department crop
report.
   The report, scheduled for release after the close of trading,
will contain final 1988 crop production figures, a hotly anticipated
tally of winter wheat plantings, new estimates of the U.S. grain
stockpiles and predictions for 1989 soybean and corn plantings.
   In early trading, wheat was \ cent to 2{ cents higher with the
contract for delivery in March at $4.43 a bushel; corn was } cent to
1\ cents higher with March at $2.87\ a bushel; oats were 1{ cents to
2\ cents higher with March at $2.40 a bushel; soybeans were } cent
to 3{ cents higher with January at $8.01 a bushel.
   Livestock and meat futures were mostly higher in early trading on
the Chicago Mercantile Exchange.
   Live cattle were .15 cent to .23 cent higher with February at
74.25 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .05 cent lower to .08 cent
higher with January at 85 cents a pound; live hogs were .17 cent
lower to .13 cent higher with February at 45.60 cents a pound;
frozen pork bellies were .20 cent to .35 cent higher with February
at 43.05 cents a pound.
   Cattle futures closed higher on Thursday while pork futures were
mixed.
</TEXT>
