<FIRST>u f PM-Bonds     01-13 0405</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Bonds,0420</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bond Prices Up</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Bond prices rose in early trading today, boosted
by a government report showing lower-than-expected December retail
sales and by a stronger dollar.
   The Treasury's benchmark 30-year bond rose 13-16 point, or about
$8.12 per $1,000 in face value. Its yield, which moves in the
opposite direction from its price, fell to 8.89 percent from 8.97
percent late Thursday.
   Retail sales were up 0.2 percent in December, less than the
increase many analysts and economists had expected. The figure
indicated that inflationary pressures may not be as great as
believed; fear of inflation can lead to lower bond prices as
investors flee the fixed-income market.
   The dollar also was up today in foreign-exchange trading despite
reported sales of the U.S. currency by central banks, providing
further confidence for the bond market, analysts said.
   Another economic report released today, the December wholesale
price index, was in line with the figure many experts expected, up
0.4 percent.
   In the secondary market for Treasury bonds, prices of short-term
government issues rose from [ point to 7-16 point, intermediate
maturities were up 9-16 point and long-term issues were up from }
point to 27-32 point, according to Telerate Inc., a financial
information service.
   The movement of a point is equivalent to a change of $10 in the
price of a bond with a $1,000 face value.
   The Shearson Lehman Hutton Daily Treasury Bond Index, which
measures price movements on all outstanding Treasury issues with
maturities of a year or longer, rose 4.63 to 1,136.30.
   In corporate trading, industrials were up. Moody's Investment
Grade Corporate Bond Index, which measures price movements on 80
corporate bonds with maturities of five years or longer, rose 0.57
to 295.81.
   Yields on three-month Treasury bills fell to 8.50 percent as the
discount fell 5 basis points to 8.22 percent. Yields on six-month
bills fell to 8.82 percent as the discount fell 5 basis points to
8.34 percent. Yields on one-year bills fell to 9.00 percent as the
discount fell 5 basis points to 8.33 percent.
   A basis point is one-hundredth of a percentage point. The yield
is the annualized return on an investment in a Treasury bill. The
discount is the percentage that bills are selling below the face
value, which is paid at maturity.
   The federal funds rate, the interest on overnight loans between
banks, was quoted at 91-16 percent, unchanged from late Thursday.
</TEXT>
