<FIRST>r f AM-DumpingonDelta Bjt   01-13 0666</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Dumping on Delta, Bjt,0685</SECOND>
<HEAD>Former Delta Air Lines Exec's Book Blasts Company</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN A. BOLT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Delta Air Lines Inc.'s carefully nurtured image of
a family-style company where life is lovely and finances are fine is
a smoke screen hiding serious flaws, says a former company
executive's new book.
   ``I have written this book to say that the `emperor has no
clothes,' to expunge the illusion that Delta is OK,'' Sidney F.
Davis says in explaining the reasoning behind ``Delta Air Lines:
Debunking The Myth.''
   ``Fact is Delta is not OK. Fact is Delta no longer deserves the
reputation that it is financially impregnable and can endure and
prosper in the worst of times.
   ``Fact is Delta is in need of strong medicine if it is to survive
over the long term,'' writes Davis, a former vice president and
assistant general counsel, who quit in 1979 after 13 years at the
airline and now serves as general counsel for an airplane leasing
company in Atlanta.
   Industry analysts, however, see little to concern them at the
Atlanta-based carrier, which generally enjoys a strong reputation on
Wall Street and among the traveling public.
   ``No, I can't confess to be to worried about Delta,'' said Robert
Decker, an analyst with Duff &amp; Phelps Inc. in Chicago, an opinion
echoed by Gail Scully at Argus Research in New York.
   The book ``offers nothing constructive,'' said Delta spokesman
Bill Berry, who gave it his own title: ``Sour Grapes by Sid Davis.''
   ``I can see nothing to the current criticisms,'' Berry said. ``I
find his book laughable. It is so out of tune with what the industry
is today and what Delta is and his opinions just are laughable. They
just don't fit today.''
   Davis said he left Delta in 1979 to become general counsel of
Springs Industries Inc. After nine years at the textile company, he
returned to Atlanta to establish a consulting business which was
bought by his current employer, Intercredit Corp.
   He says high salaries, lack of marketing expertise, a sub-par
computer reservations system and failure to deal with airline
deregulation have made Delta a company ``living on borrowed time.''
   ``We're stable; we're financially healthy; we're growing,'' Berry
said. ``We're not setting the world on fire, but we're doing it the
Delta way.
   ``The company has always been ultraconservative.''
   Davis offers a litany of problems at Delta: complaints that Chief
Executive Officer Ron Allen has no grasp of marketing and is ``the
wrong man at the wrong time;'' accusations that Delta's budget
process is non-existent; claims the airline has prospered by ``dumb
luck;'' and suggestions its hiring-from-within process has perverted
the company.
   He says the company has a ``siege mentality'' about criticism,
and has no planning process.
   Among Davis' solutions are for the company to more aggressively
hire non-Delta employees, totally restructure its marketing
department, get rid of its no-layoff policy and ``demonstrate
financial stewardship.''
   Davis doesn't expect his recommendations to be heard. ``The very
problems I name and the solutions I pose will by my naming and
proposing be immediately ruled out of any serious consideration of
how to resolve Delta's predicament,'' he writes.
   The book, which arrived in Atlanta stores last week, has been
greeted with a demand unusual for a business-oriented book,
according to sales people at some local bookstores.
   ``It's moving more quickly than even we imagined,'' said Cindy
Gelb, spokeswoman for Peachtree Publishers Ltd., which printed
15,000 of the books initially.
   Berry admits to keeping up with sales, but he says there has been
little response coming to the airline.
   Berry said just-released figures show ``Delta for the 15th
consecutive year got the lowest number of consumer complaints of the
major airlines. Our passengers like us; if nobody else, our
passengers like us.''
   Last week, Delta, the nation's third largest airline, reported an
11.3 percent increase in revenue passenger miles in 1988 and said
the actual number of passengers rose 7.1 percent to almost 60
million.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
