<FIRST>u f BC-AutoSales     01-13 0476</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Auto Sales,0489</SECOND>
<HEAD>Car, Truck Sales Up; GM Cars Way Down</HEAD>
<HEAD>With BC-Auto Sales-Table</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: AMs planned.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FREDERICK STANDISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Big Three U.S. automakers got 1989 off on an
upbeat note, selling 3.7 percent more U.S.-built cars and light
trucks in early January than they did during the same period last
year, the companies said Friday.
   A 20.4 percent gain in light truck sales by General Motors Corp.,
Ford Motor Co. and Chrysler Corp. was diluted by a 5.5 percent
decrease in car sales overall, prompted by a 19.8 percent decline in
sales of GM cars.
   Ford and Chrysler showed increases of 13 percent and 11.4
percent, respectively, in car sales.
   The Big Three said they sold cars and light trucks at a daily
rate of 24,393 during the Jan. 1-10 period this year, compared with
a rate of 23,534 during the same time last year.
   There were seven selling days in both periods.
   GM, Ford and Chrysler said light trucks, including small pickups,
minivans and sport-utility vehicles, were bought at a daily rate of
10,021 in early January this year, compared with a daily rate of
8,324 during the same time last year.
   On the car side, the Big Three reported early January sales at a
rate of 14,372 in 1989, compared with 15,210 cars a day during the
same period of 1988.
   Automakers had ambitious production schedules through the
fourth-quarter of last year, indicating confidence in the early 1989
sales market. Incentives continued to be a factor and a new round of
incentives appears near.
   On Wednesday, the day after the early-January sales period ended,
Ford returned to cut-rate financing as an option to cash-back
financing. GM and Chrysler did not follow suit in the
low-interest-rate game by noon Friday.
   GM, the only member of the Big Three to show fewer car sales this
year than in the first reporting period of 1988, said it sold cars
at a daily rate of 6,801 during early January this year, compared
with an 8,481 daily rate during the same time last year.
   GM's truck sales rose 6.3 percent to a daily rate of 3,968 this
year, compared with a 3,732 rate last year.
   Chrysler's light truck sales showed a 46.9 percent increase in
early January, climbing to a daily rate of 2,347 in 1989 from 1,598
during the period last year. Chrysler-made cars sold at a rate of
2,225 a day in early January this year, up 11.4 percent from the
13,985 daily rate of a year before.
   Ford said it sold trucks at a daily rate of 3,706 in early
January, 23.8 percent more than the 2,993 early-January rate last
year. Car sales at Ford rose 13 percent, to a daily rate of 5,346 in
early January this year from a 4,731 during the period last year.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
