<DOCNO> AP890113-0261 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-01-13-89 1521EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-Texaco-Canada     01-13 0269</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Texaco-Canada,0279</SECOND>
<HEAD>Texaco's New Canadian Subsidiary Names President</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Texaco Inc.'s newly formed Canadian subsidiary,
Texaco Canada Petroleum Inc., said Friday it has named a new
president and chief executive officer.
   The appointment of Phillip J. Cram, a native of Reading, England,
is effective immediately, the company said.
   Texaco Canada Petroleum was formed last September to continue
Texaco Canada Inc.'s interest in production and exploration in
Brazil, West Africa and Canada after that company is sold.
   The new company's assets in Brazil, Mauritania and 11
Canadian-producing properties have been valued at $92 million
(Canadian dollars). In addition, it has cash and marketable
securities worth an estimated $65 million.
   Texaco, based in White Plains, N.Y., announced last year that it
was selling its 78 percent interest in Toronto-based Texaco Canada
as part of a restructuring to raise some $5 billion after emerging
from bankruptcy last April.
   Shareholders in Texaco Canada will receive a special dividend of
one share of Texaco Canada Petroleum for each outstanding share of
Texaco Canada. The stock will begin trading on the Toronto Stock
Exchange in approximately six weeks, Texaco spokesman Hart S. Searle
said.
   Analysts speculated recently that final bids for Texaco Canada
were received on Monday and that the unit could fetch in the range
of $4 billion. The sale of Texaco Canada represents one of the final
steps in Texaco's massive restructuring plan.
   Cram, a research chemist and 15-year veteran of Texaco, has
served in various capacities in the United States, Canada and the
Middle and Far East. He will be based at Texaco Canada Petroleum's
headquarters in Calgary.
</TEXT>
