<TEXT>
   The stock market headed higher today, continuing
its early-1989 rally after a pause for some early selling.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials, which had climbed 15.89
points Thursday, rose another 6.61 to 2,228.93 by 2 p.m. today on
Wall Street.
   Gainers outnumbered losers by about 5 to 4 in nationwide trading
of New York Stock Exchange-listed issues, with 754 up, 608 down and
541 unchanged.
   The Commerce Department reported that retail sales increased 0.2
percent in December, a gain much smaller than most analysts had
estimated. Stock traders seemed uncertain at first how to respond to
the news.
   In the bond market, investors reacted positively, sending
interest rates lower on the report's suggestion that economic
activity was a bit less robust than had been thought.
   But the dollar declined in foreign exchange after the figures
were made public.
   Brokers said blue-chip stocks also were faced with some selling
to cash in on the gains that have recently carried the market to its
highest levels since the October 1987 crash.
   Among actively traded blue chips, USX gained ] to 31]; Merck ~ to
60}; International Business Machines { to 123|; General Motors } to
88], and American Telephone &amp; Telegraph [ to 29\.
