<FIRST>r f BC-HollyFarms     01-13 0190</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Holly Farms,0196</SECOND>
<HEAD>Date Set For Auction of Chicken Company</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MEMPHIS, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Holly Farms Corp. has given suitors of the
chicken company until next Wednesday to submit their offers for a
takeover auction, one of the prospective bidders said Friday.
   ``We have teams now touring all of the (Holly Farms) facilities.
Until that information is put together, we're standing on our
present bid,'' said Bob Justice, a spokesman for Tyson Foods Inc.,
which has been trying to take over Holly Farms since October and is
offering $60 a share or about $1.2 billion.
   Ted Bailey, a Holly Farms vice president designated as the
spokesman on the possible takeover, was in a meeting and unavailable
for comment, a company receptionist said.
   Holly Farms, a diversified company heavily involved in fresh
poultry sales, has resisted Tyson's advances and is trying to merge
with ConAgra Inc. of Omaha, Neb., but decided earlier this month to
hold an auction after Tyson sweetened its bid.
   Tyson, headquartered in Springdale, Ark., is the nation's largest
poultry processor. ConAgra has offered a stock swap for Holly Farms
that is valued at about $1 billion.
