<HEAD>Coca-Cola, Singer George Michael Team Up</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pop music star George Michael has begun work on a
video project that may result in a commercial for diet Coke,
Coca-Cola USA said.
   Soft drink companies in recent years have repeatedly turned to
entertainment figures to appear in their commercials which they hope
will catch the attention of viewers of all ages and help sell their
soda pop.
   Pepsi-Cola, for instance, has featured entertainers Michael
Jackson and Lionel Ritchie in commercials. Coca-Cola has employed
singers Whitney Houston, the Pointer Sisters and the Manhattan
Transfer in its advertising.
   The agreement disclosed Thursday calls for the singer and the
soft drink company to collaborate in both the development and
production of the project, Coke officials said Thursday.
   ``We're mutually developing some concepts which may or may not
lead us to the altar. We'll know more by the end of next week,''
said Michael A. Beindorff, vice president for advertising and
associate director of marketing for Coca-Cola USA.
   Michael, whose ``Faith'' album was one of 1988's biggest sellers,
filmed portions of the potential ad Thursday at Madison Square
Garden in New York with British filmmaker Stephen Frears.
   The first spot, if approved by both Michael and Coca-Cola USA, is
tentatively scheduled to be broadcast during the Super Bowl Jan. 22.
