<FIRST>u f BC-BoardofTrade Close   01-13 0350</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Board of Trade, Close,0362</SECOND>
<HEAD>Grain, Soybean Futures Close On High Note</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grain and soybean futures prices closed mostly
higher Friday on the Chicago Board of Trade in subdued activity
ahead of the Agriculture Department's eagerly awaited first crop
report of the new year.
   Soybean futures posted the strongest gains on rumors the Soviet
Union was in the market for U.S. soybean meal. But overall, ``today
was really a dull day,'' said Victor Lespinasse, a trader with Dean
Witter Reynolds Inc. in New York.
   The crop report, which was released at 3 p.m. EST in Washington,
contained the government's final 1988 crop production figures, a
hotly anticipated tally of 1989 winter-wheat seedings, and estimates
of U.S. grain stockpiles.
   The winter-wheat seedings figure came in at 54.46 million acres,
well below the average pre-report estimate of 57.59 million acres
and 12 percent above the 1988 seeding figure.
   Analysts called the number bullish for the wheat futures market.
   The USDA said 1988 soybean production totaled 1.54 billion
bushels, 19.8 percent below the 1987 harvest but higher than most
pre-report estimates and higher than the USDA's Nov. 9 projection of
1.51 billion bushels. Analysts called the number bearish for soybean
futures.
   The USDA said 1988 corn production totaled 4.92 billion bushels,
30.3 percent below the 1987 harvest but higher than most pre-report
estimates and higher than the USDA's Nov. 9 projection of 4.67
billion bushels. Analysts termed the number bearish for corn futures.
   The USDA pegged soybean stocks as of Dec. 1 at 1.37 billion
bushels, corn stocks at 7.07 billion bushels and wheat stocks at
1.71 billion bushels.
   The USDA will project 1989 corn and soybean acreage on March 31.
   At the close of trading, wheat was 1\ cents lower to } cent
higher with the contract for delivery in March at $4.41 a bushel;
corn was 2{ cents to 3 cents higher with March at $2.88{ a bushel;
oats were 4\ cents to 5 cents higher with March at $2.43 a bushel;
soybeans were { cent to 6{ cents higher with January at $8.03{ cents
a bushel.
</TEXT>
