<FIRST>u f AM-AutoSales Bjt   01-13 0533</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Auto Sales, Bjt,0548</SECOND>
<HEAD>Sales Up Overall; GM Cars Down Substantially</HEAD>
<HEAD>With BC-Auto Sales-Table</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FREDERICK STANDISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S.-made car and truck sales rose 5.6 percent
during early January this year compared with the same period last
year, despite a 19.8 percent decline in car sales at General Motors
Corp., automakers said Friday.
   The drop at GM may have been due to dealers moving some sales
from early January to late December to inflate year-end numbers,
analysts speculated. Strong truck sales helped bolster sagging
automobile sales industrywide.
   The seven U.S. automakers said they sold cars and light trucks on
a daily rate of 25,622 vehicles during the Jan. 1-10 period this
year. During the same period last year, they sold cars and trucks at
a daily rate of 24,252.
   There were seven selling days in both periods.
   GM was the only U.S. maker to show a decline during the period,
as its car sales skidded 19.8 percent, to a daily rate of 6,801 in
early January this year compared with a rate of 8,481 during the
same time last year.
   ``I think you're just seeing a payback from the end of
December,'' said analyst Charles Brady of Oppenheimer &amp; Co. of New
York. ``A few of the dealers probably called a few of the Jan. 3-4
sales Dec. 31 sales (to boost year-end figures).''
   David Healy of Drexel Burnham Lambert Inc. of New York agreed,
saying: ``Their sales were unbelievably good in late December and
unbelievably bad in early January. If you add the two periods
together and divide by two, things are about normal.
   ``There was a lot of year-end window dressing in late December,''
Healy added.
   During the final 10-day period of December, GM reported a daily
sales rate of 14,657 cars a day, more than twice the early January
rate.
   Overall, U.S. automakers said they sold cars at a daily rate of
15,283 during the first 10 days of the year, a 3.1 percent decline
from a daily rate of 15,765 during the same time last year.
   Car sales for Ford Motor Co. and Chrysler Corp. rose during early
January, 13 percent and 11.4 percent, respectively.
   Light truck sales among all the makers rose 21.8 percent to a
daily rate of 10,339 during early January this year compared with a
rate of 8,488 last year.
   Chrysler's light truck sales showed a 46.9 percent increase in
early January, climbing to a daily rate of 2,347 in 1989 from 1,598
during the period last year. Chrysler-made cars sold at a rate of
2,225 a day in early January this year, up from 1,998 daily rate of
a year before.
   Ford said it sold trucks at a daily rate of 3,706 in early
January, 23.8 percent more than the 2,993 early-January rate last
year. Car sales at Ford rose to a daily rate of 5,346 in early
January this year from a rate of 4,731 during the period last year.
   While its car sales rate fell, GM's truck sales rose, going up
6.3 percent to a daily rate of 3,968 in early January of this year
from a 3,732 truck-per-day rate during the same time last year.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
