<FIRST>u f AM-CommodityRdp     01-13 0874</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Commodity Rdp,0902</SECOND>
<HEAD>Copper Futures Advance On Chilean Refinery Blast</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID DISHNEAU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Copper futures prices rose sharply Friday on New York's Commodity
Exchange in reaction to reports of a disastrous explosion at the
smelting operations of the world's largest copper mine near
Chuquicamata, Chile.
   On other markets, gold and silver futures retreated; coffee
futures fell; grains and soybeans were mostly higher; energy,
livestock and meat futures were mixed; and stock-index futures
advanced.
   Copper settled 4.3 cents to 5.2 cents higher with the contract
for delivery in March at $1.431 a pound. The Commodity Exchange's
spot copper price settled at the day's high of $1.536 a pound.
   The explosion of the flash furnace feeding Chilean Copper Corp.'s
Chuquicamata smelter was reported to have killed at least 16 people
and could result in significant production losses, putting further
strain on extremely tight copper supplies, analysts said.
   ``The question of how much production loss will occur is not
clear at all (but) any losses are very bullish because the market is
so tight,'' said Bette Raptopoulos, a metal-market analyst with
Prudential-Bache Securities Inc. in New York.
   Production problems have plagued the worldwide copper industry in
the past year, helping to drive the Commodity Exchange's spot-month
price to a record high of $1.6475 a pound on Dec. 8.
   A loss of production from Chuquicamata ``is not going to be a big
supply problem in times to come but it will have an immediate
short-term impact'' on prices, said analyst James Steel of Refco
Inc. in New York.
   Gold and silver futures prices fell moderately on the Commodity
Exchange, reflecting gains in the dollar's value against major
foreign currencies, analysts said.
   Gold settled $2.30 to $2.40 lower with February at $403.50 a troy
ounce; silver was 2.8 cents lower across the board with March at
$5.957 a troy ounce.
   Coffee futures ended lower in a second day of volatile activity
on New York's Coffee, Sugar &amp; Cocoa Exchange. Despite the decline,
analysts said the market's bullish supply-and-demand fundamentals
remained in place.
   Coffee settled 1.38 cents to 3.01 cents lower with March at
$1.397 a pound.
   Grain and soybean futures ended mostly higher on the Chicago
Board of Trade ahead of an Agriculture Department crop report that
was released after the close of trading and is expected to boost
wheat prices, and pressure corn and soybean prices, on Monday.
   In the report, the USDA estimated 1989 winter-wheat seedings at
54.46 million acres, 12 percent above the 1988 tally but well below
analysts' pre-report estimates.
   The USDA said 1988 soybean production totaled 1.54 billion
bushels, 19.8 percent below the 1987 harvest but higher than most
pre-report estimates and higher than the agency's Nov. 9 projection
of 1.51 billion bushels.
   The government said 1988 corn production totaled 4.92 billion
bushels, 30.3 percent below the 1987 harvest but much higher than
pre-report estimates and the USDA's Nov. 9 projection of 4.67
billion bushels.
   The USDA pegged soybean stocks as of Dec. 1 at 1.37 billion
bushels, compared with 1.76 billion bushels a year earlier; corn
stocks at 7.07 billion bushels, compared with 9.77 billion bushels a
year earlier; and wheat stocks at 1.71 billion bushels, compared
with 2.51 billion bushels a year earlier. The soybean number was
slightly below expectations while the wheat and corn figures were
higher than expected.
   The winter-wheat seedings figure alone would have been ``very
bullish'' for the wheat market, said Victor Lespinasse, a trader
with Dean Witter Reynolds Inc. in Chicago.
   But he said buying enthusiasm in the wheat market on Monday
probably would be tempered by the bearish corn and and soybean
production numbers and the bearish wheat and corn stocks figures.
   The corn numbers were ``a shockingly bearish surprise,''
Lespinasse said, and could translate into opening declines of more
than 5 cents a bushel on Monday.
   Wheat settled 1{ cents lower to { cent higher with March at $4.41
a bushel; corn was 2\ cents to 3 cents higher with March at $2.88\ a
bushel; oats were 4\ cents to 5\ cents higher with March at $2.43 a
bushel; soybeans were 1\ cents to 6\ cents higher with January at
$8.03} a bushel.
   In energy futures trading on the New York Mercantile Exchange,
West Texas Intermediate crude oil settled 14 cents lower to 31 cents
higher with February at $18.48 a barrel; heating oil was .33 cent
lower to .31 cent higher with February at 52.95 cents a gallon;
unleaded gasoline was .52 cent to 1.20 cents higher with February at
49.97 cents a gallon.
   Livestock and meat futures finished narrowly mixed on the Chicago
Mercantile Exchange.
   Live cattle were .10 cent to .43 cent higher with February at
74.45 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .30 cent lower to .05 cent
higher with January at 84.90 cents a pound; live hogs were .10 cent
lower to .30 cent higher with February at 45.50 cents a pound;
frozen pork bellies were .55 cent lower to .08 cent higher with
February at 42.65 cents a pound.
   Stock-index futures advanced moderately on the Chicago Mercantile
Exchange, where the contract for March delivery of stocks
represented by the Standard &amp; Poor's 500 index settled 1.05 points
higher at 286.30. Each point is worth $500.
</TEXT>
