<FIRST>u f AM-ShearsonLoss 1stLd-Writethru f0244 01-13 0659</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Shearson Loss, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0244,0676</SECOND>
<HEAD>Shearson To Report Fourth-Quarter Loss, Restate 1988 Profit</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: ADDS closing stock price in final graf; No pickup</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BART ZIEGLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Shearson Lehman Hutton Inc., Wall Street's
largest firm, said Friday it would report a loss for the fourth
quarter of 1988 due to bad investments in a troubled Texas bank.
   The company also said it would revise downward its profit for the
rest of 1988 because of previously reported accounting problems at
The Boston Co., a subsidiary that caters to wealthy clients.
   Shearson did not estimate the amount of quarterly loss from
devalued securities in MCorp of Dallas, but said it would release
fourth-quarter figures later this month. One stock analyst put the
loss at $15 million to $16 million.
   With capital exceeding $4.5 billion, 40,000 employees and more
than 700 offices worldwide, Shearson i the largest U.S. investment
firm. About 61 percent of it is owned by American Express Co., the
financial services giant.
   Shearson said it will record a pretax charge of $70 million in
the fourth quarter ended Dec. 30 to reflect a further reduction in
the value of MCorp securities. Shearson initially lowered the value
of the holdings in early 1988.
   To correct an overstatement in Boston Co. earnings, Shearson said
it would restate profit for the first three quarters of 1988 that
will lower Shearson's earnings for that period by $30 million, to
about $110 million.
   Shearson spokesman Michael O'Neill said the problem at The Boston
Co. stemmed from recording revenues that should have been deferred,
and deferring expenses that should have been recorded.
   He said an unidentified employee disclosed the problem and there
was no misuse of company or client assets.
   Last month, Shearson estimated the restatement would result in a
$15 million profit reduction. It also said three top Boston Co.
officers were suspended with pay over the improper accounting.
   Thomas Schick, another Shearson spokesman, said a committee of
outside auditors and Shearson officers is expected to determine who
was responsible within a few weeks.
   Shearson declined to name the three suspended officers. They have
been identified by Boston newspapers as President James N. von
Germeten, Executive Vice President Joseph F. Murphy and Chief
Financial Officer Michael J. Walsh.
   ``The review's conclusion was that what was involved here was
accounting decisions that would boost the reported earnings,''
Schick said. ``In terms of what the motive was, I cannot possibly
speak to that. We do not believe that any laws were broken.''
   Shearson said it would have reported a fourth-quarter profit
without the devaluation of MCorp holdings.
   Alison Deans, who follows the securities industry for Kidder,
Peabody &amp; Co. Inc., estimated the profit would have been $30 million
to $35 million, or 30 to 35 cents a share. Because of the MCorp
problem, the loss should be $15 million to $16 million, she said.
   Shearson said it owns MCorp money market cumulative prefered
stock with a face value of $117.5 million, and MCorp subordinated
debt securities with a principal amount of $29 million.
   After the adjustments, the preferred stock will be valued at
$29.4 million and the debt securities at $11.6 million, Shearson
said.
   MCorp, which has requested financial assistance from the Federal
Deposit Insurance Corp., in October declared a moratorium on payment
of preferred stock dividends and principal and interest on debt.
   Ms. Dean said Shearson acquired the MCorp securities after it
agreed to underwrite them, or bring them to market, in early 1988.
There was a lack of investor interest and Shearson ending up buying
them itself.
   It was unclear whether any other brokerage firms own MCorp
securities in any significant amount. But Ms. Dean said she did not
foresee the fallout from the troubles in the banking and savings and
loan industries becoming widespread in the securities industry.
   In composite New York Stock Exchange trading, Shearson's shares
closed at $19.62{, up 87{ cents from Thursday.
</TEXT>
