<FIRST>u f AM-EconomyRdp     01-13 0351</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Economy Rdp,0359</SECOND>
<HEAD>Friday the 13th Economic News Helps Dollar, Stocks, Bonds</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   The government's Friday the 13th economic reports showing higher
inflation and a mixed picture for retail sales didn't cast any
bad-luck spells on the financial markets, where the dollar rallied,
bond prices jumped and stocks reached the highest level since the
Wall Street crash 15 months ago.
   The Labor Department said the rate of increase in wholesale
prices nearly doubled in 1988 to 4 percent, the worst pace since the
early 1980s. Although inflation remains far below the double-digit
era of last decade, many economists expressed concern.
   ``I don't like the sound of a doubling of inflation, but we have
to put 4 percent in perspective,'' said Robert Brusca, an economist
with Nikko Securities Co. International Inc. in New York ``It's not
that bad, but it's not that good either.''
   In another report released Friday, the Commerce Department said
retail sales in December rose a weak 0.2 percent, following strong
increases in October and November. But for the year, retail spending
rose 6.7 percent in 1988 to $1.61 trillion, the best performance in
four years.
   The wholesale prices report had little effect on the markets, but
some traders said the retail sales figure for December was weaker
than expected and suggested that inflationary pressure was easing,
which helped stocks and bonds.
   Others credited the strength in the markets to a relentless rise
in the dollar's value despite coordinated dollar-selling by major
central banks to stem the U.S. currency's advance. A more expensive
dollar makes investments denominated in the currency more attractive.
   In the bond market, the Treasury's benchmark 30-year bond rose
nearly $10 per $1,000 in face value, while its yield declined from
8.97 percent late Thursday to 8.88 percent, the lowest in more than
two months.
   Lower yields in the bond market encouraged investors to buy
stocks and helped the market reach another in a recent series of
post-crash highs. On Wall Street, the Dow Jones industrial average
rose 3.75 points to 2,226.07, finishing the week with a net gain of
31.78 points.
</TEXT>
