<FIRST>r f AM-PiedmontLawsuit     01-13 0237</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Piedmont Lawsuit,0246</SECOND>
<HEAD>Pilots Sue Airlines Over Seniority Dispute</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SYRACUSE, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A group of 84 former Empire Airlines pilots
now employed by Piedmont Aviation Inc. have filed a $25 million
lawsuit against the Winston-Salem, N.C.-based airline, its parent
company and the pilots' union.
   The suit will be served on Piedmont, USAir Group Inc. and the Air
Line Pilots Association next week, said Alan Peterman, a Syracuse
attorney who is representing the pilots.
   The suit claims the union arbitrarily refused to represent the
pilots' seniority interests and other employment rights in the
USAir-Piedmont merger and accuses all three organizations of
breaching contractual obligations to ensure the pilots' interests
were represented fairly, the attorney said.
   The suit was filed Thursday in U.S. District Court in Syracuse.
   In December 1987, the pilots filed a $5.2 million lawsuit against
the union and its Piedmont Master Executive Council, which is
pending.
   Both lawsuits seek to increase the pilots' seniority with
Piedmont to include time spent flying for Empire. Empire, based in
Utica, N.Y., merged with Piedmont in 1986.
   The pilots' lawsuit contends they will lose pay, advancement
opportunities and transfer ability during the decade following the
merger because of their low placement on the integrated seniority
list.
   Peterman said he expects the airlines and union to ask for the
pilots' lawsuits to be consolidated. He said the 1987 lawsuit
probably would go to a non-jury trial by year's end.
</TEXT>
